[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[Variant "illegal"]
[PlyCount "0"]
[EventDate "2020.06.09"]

{In the first part of my article I will investigate the historical development
of the ideas in the Exchange Spanish structure. This pawn structure usually
arises after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 from one of the following lines: A) 3...
a6 4.Bxc6 (Exchange Spanish) B) 3...a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.Bxc6 or 5.0-0 Be7 6 Byc6 
(delayed Exchange Spanish) C) 3...Nf6 4.Bxc6 (Anti-Berlin) Doubling the pawns
doesn't automatically trouble Black. His queenside pawn formation is compact
and without holes. For someone who is not an expert of the line, it may seem
that White achieves almost nothing in return for the exchange of his best
piece. So the question is: How does White justify such a decision, and why did
the Exchange Spanish pass the test of time? The first big deception was that
White can play for a win in the endgame, where his 4/3 majority on the
kingside will prevail over Black's bishop pair. It very quickly proved to be
unrealistic against an average level of defence. The first great champion in
history who created the image of the Exchange Spanish as a dangerous weapon
was Lasker. His 13th game from the 1894 world championship match against
Steinitz was the first real test for the value of the line. Lasker was leading
with 7-2 and only now Steinitz gave him the option to play his pet line.
Lasker played the most solid way (5.d4), with an early queen exchange, but the
result was very disappointing, as he lost without making any notable mistake 
(game 1). Black's bishop pair and the pressure on the open d-file proved to be
more than enough to balance the situation in the endgame. Between the two
matches in 1894 and 1896, Lasker adjusted the plan and decided that it is
better to avoid the endgame. In the second match against Steinitz in 1896, he
found an original way to exploit the imbalances created with the early bishop
exchange. In game 10, when he was already leading by 5-0, he had the chance to
adopt the Exchange Spanish again. It came as a great surprise for Steinitz
when Lasker castled long and smashed him with a pawn storm (game 2). Lasker
also won the last game of the match without much of a fight (game 3). Later in
1896 he used the new approach to beat Tarrasch in a very instructive endgame
after Tarrasch committed an inexplicable positional blunder by exchanging
queens on e3 (game 4). Probably at this point, Lasker drew the conclusion that
Tarrasch's weakest spot was his endgame technique. He also adopted the line
with 5.d4 one more time to easily win the first game of the long-awaited match
against Tarrasch in 1908. With rook and knight against rook and bishop, Lasker
didn't give his rival any chances, creating one more endgame masterpiece (game
4). After an amazing streak of victories between 1904 and 1910, Lasker became
the acknowledged expert of the Exchange Spanish. He crushed Chigorin in an
opposite-castling position in Cambridge-Springs in 1904 and three times
Janowski in 1909.1914 was a memorable year for the chess community. The
historical tournament in Saint Petersburg marked the recognition of the
Exchange Spanish as a tough weapon by other great players - the future world
champions Capablanca and Alekhine. The first well-known game, annotated in
many chess books and monographs, was Capablanca - Janowski. Although
Capablanca was known for his brilliant technique, he didn't enter the endgame
and improved on one of the games Lasker-Janowski from 1909. Castling short on
move 10 was a new and aggressive decision which later Capablanca proved to be
best with energetic play, creating a masterpiece for attacks with opposite
side castling (game 5). Only a few days later, Alekhine played 4.Bxc6 against
the father of the line - Lasker. The endgame was about equal for most of the
time, and even on move 32 Alekhine had some advantage, but later on he
blundered and lost. Two weeks later came the Lasker-Capablanca game, which is
the most famous game with the Spanish Exchange structure by far (game 6). In
an equal endgame, Lasker played the "anti-positional" f4-f5, which made a huge
impact on the future world champion and later became a standard technique for
handling the structure with White's pawns on d4 and e4. Later this device was
used in the middlegame by Fischer in his game against Unzicker (you can find
this game at the special section devoted to the f4-f5 idea). 1920-1930 was the
period when the Russian chess school started its rise to the top. The first
Russian (apart from Alekhine) who started playing and analysing the Spanish
Exchange was the legendary player and coach Piotr Romanovsky. He was the first
player to adopt the delayed exchange line with taking on c6 on the fifth or
even sixth move. Very soon the line came into the range of vision of the
patriarch - Michail Botvinnik. First he tried it in 1961 in a training game
against Furman and then won against Wade in Hastings 1961, but lost against
Stein in 1965 (game 8) . I am sure that he was deeply convinced the whole
approach was wrong and therefore all of his great students, Kasparov, Kramnik,
Shirov and Svidler, were sceptical about it. Ratmir Kholmov played the delayed
Spanish Exchange regularly for more than 35 years, between 1950 and 1987. His
best achievements were the victories against Beliavsky in 1982 and Vasiukov in
1987. Fischer was the next great champion who took the baton, turning the
Exchange Spanish into a formidable weapon. Fischer was famous for his endgame
technique, but he respected the bishops too much. His victories, against
Gligoric at the Havana Olympiad 1966, Unzicker at the 1970 Olympiad and
against Spassky in 1992, are well-documented in chess literature as unique
masterpieces. In the 21st century it was Rustam Kasimdzhanov who used the
Exchange Spanish at the most decisive moment in his chess career. In Tripoli
2004 he became world champion after he used it to win two decisive games: The
first rapid game in the semi-final match against Grischuk and the decisive
game of his final match against Adams. It is quite amazing that Kasimdzhanov
didn't use the Exchange Spanish before 2004 and only a couple of times after
those matches. This historical review should provide enough evidence that the
Spanish Exchange has always had great surprise and psychological value and for
this reason it survived the test of time. On the other hand, 21st century GM
practice clearly proves that if Black is well prepared, he might even get an
advantage. I devote part 2 to the endgame ideas and part 3 to the ideas of the
related pawn structures. Part 4 is devoted to positions with castling on
opposite sides while in part 6 I analyse the games where White employed the
plan with the flank attack f2-f4. Eliminating the important central pawn and
opening the f-file creates unpleasant pressure on Black's position. Top Games
from the 21st century show that the pawn structure with dxc6 can be extremely
dynamic, see the games Caruana-Anand and Aronian-Kramnik. In Part 6, I provide
a theoretical overview of the lines in which this pawn structure appears.}  *

