[Event "World-ch05 Lasker-Steinitz +10-5=4"]
[Site "NY, Philadelphia & Montreal"]
[Date "1894.05.05"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Game 1"]
[Black "Lasker - Steinitz"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "110"]
[EventDate "1894.03.15"]
[EventRounds "19"]
[EventCountry "USA"]

{Let's go back 125 years. It is the first test for the Exchange Spanish on
such a high level. Lasker is leading 7-2 and the match seemed decided for some
time. At this point, the world champion Steinitz decided to play 3...a6 for
the first time in the match and check the technique of the challenger in the
Exchange Spanish.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6.
Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 c5 {Take a look at the Games from the endgame section to get
a feel for the positions and how to play them.} 8. Ne2 Bd7 9. Nbc3 O-O-O 10.
Bf4 Bc6 $1 {Stopping White from castling long, which is already a notable
achievement for Black.} 11. O-O Nf6 12. f3 Be7 13. Ng3 g6 {The standard way to
restrict the knight, but} (13... Nd7 14. Nf5 Bf6 {would have been even better})
14. Rfe1 Nd7 15. Nd1 $6 (15. Nd5 Bxd5 16. exd5 Bf6 17. c3 Nb6) (15. Rad1 Rhe8)
15... Nb6 16. Nf1 $6 {Not very inspiring. Obviously White only has a vague
idea of how to handle this type of endgame.} Rd7 17. Be3 $6 (17. Nf2 Rhd8 18.
Ng4 f6 19. e5 $1 $11) 17... Rhd8 (17... Nc4 18. Bf2 Bf6 19. Rb1 b6 $15) 18. b3
c4 $1 {This will become a standard way of handling the position on the black
side.} (18... f5 19. exf5 Nd5 20. fxg6 Nb4 21. Re2 hxg6 $44) 19. Bxb6 $2 {
This is already the decisive mistake.} (19. Rb1) (19. Nb2 Bb4 20. Red1 Bc3 21.
Rab1 Rxd1 22. Nxd1 Bg7 23. Ng3) 19... cxb6 20. bxc4 Bb4 21. c3 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Rd3
{It was too easy for Black to establish full control of the position. Black is
now threatening f7-f5, with the idea exf5 Rxf3, and White can't take back
because of mate.} (22... f5 23. exf5 gxf5 24. Nde3 f4 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. cxd5
Rxd5) 23. Rc1 a5 (23... f5 24. exf5 Rxf3 25. fxg6 hxg6 26. Rc2 Rf4 $19) 24.
Nde3 f5 $1 25. exf5 (25. Nd5 fxe4 26. fxe4 Rf8 27. Rc2 a4 $17) 25... gxf5 26.
h3 (26. Nxf5 Rxf3 $1) 26... Rg8 (26... f4 27. Ng4 Ba3 $19) 27. Nd5 Bxd5 28.
cxd5 Rxd5 29. Rcd1 {White minimizes the damage, but still his position is
nearly lost because of the many pawn weaknesses and the passive knight on f1.}
Rxd1 30. Rxd1 f4 $1 {Total domination by Black's pieces - from this point the
game is instructive for the realisation of good bishop vs bad knight.} 31. Kh2
Re8 $1 32. a4 Kc7 33. h4 Kc6 34. c4 Bb4 35. Kh3 Re1 $1 {The elimination of the
rooks is the most simple way to victory.} 36. Rxe1 Bxe1 37. Kg4 Kc5 38. Kxf4
Kxc4 39. Ke4 (39. h5 b5) 39... Bxh4 (39... b5 $1 40. Ne3+ Kb3 41. axb5 a4 42.
Kd3 a3 43. Nc2 a2 44. h5 Bg3 $19) 40. g3 Bd8 41. Ne3+ Kb4 42. Kd3 Kxa4 43. Kc2
Kb4 44. f4 Kc5 45. f5 Kd6 46. g4 b5 47. Nd1 Ke5 48. Nc3 b4 49. Na4 Kd4 50. Nb2
b5 51. Kb3 Be7 52. g5 a4+ 53. Nxa4 bxa4+ 54. Kxa4 Ke5 55. Kb3 Kxf5 {A very
instructive game for how to handle this endgame with the black pieces.} 0-1

[Event "World-ch06 Lasker-Steinitz +10-2=5"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1896.12.11"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Game 2"]
[Black "Lasker - Steinitz"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "1896.11.07"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 Bg4 {Taking into account
what happened in the previous game, this was an important psychological moment.
Instead of entering the endgame with 5.d4, Lasker plays 5.Nc3, and after Bg4
the d4 advance is not possible anymore, which may seem like a huge achievement.
But the voluntary parting with the bishop pair gives White a long-term
advantage.} 6. h3 $1 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 $14 Ne7 8. d3 c5 $1 {This is the right way
to handle the position as Black - the knight would go to the nice outpost on
d4 and it should be enough for equality or maybe even more. But this way of
thinking is too superficial.} 9. Qg3 $1 {White is preparing to break with f4,
so Steinitz adjust his initial idea and places his knight on g6 to prevent the
opponent's plan.} Ng6 $6 (9... Nc6 10. O-O Qd7 11. f4 f6 12. Nd5 O-O-O {
would be fine.}) 10. Be3 $1 Bd6 11. O-O-O $1 {The best decision. After f4 has
been stopped for now, White's best way to create dynamic chances is to slowly
prepare it with g3. Therefore the king will be better placed on the queenside.}
O-O $6 {A brave decision. It might be wiser to prepare long castling, but this
appears difficult to achieve.} (11... Qd7 12. h4 $1 O-O-O (12... h5 13. Bg5 $1)
13. h5 Nf4 14. Qxg7 Qe6 15. Qg3 Rhg8 16. Qf3 $14) 12. h4 $1 Nf4 13. Kb1 Ne6 14.
Qg4 $1 Qe8 $1 (14... Nd4 15. h5 Kh8 16. h6 g6 17. f4 $16) 15. Ne2 Nd4 {Black
completed his initial plan to bring the knight to d4, but this is not so
relevant anymore. At this point it only helps White to speed up his actions.}
16. Nxd4 exd4 {A sad necessity.} (16... cxd4 $6 17. Bh6) 17. Bh6 $1 {The most
precise - White is winning a tempo for his attack.} Be5 18. Bc1 $1 Qe6 19. Qe2
$1 {Lasker adjusted his ideas, and now he is playing for an attack instead of
trying to win in the endgame.} f5 20. f4 Bd6 21. e5 Be7 22. h5 $1 {From this
point until the end, White didn't give his opponent any more chances. He
practically has a healthy extra pawn and it is a matter of time until the
blockade is broken down.} Rad8 23. g4 b5 24. Rdg1 c4 25. Rg2 cxd3 26. cxd3 fxg4
27. Rxg4 Rf5 28. Rhg1 Bf8 29. Rg5 $1 {Removing the blockade.} Rxg5 30. Rxg5 Rd5
31. Qf3 Rd7 32. Qe4 Rd5 33. Rg2 c6 {There is no time to hold the pawns with
Rd7-f7.} 34. Re2 $1 {It is over, as there is no defence against f4-f5.} Qg4 35.
e6 Be7 36. Rc2 $1 {A second weakness.} Qxh5 37. Rxc6 Rd8 38. Rxa6 Qe8 39. Ra7
h5 40. f5 h4 41. Qg4 1-0

[Event "World-ch06 Lasker-Steinitz +10-2=5"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1896.12.29"]
[Round "14"]
[White "Game 3"]
[Black "Lasker - Steinitz"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[EventDate "1896.11.07"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. e4 {This was the 14th and last game of the match. This game marked the end
of the long rivalry between the two giants of 19 century in favour of the
longest reigning world champion in history.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6
dxc6 5. Nc3 f6 $1 {Improving on the previous game. Steinitz understood that it
is not worth preventing d4 by exchanging the important bishop.} 6. d4 exd4 7.
Qxd4 Bd6 {Taking into account that Steinitz won the endgame easily, this is a
surprising decision. It may be that Steinitz, who was in a hopeless situation
in the match, continued to look for winning chances.} (7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 c5 9.
Nde2 Be6 10. Bf4 O-O-O {would prevent White from castling long.}) 8. Be3 Ne7 9.
Nd2 {looks like a nasty idea - the knight will go to c4 to challenge the
important bishop. But Black could have easily dissuaded this manoeuvre.} (9.
O-O-O O-O 10. Qc4+ Kh8 11. Bc5) 9... c5 $6 {It is too early for this move, as
it weakens the light squares and blocks the bishop on d6.} (9... Be6 {would be
some kind of a refutation, as} 10. Nc4 $2 Bb4 $1 {is bad for White.}) 10. Qd3
b5 $5 {Demonstrating fighting spirit!} (10... Be6 11. Nc4 Nc6 12. O-O-O $14)
11. Qe2 {With the simple trick to win a pawn with Bc5 and Qh5.} (11. a4 Bd7)
11... c4 $6 {Too hasty. It was already fine to castle.} (11... O-O 12. O-O (12.
a4 b4 13. Nd1 a5 $1) 12... Ng6 13. f4 Bb7 $132 {, with a perfect position for
Black.}) 12. Qh5+ $1 {Now Black is in trouble.} g6 (12... Ng6 13. f4 f5 14.
O-O-O Qh4 15. Qe2 $40) 13. Qh6 (13. Qf3 $1 {was the right move.} Be5 (13... O-O
14. e5) 14. Rd1 Bd7 15. O-O O-O 16. Bc5 Qe8 17. Qe3 $16 {, followed by f4.})
13... Kf7 $6 (13... Be6 $1 {was the best move - sacrificing the pawn for a
strong counterattack.} 14. Qg7 $6 Rf8 15. Qxh7 Qd7 16. O-O-O b4 17. Ne2 O-O-O)
14. f4 Qf8 15. Qh4 $1 Nc6 (15... Kg7 16. O-O h6 17. Qf2 $16) 16. Nd5 $1 $18 f5
17. Qf6+ Kg8 18. Qxf8+ Bxf8 19. Nxc7 {The rest is not significant. This game
marked the end of the era of the first world champion Steinitz.} 1-0

[Event "Nuernberg Internationales Meisterturnie"]
[Site "Nuremberg"]
[Date "1896.08.08"]
[Round "18"]
[White "Game 4"]
[Black "Lasker - Tarrasch"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "1896.07.20"]
[EventRounds "19"]
[EventCountry "GER"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 Bc5 {Instead of Bg4 and f6,
Tarrasch chose the third option, which later became the most fashionable.} 6.
d3 Bg4 7. Be3 Qd6 8. Bxc5 Qxc5 9. Qd2 {Voluntarily doubling the pawns - one of
the deep psychological decisions typical for the second world champion.} Bxf3
10. gxf3 Ne7 (10... Qd6 $1 11. Qg5 g6 12. O-O-O f6 13. Qe3 c5 14. Ne2 Ne7 15.
f4 O-O-O) 11. O-O-O (11. f4 $5) 11... Ng6 12. Qe3 {This is the most critical
moment in the game. The position should be about equal - White's doubled pawns
are compensated by his piece activity. Here Tarrasch, who is one of the
greatest strategic players of all times, took a fascinating decision.} Qxe3+ $2
{You must be under heavy psychological pressure to take such an antipositional
decision.} ({Of course after going back with} 12... Qe7 {, Black would have
some trouble with the long castle. But this should be the lesser evil.} 13. d4
(13. Kb1 b6 14. d4 O-O-O) 13... O-O $1 14. h4 Rad8 15. h5 exd4 16. Rxd4 Rxd4
17. Qxd4 Qg5+ 18. Kb1 Ne5 $13) 13. fxe3 {This was exactly what White needed -
to strengthen his pawn structure.} Rd8 14. Ne2 f6 15. Rhg1 Kf7 16. Rdf1 Rhe8
17. Ng3 Nf8 18. f4 $1 c5 $2 {Tarrasch just forgot to check the opponent's
ideas - something you should never do if you want to survive against Lasker.} (
18... g6 $1) 19. Nh5 $1 {Black has no defence.} g6 20. fxe5 $3 {This is what
Tarrasch had missed. The knight is immune.} Rxe5 (20... gxh5 21. Rxf6+ Ke7 22.
Rg7#) 21. Nxf6 $18 Kg7 22. Rf2 h5 23. Nd5 c6 24. Nf4 c4 25. Rfg2 Rd6 26. h4
cxd3 27. cxd3 Kf7 28. Rg5 Rxg5 29. Rxg5 Rf6 30. e5 Rf5 31. Rxf5+ gxf5 32. d4
Ke7 33. Kd2 c5 34. Kd3 cxd4 35. exd4 Kd8 36. d5 Kd7 37. Kd4 Kc7 38. b4 Kd7 39.
Kc5 Kc7 40. d6+ Kd7 41. Kd5 1-0

[Event "World-ch08 Lasker-Tarrasch +8-3=5"]
[Site "Duesseldorf & Munich"]
[Date "1908.08.17"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Game 5"]
[Black "Lasker - Tarrasch"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "109"]
[EventDate "1908.08.17"]
[EventRounds "16"]
[EventCountry "GER"]

1. e4 {This is the first game of the World Championship match, played 12 years
after the previous game.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 {After
the painful defeat against Steinitz, Lasker was not that convinced of White's
advantage in the endgame anymore. But seeing Tarrasch play such an
anti-positional move as 12...Qxe3?, he might have adjusted his views and is
now challenging Tarrasch one more time in the endgame. Employing psychology in
the opening like this is quite typical today, but at this time it must have
been revolutionary.} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Ne2 Bd7 9. b3 Bc6 10. f3
Be7 $6 {This exchange is antipositional, and even kids can understand which
side will profit more from it.} (10... O-O-O $11 {, as played by Steinitz,
would suffice to maintain the balance.}) (10... Bd6 11. Bf4 $1) (10... Ne7 11.
Bb2 f5 {may be the critical attempt to fight for more than equality.} 12. Nd2
fxe4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. fxe4 O-O-O 15. Rd1 Re8 16. Ng3 Nc6 17. O-O c4 $1 {
Underlining the drawback of White's b2-b3.} 18. bxc4 Bc5+ 19. Kh1 Rhg8 $15 20.
Nh5) 11. Bb2 Bf6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nd2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O {This is an equal
endgame, which was proven many times by tournament practice in the 20th and
21st century. But it is Black who has to be careful.} Rd7 (14... Nd7 15. Nf4 (
15. Nc4 Bb5 $1) 15... Ne5 16. h4 b6 17. Rhe1 (17. h5 g5 $1) 17... Kb7 18. Nf1
Rde8 19. Ne3 Ng6 $1 $11) 15. Nf4 Re8 16. Nc4 $1 b6 17. a4 $1 {The first step
is to fix the pawns on the queenside.} a5 18. Rxd7 Nxd7 19. Rd1 Ne5 20. Nxe5
Rxe5 21. c4 $1 Re8 ({Black main problem is his complete lack of active
counterplay.} 21... g5 22. Nd3 Re8 23. Kd2 g4 24. Ke2 gxf3+ 25. gxf3 Rg8 26.
Nf4) 22. Nh5 {The start of the second stage - centralising the king and
advancing the kingside pawns.} Rg8 23. Rd3 f6 24. Kd2 Be8 25. Ng3 Bd7 26. Ke3
Re8 27. Nh5 Re7 28. g4 $1 c6 29. h4 Kc7 30. g5 $6 {Too hasty.} ({It was
necessary to adjust the position of the rook - to execute the following idea.} 
30. Rd2 $1 Be8 31. Ng3 Bd7 32. g5 f5 33. f4 $1 fxe4 34. f5 $18) 30... f5 31.
Ng3 fxe4 {This is the problem - the rook is hanging on d3.} 32. Nxe4 (32. fxe4
$6 Rf7 $1 $132) 32... Bf5 $1 33. h5 (33. Kf4 Bg6) 33... Rd7 $1 {After White
committed the mistake and released Black's bishop, Black can exchange the
rooks, as White's knight has to cover the c2-square.} 34. Rc3 {White's rook
has to retreat, losing control of the d-file.} (34. Rxd7+ Kxd7 35. Kf4 Ke6 36.
h6 gxh6 37. gxh6 Bg6 $11) 34... Rd1 $1 35. Kf4 Bd7 $6 (35... Bxe4 36. Kxe4 Rh1
{should be good enough, but I suspect that here Tarrasch became ambitious and
started to play for a win.} 37. f4 Rxh5 38. Kf5 Rh4 $11) 36. Re3 Rh1 (36... Bc8
37. g6 $1 h6 38. Ng3 Rd4+ (38... Kd6 39. Re8) 39. Ke5 Rd1 40. Re4 $18) 37. Ng3
Rh4+ 38. Ke5 Rh3 39. f4 $18 {The fate of the game is decided - the last stage
is the effective realization of the pawn majority.} Kd8 (39... Bg4 40. f5 Bxh5
41. Ke6 $18) 40. f5 Rh4 41. f6 gxf6+ 42. Kxf6 Be8 43. Nf5 Rf4 44. g6 hxg6 45.
hxg6 Rg4 46. Rxe8+ Kxe8 47. g7 Kd7 48. Nh4 Rxg7 49. Kxg7 Ke6 50. Nf3 Kf5 51.
Kf7 Ke4 52. Ke6 Kd3 53. Kd6 Kc3 54. Kxc6 Kxb3 55. Kb5 {This was the first and
the last time Lasker played the Exchange Spanish in the match.} 1-0

[Event "St Petersburg International Preliminary"]
[Site "St Petersburg"]
[Date "1914.05.03"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Game 6"]
[Black "Capablanca - Janowski"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "61"]
[EventDate "1914.04.21"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

{21st century players will probably underestimate the importance of this game.
Capablanca hasn't yet reached his peak in 1914, but nevertheless shows that he
was far ahead in modern understanding of the game compared to his
contemporaries. But before analysing the game, we have to take into account
that one year before, in 1913, there was a game between the same opponents at
the American national tournament in New York, which Capablanca also won
convincingly. It was also the Spanish Exchange variation and it was again a
position with opposite side castling, which after many exchanges transposed to
an endgame decided in favour of the Cuban, who showed extremely good technique.
You can find this game in the endgame section - part 2.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 {With this move Lasker won two games against
Steinitz in 1894 and 1896 (games 2 & 3). It was time now for Capablanca to
reveal his opening preparation.} Bc5 (5... f6 $1 {was played by Steinitz in
game 3, and this is still considered as Black's best defence nowadays.}) 6. d3
Bg4 7. Be3 $1 {Objectively every exchange is in White favour in this structure,
and it also favours the Cuban, who is known for his mastery in simple
positions, while Janowski is an acknowledged master of attack.} Bxe3 (7... Qe7
$1 {should be played, but Janowski always took on e3, although he was defeated
in most of those games.}) 8. fxe3 Qe7 9. O-O $5 {This is the new idea prepared
by Capablanca. It is a logical improvement over the game Lasker,E-Janowski,D,
Paris 1909 HCL, where both sides have castled long.} (9. Qe2 Nh6 10. O-O-O
O-O-O 11. h3 Bh5 12. d4 exd4 13. exd4 {Entering structure #2, which I analyse
in part 3. In the game, Black was more than fine after the simple} f6 14. Rhe1
Rhe8 $132) 9... O-O-O $1 {This is what Janowski was looking for, a
double-edged fight instead of trying to survive in a slightly worse endgame 
(which wasn't successful one year ago - in 1913).} (9... Nf6 10. Qe1 O-O 11.
Qg3 Bxf3 12. Rxf3 Ne8 {It looks like White has all the play here, but Janowski
is well-known to be a strong tactical player, so he predictably castles long,
striving for a double-edged position.}) 10. Qe1 ({The immediate} 10. Rb1 {
was also possible.}) 10... Nh6 11. Rb1 $1 f6 12. b4 {The fight has already
started. White's plan is very simple: To open files with a4, b5. With two pawn
levers on a6 and c6, Black can't avoid the opening of the files on the
queenside. Therefore he has to start defending, which is the first small
victory for White.} Nf7 13. a4 Bxf3 $1 {The bishop is not participating,
neither in the attack nor in the defence, so he decides to exchange it for a
potential attacking unit (Nd2-c4).} 14. Rxf3 b6 $6 (14... Nd6 $5 {, and White
has to spend some time to prepare b5, as the immediate} 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5
Nxb5 17. Nxb5 cxb5 18. Rxb5 b6 {brings no results for White.}) 15. b5 $1 cxb5
16. axb5 a5 {Raising the barrier on the dark squares, but Black's defence will
fall with a domino effect.} 17. Nd5 Qc5 18. c4 $1 Ng5 19. Rf2 Ne6 20. Qc3 {
Black has no defence against the advance of the pawns d3-d4 and c4-c5.} Rd7 21.
Rd1 $1 $18 {The fate of Black's defence is already decided at this point. The
conclusion is that Black can't survive the attack without active counterplay
on the other wing.} Kb7 22. d4 Qd6 23. Rc2 exd4 24. exd4 Nf4 25. c5 Nxd5 26.
exd5 Qxd5 27. c6+ Kb8 28. cxd7 Qxd7 29. d5 Re8 30. d6 cxd6 31. Qc6 {Perfect
execution, there was practically no chance for the opponent. One of
Capablanca's most famous games.} 1-0

[Event "St Petersburg International Final"]
[Site "St Petersburg"]
[Date "1914.05.18"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Game 7"]
[Black "Lasker - Capablanca"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "83"]
[EventDate "1914.05.10"]
[EventRounds "10"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

{Lasker's choice to play 5.d4 against a great endgame expert like Capablanca
may seem strange, and it would hardly make sense without a concrete idea in
mind: To play f2-f4 and later f4-f5. The idea was probably borrowed from
Alekhine, who utilized it successfully in the same tournament. But this is how
chess was developing in the first half of the 20th century. Now, let's take a
look at this memorable game. No story about Lasker's chess career is complete
without it. The young Cuban genius, Capablanca, was playing easily and
convincingly in this tournament, probably the strongest ever held until that
time. Lasker, as usual, began quite slowly and, with just four rounds to go,
he was trailing a full point behind Capablanca, whom he was desperately trying
to catch. His last chance to fight for tournament victory was to beat the
leader. (G. Kasparov)} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {(!) A very
surprising choice. The Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez was a dangerous
weapon in Lasker's hands. But nobody in the audience and amongst the
participants believed that this quiet opening would work against Capablanca,
whose excellent technique was already widely recognised. With the charming
self-confidence of youth, Jose Raoul unfortunately shared this misconception
and did not recognise Lasker's real intentions. (Garry Kasparov). This is only
partially true, as the real surprise is not 4.Bxc6 but 5.d4. More concretely,
the novel idea was the treatment of the endgame with a quick f2-f4.} dxc6 5. d4
{If we count only serious games - world championships and international
tournaments, Lasker played like this only five times in his chess career. From
these five games he lost one, in 1894 against Steinitz, and won 3 - against
Tarrasch (game 5) and two times against Janowski. Invariably he played f2-f3
and in all those games he got either worse or equal endgames. The reason he
chooses the line one more time and also at such a decisive moment was exactly
the idea that he learned from his game against Alekhine: The quick f2-f4-f5.
This approach - to take the other players' ideas from the same tournaments and
immediately adopt them against the next opponents, was used by many strong
players - one of them who mastered this at a very high level is the great
Anand.} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. O-O $1 {This move passed
unnoticed by Garry Kasparov in his comment. Castling short in this position
might have been a revolutionary approach at this time. Usually White's king
stayed in the centre or castled long. The idea of this move probably came to
Lasker because in his game against Alekhine, White had trouble defending the
g2 pawn, so Lasker now defends it immediately.} O-O 10. f4 $1 {This move marks
the start of a plan which was completely new at this time - 1914. Instead of
fighting for the d-file and looking for exchanges, White immediately advances
his pawn majority. This is definitely the more demanding and risky plan, but
the main point is that it was still unknown and also the defence against it
was very difficult to find, even for the greatest endgame expert of his time.
This was actually the main reason for his uncertainty and instability with
which he played the rest of the game. Who dares wins! By adopting this new
approach, Lasker gave the world an unforgettable masterpiece, which now, more
than 100 years later, is still an example of the realisation of space
advantage in the endgame.} Re8 ({Of course for us, players from the 21st
century, it looks obvious to find the blockading idea} 10... f5 11. e5 Bc5 12.
Be3 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 b6 {, when despite the passed pawn only Black can be better.}
) 11. Nb3 {Removing the hanging knight and taking the c5-square under control
- exactly what Alekhine did in his game.} f6 {Of course only Black can be
better here according to modern endgame understanding.} (11... Ng6 {is also
good.}) 12. f5 $1 {Under the classical rules of the Steinitz positional school,
this move has to be damned. White gets a weak pawn on e4, Black a stronghold
on e5, with a devaluation of White's pawn advantage on the kingside - too many
negative points for just one move. But Lasker's eagle eye had seen much
further. (G.K) This move is a strong psychological weapon. Black's pieces are
severely restricted - the knight on e7 has no future and the Bc8 needs to find
a better diagonal. But its abovementioned disadvantages are also quite real.
You may play hundreds of games even against much weaker opponents and possibly
never make the plan work which Lasker convincingly realised in this game. But
Capablanca was under psychological pressure to find a concrete response. Being
under pressure, even strong players make such errors - they just lose their
confidence and start exaggerating their opponents' ideas, adopting passive
approaches and committing unbelievable positional mistakes, which under normal
circumstances they would never do. To embarrass the opponent by creating a
psychologically unpleasant situation became a trademark for many world
champions and strong players like Tal, Kortschnoj, Kasparov Kramnik, and
Topalov.} b6 {And here} 13. Bf4 Bb7 $2 {This was the first error, which passed
the advantage to White. There was no need to create a weakness on d6. After
the obvious} (13... Bxf4 $1 14. Rxf4 c5 $1 15. Rd1 Bb7 16. Rf2 Rad8 17. Rfd2 (
17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Rd2 Rxd2 19. Nxd2 Nc6) {or} 17... Rxd2 18. Rxd2 Nc6 19. Rd7
Rc8 {, and after Ne5 Black is fine. This plan was later recommended by
Capablanca.}) 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nd4 Rad8 $2 {Capablanca doesn't take White's
plan serious. The knight on e6 will be a bone in his throat, so 15...Bc8 was
obligatory. (GK) But here to play Bc8 is somewhat inhuman.} 16. Ne6 Rd7 17.
Rad1 Nc8 18. Rf2 b5 19. Rfd2 Rde7 20. b4 $1 {This was the only move to defend
against Black's plan to release the pressure by b5-b4, Nb6 and d6-d5.} Kf7 21.
a3 Ba8 $2 (21... Rxe6 22. fxe6+ Rxe6 {would have given him the best fighting
chances.}) 22. Kf2 Ra7 23. g4 $1 {After installing the knight on e6, White is
trying to create a weakness on the kingside in order to activate his rooks} h6
24. Rd3 a5 $2 25. h4 axb4 26. axb4 Rae7 27. Kf3 Rg8 28. Kf4 g6 29. Rg3 (29. g5
hxg5+ 30. hxg5 $18) 29... g5+ {It's too late for good advice.} (29... gxf5 {
doesn't offer any relief:} 30. exf5 d5 31. g5 $1 hxg5+ 32. hxg5 fxg5+ 33. Nxg5+
Kf8 34. f6 Ra7 35. Ke5 $1) 30. Kf3 Nb6 {A desperate try.} 31. hxg5 hxg5 32. Rh3
$1 {Lasker continues to execute his plan without any diversions.} (32. Rxd6 {
would have given Black some extra breathing time.} Nc4 33. Rd1 Rh8) 32... Rd7 (
32... Nc4 33. Ra1 {The combined invasion of the white rooks on the a- and
h-files demolished Black's defence.}) 33. Kg3 {The final preparation.} Ke8 34.
Rdh1 Bb7 35. e5 $1 $18 {It's amazing that with so many pieces Black wasn't
able to prevent this pawn from going ahead!} dxe5 36. Ne4 Nd5 37. N6c5 Bc8 38.
Nxd7 Bxd7 39. Rh7 Rf8 40. Ra1 Kd8 41. Ra8+ Bc8 42. Nc5 {Black resigned, and
the old chess wizard Lasker had become the winner of this historical contest.
The psychological effect of this brilliant victory was long-lasting. A shaken
Capablanca lost with White in the next round to Dr Tarrasch. And even seven
years later, in his world championship match against Lasker, he never played 3.
..a6 in the Ruy Lopez! (GK) It was really impressive to see Capablanca's
execution in this highly important game. And it was amazing to see the match
from 1921, when he won the title. Capablanca met the Ruy Lopez with the
Steinitz Defence 3...d6, which gave him completely passive positions, typical
for this line. But he successfully avoided the Exchange Variation and was
awarded for his stoicism with the championship title!} 1-0

[Event "Trade Union Spartakiad-08 Preliminaries"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1965.08.03"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Game 8"]
[Black "Botvinnik, M - Stein"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C85"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "98"]
[EventDate "1965.08.03"]
[EventRounds "5"]
[EventCountry "URS"]

{This was the second and last time Botvinnik played the delayed exchange in
his career. He had already lost the title to Petrosian two years before.
Usually Botvinnik played 1.d4, but meeting Leonid Stein, the acknowledged
King's Indian expert, he conducted the game in a safer manner. 1.e4 and the
Exchange Spanish was supposed to be enough to tame the beast.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 Nd7 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. Nc4 Bf6 9. O-O
O-O 10. b4 $5 {A novelty in this position. As usual, Botvinnik demonstrates
his great level of home preparation even in the lines he plays only
occasionally. Before this, he played it only in a training game against Furman
in 1961 and when he beat Wade the same year at Hastings Congress.} Qe7 11. a4 {
It is difficult for Black to create counterplay, as f7-f5 is not that easy to
prepare. Stein is patiently improving his pieces, waiting to see what White's
idea is.} Re8 12. Ba3 $5 (12. Bd2 Nf8 13. h3 Ng6 {would be the normal way to
proceed. The position is very rich, strategically. At first sight, it seems
like White is much better, but it is not clear how to make further progress.})
12... b5 ({It is questionable if Black should stop b4-b5. By playing b5, Black
restricts the bishop but also creates irreparable weaknesses. The bishop can
be redirected to b2 while the pawns never go back.} 12... Nf8 $1 13. b5 c5 14.
Bb2 Ng6 15. b6 Bg4 $132) 13. Na5 (13. Ne3 $5 Nb6 14. a5 Na4 15. c4 g6 16. h3
Bg7 17. Qc2 Be6 18. Rfd1 Rad8) 13... Qd6 (13... Qe6 14. c4 Nb6 15. axb5 axb5
16. c5 Na4 17. Bc1) 14. c4 $1 {The start of the central deployment - typical
for Botvinnik's style.} Nf8 15. c5 Qe6 16. Re1 {Botvinnik prepares d4 to smash
Black's last hold in the centre.} Rd8 17. Qc2 Ng6 18. Bc1 $1 {Preventing Nf4:
Accuracy, punctuality and precision was Botvinnik's slogan.} (18. Rad1 Nf4)
18... Nh4 19. Nxh4 Bxh4 20. Bb2 Re8 21. Re2 {White should look for a way to
open up files for penetration. He achieved a lot on the queenside, and it was
time to move on, but how and where?} (21. Rf1 $1 {, with the idea f4.} Bg5 22.
Nb3 Bd7 23. Bc1 Bxc1 24. Raxc1 Rad8 25. Rce1 Qg6 26. f4 exf4 27. Rxf4 f5) 21...
Qg6 22. f3 Re6 $6 (22... Bd7) 23. Bc3 ({It was the perfect moment for} 23. d4
$1 exd4 24. Nb3 $1) 23... Qh5 24. Qb2 Bg5 25. Rf1 Bf4 $1 {Black organized
unpleasant pressure while practically playing a rook down.} 26. g4 (26. g3 Rg6
27. Nxc6 Rxc6 28. gxf4 Rg6+ 29. Kh1 exf4 $13) 26... Qh3 27. Bd2 Rg6 28. Bxf4
exf4 29. Rg2 h5 30. Qe5 $1 {White took complete control of the centre, but his
kingside is under reconstruction.} hxg4 31. Qxf4 (31. Nxc6 gxf3 32. Rxg6 fxg6
33. Rf2 Qd7 34. Ne7+ Kh7 35. h3 $11) 31... bxa4 $1 {I have this somewhat
speculative idea about Leonid Stein. He was extremely talented and passed away
too young. I have heard that he was also very often in time trouble - so
imagine the additional pressure when everything was hanging on a tiny rope.
Some people are just addicted to situations like that.} 32. Rg3 $6 {Losing an
important tempo.} (32. Qxc7 gxf3 33. Rxg6 fxg6 34. Qg3 Qh6 35. Nxc6 Bh3 36.
Rxf3 Qc1+ 37. Kf2 Qd2+ $11) 32... gxf3 33. Rxg6 (33. Qxf3 Rxg3+ 34. hxg3 Be6
35. Nxc6 Re8 $17) 33... fxg6 34. Rxf3 Qg4+ $1 {Suddenly after the queen
exchange the situation is hopeless for White.} 35. Qxg4 Bxg4 36. Rg3 Bd7 37.
Rg2 Rf8 $1 38. Nc4 Bh3 39. Rf2 Rd8 (39... Rf6 $1 $19) 40. Rf3 Be6 41. Na3 Bb3
42. Kf2 Rb8 43. Rg3 Bf7 44. Ke3 Rxb4 45. Rg1 Rb2 46. Rb1 Ra2 47. Rb8+ Kh7 48.
Nc4 Bxc4 49. dxc4 a3 {White started with pressure on the queenside, then took
over the centre. But later he was first outplayed on the kingside and finished
on the queenside. Pay attention to the flanks!} 0-1

[Event "Olympiad-19 Final A"]
[Site "Siegen"]
[Date "1970.09.21"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Game 9"]
[Black "Fischer - Unzicker"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "83"]
[EventDate "1970.09.05"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "GER"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Ne7 {
Instead of the usual c5, which results in a somewhat worse endgame, Black
completes the development of his kingside, looking for dynamic chances in the
forthcoming middlegame. This was a novel idea at that time, developed by the
Hungarian players and introduced successfully at the highest level by Portisch.
He already won two games with it in 1967 and 1968, against Damjanovic and Hort.
There was also one earlier game against Unzicker in which he easily equalised.
Therefore, by exchanging on c6, Fischer demonstrated that he had found an
improvement.} 8. Be3 Ng6 {White has the freedom to choose his setup. For the
moment, Fischer follows the Damjanovic-Portisch game.} 9. Nd2 Bd6 10. Nc4 O-O
11. Qd3 $5 {This is the improvement that Fischer had in mind - White prepares
to exert pressure on the d-file.} (11. c3 {Damjanovic, M-Portisch,L Palma de
Mallorca 1967}) (11. f4 {prevents the trade of the knights, but then the
e4-pawn may become vulnerable.} Re8 12. Qd3 Qe7 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Rfe1 Qf7 $1
$11 (14... Qxe4 $2 15. Bf2 Qxd3 16. Rxe8+ Kf7 17. Rxc8 $3 $18)) 11... Ne5 (
11... Re8 12. Rad1 Qe7 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Nf5 Qxe4 15. Qxe4 Rxe4 16. Nxd6 Re7
17. Bc5 {gives White an advantage due to his total control of the holes on b6
and d6.}) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 (12... fxe5 13. Qb3+ Kh8 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. Qxe6 {
is obviously in White's favour.}) 13. f4 Bd6 ({For the moment, Black doesn't
like to fight for a draw by} 13... Bxd4 14. Bxd4 b6) 14. f5 $5 {Fischer
realises that he has nothing special and adopts the psychological trick known
from the Lasker-Capablanca game. The main idea is to restrict the Bc8, but it
seems antipositional to voluntarily devaluate one's own pawn majority,} (14.
Nf3 Be6) (14. Rad1 Qe7) (14. Rae1 Kh8) 14... Qe7 15. Bf4 $1 Bxf4 16. Rxf4 Bd7
17. Re1 $1 {The idea becomes clear now. White is preparing the plan to unblock
the pawns with Nf3 and e4-e5.} Qc5 ({Unzicker was right to avoid} 17... c5 18.
Nf3 Bc6 19. Qc4+ Kh8 20. Nh4 Be8 21. e5 fxe5 22. Nf3 Qd6 23. Nxe5 {, when
White will dominate the board,}) ({But the most critical test for White's idea
would be} 17... Qb4 $1 18. Nf3 Rad8 19. Qb3+ Qxb3 20. axb3 c5 ({or even} 20...
g5 $5) 21. g4 Bc6 22. Kf2 Rfe8 23. g5 Rd7 24. Rg4 Kf8 25. Kg3 Rde7 {, and
White's advantage in the endgame is questionable.}) 18. c3 Rae8 (18... Qd6 {
might have posed White some obstacles to reach the ideal setup.} 19. Qg3 (19.
Qe3 c5) 19... c5 20. Nf3 Rae8 $132) 19. g4 {This move was necessary to protect
the f5-pawn, but on the other hand, with so many pieces yet on the board,
weakening the king's position clearly offers Black counterattacking options.}
Qd6 20. Qg3 Re7 ({Taking into account what happened later in the game, it was
the ideal moment to look for active counterplay with} 20... g5 $1 21. Rf3 (21.
Rf2 Qxg3+ 22. hxg3 c5 23. Nf3 Bc6 24. Rfe2 Rd8 25. Re3 (25. Kf2 Rd3 26. Re3
Rfd8) 25... Rfe8 26. Kf2 Kf8) 21... Qxg3+ 22. Rxg3 c5 23. Nb3 b6 24. Rge3 Rd8
25. e5 fxe5 26. Rxe5 a5 27. Nc1 Bc6 $132 {, and despite obtaining the passed
pawn and full control of the e-file, the situation is still far from clear.})
21. Nf3 c5 ({One more time missing} 21... g5 $1 22. fxg6 (22. e5 Rxe5 23. Rd4
Rd5) 22... hxg6 23. e5 (23. h4 Rfe8 24. Kh2 c5 $132) 23... fxe5 24. Rxf8+ Kxf8
25. Nxe5 Kg7 $132) 22. e5 {Fischer executes his plan.} ({There was also the
possibility to play for an attack.} 22. g5 Kh8 23. Kf2 Rfe8 24. Qh4 {, with
unpleasant kingside pressure.}) 22... fxe5 23. Rfe4 {Analysis shows that even
here Black still enjoys excellent counterattacking chances.} Bc6 {Unzicker
tries to balance the situation by simplifications.} (23... g6 $5 24. Rxe5 (24.
fxg6 hxg6 25. Nxe5 Rfe8 26. Nxd7 Qxd7 27. Rxe7 Rxe7 28. Rxe7 Qxe7 $11) 24...
Rg7 25. fxg6 Rxg6 26. h3 h5 (26... c4 27. R1e2) (26... Rgf6 27. Rg5+ Kh8 28.
Qxd6 cxd6 29. Nh4 R8f7) 27. Nh4 Rg7 28. g5 Re7 29. Ng6 Rxe5 30. Nxe5 Kg7) (
23... Bc8 $5 24. Rxe5 (24. Nxe5 b5) 24... Rxe5 25. Nxe5 b6 26. Qf4 Bb7 27. Qc4+
Bd5 28. Qxa6 Re8) 24. Rxe5 Rfe8 25. Rxe7 Rxe7 26. Ne5 ({Fischer avoids the
trade of the last pair of rooks, as this would offer Black concrete drawing
chances.} 26. Rxe7 Qxe7 27. Ne5 Qg5 $1 (27... Bd5 28. c4) 28. Nxc6 bxc6 29. Kg2
h5) 26... h6 $6 {This is the first real mistake committed by Unzicker. So far
his defence was a little bit passive, but otherwise completely correct. Now
the time to take responsible decisions has come. It is necessary to stop the
advance of the pawns with g4-g5 and f5-f6, which will lead to the creation of
a far-advanced passed pawn and a direct mating attack.} (26... g6 $1 27. Qf4
gxf5 28. gxf5 Qd5 $132) 27. h4 Bd7 $6 {Continuing to play in the same passive
mode.} ({Why not} 27... Qd2 $1 28. Qf2 (28. g5 hxg5 29. hxg5 Bd5 30. f6 Re8
$132) 28... Qd5 {, and White has to exchange on c6,} 29. Nxc6 Rxe1+ 30. Qxe1
Qxc6 31. Kf2 c4 32. Qe3 Qd6 {, after which the queen endgame is a clear draw.})
28. Qf4 Qf6 {Black managed to stop g4-g5, but the final wave is yet to come.}
29. Re2 Bc8 $6 (29... b6 {would avoid the idea realised in the game.} 30. Nxd7
(30. Qc4+ Kh7 31. Ng6 Bb5 32. Rxe7 Bxc4 33. Re8 Bg8 $1 $11) 30... Rxd7 31. g5
hxg5 32. hxg5 Rd1+ 33. Kf2 Qd6 34. Qxd6 cxd6 35. Re8+ Kf7 36. Rb8 Rd5) 30. Qc4+
Kh7 31. Ng6 Rxe2 32. Qxe2 Bd7 $2 {The final mistake.} ({He had to defend
actively by} 32... Qd6 $1 33. Qe8 (33. h5 c4 $1) 33... Qd1+ 34. Kf2 Qc2+ 35.
Kf3 Qd3+ 36. Qe3 Qd1+ 37. Kg3 h5 $1) 33. Qe7 $1 {The endgame is winning for
White} Qxe7 34. Nxe7 g5 35. hxg5 hxg5 36. Nd5 Bc6 37. Nxc7 Bf3 38. Ne8 Kh6 39.
Nf6 Kg7 40. Kf2 Bd1 41. Nd7 c4 42. Kg3 {As in the Lasker-Capablanca game, the
idea of playing f4-f5 in this pawn structure was more of a psychological
weapon than a winning plan. Both games were won by White only because of the
extremely passive defence, probably caused by the surprise effect. In the
structure section you can find other games which will reveal in which
situation f4-f5 is a good idea objectively.} 1-0

[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
[Site "Berlin"]
[Date "2018.03.12"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Game 10"]
[Black "Aronian, L - Kramnik"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "54"]
[EventDate "2018.03.10"]
[EventRounds "14"]
[EventCountry "GER"]
[EventCategory "22"]

1. e4 {Aronian already surprises with his first move!} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7 {Black's idea, as described by Kramnik in
his annotations, is that if White delays h2-h3, Black also holds back with the
move Nf6-d7 and first develops his bishop. For example 7.Nbd2 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.
Nc4 Nd7. In my opinion, this is an ideal setup for Black, in which he has
hardly any problems.} 7. h3 $6 {After this game it became common knowledge
that combining h2-h3 and 0-0 is suicidal. But the refutation is not that
obvious.} Rg8 $1 {Black wants to save a tempo on h7-h6.} 8. Kh1 Nh5 $5 (8... h6
9. Nbd2 g5 10. Nc4 g4 11. Nfxe5 h5 12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 gxh3 {, and White is
still hanging on. The knight move is more ambitious.}) 9. c3 $6 {The most
natural, but an unfortunate reaction.} ({The engine recommends} 9. Nh2 {
, but after Black plays} g6 {and prepares to castle long, his position is just
perfect.}) (9. Nc3 g5 10. Nxe5 g4 11. d4 Bd6 12. g3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. h4
Bd7 {The position is still more or less level, but playing it with Black is
considerably more pleasant: He will castle long and have the initiative while
White's king and light squares are weak.}) 9... g5 10. Nxe5 ({After} 10. d4 {
the right move is} exd4 $1 (10... g4 $5 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. dxc5 Qf6) 11. cxd4
Bb6 12. Nh2 Nf6 13. e5 Nd5 {It is clear that White has lost the opening duel.})
10... g4 11. d4 {This is obviously the only move.} (11. hxg4 $4 Qh4+ 12. Kg1
Ng3) 11... Bd6 12. g3 Bxe5 ({Best was to complete development with} 12... Be6
$1 {, and if} 13. hxg4 $2 Bxe5 {, White will soon be mated. Otherwise Black
plays 0-0-0 and obtains a powerful attack in return for the pawn.}) 13. dxe5
Qxe5 14. Qd4 $1 {The most logical continuation.} (14. Kh2) (14. h4 Be6 {
The threat is to capture on g3 when} 15. Kh2 {can at least be met with} Qxe4 {
, winning a pawn.}) 14... Qe7 $5 ({It was possible to enter an endgame with an
extra pawn, but Kramnik is playing for more.} 14... Qxd4 15. cxd4 gxh3 16. Kh2
Be6) 15. h4 c5 $1 {The idea behind this move is to transfer the bishop to c6,
castle and then start the attack with f7-f5. The knight does not look best
placed on h5, but in the event of play on the light squares it will not be
possible for White to hold on to the pawn on e4, whilst the white king is very
weak.} 16. Qc4 $2 {The decisive mistake.} (16. Qd5 Nf6 {.}) (16. Qd3 Bd7 17. c4
O-O-O 18. Nc3 Rge8 19. Re1 Bc6 $40) 16... Be6 17. Qb5+ c6 18. Qa4 (18. Qe2 f5
19. Bg5 Rxg5 20. hxg5 f4 {does not help much either - it's only a slightly
better version of what happened in the game.}) ({The computer recommends} 18.
Qd3 Rd8 19. Qe3 (19. Qe2 f5) 19... Bc4 20. Rg1 (20. Re1 Rd3 21. Qh6 Qe5) 20...
Rg6 21. Qe1 Bd3 $19) 18... f5 $1 19. Bg5 (19. exf5 Nxg3+ $1 20. fxg3 Bd5+ 21.
Kg1 Qe2 22. Rf2 Qe1+ {with mate.}) 19... Rxg5 $1 {This move can hardly be
considered a sacrifice. .} 20. hxg5 f4 {White has no counterplay and will
simply be mated.} 21. Qd1 Rd8 {Of course 21...fxg3 also wins.} 22. Qc1 fxg3 23.
Na3 Rd3 $1 24. Rd1 Bd5 $1 (24... Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 gxf2) 25. f3 (25. exd5 Qe4+ 26.
Kg1 gxf2+ $19) 25... gxf3 26. exd5 (26. Rxd3 Qxe4 $1 27. Re3 f2+ 28. Rxe4+
Bxe4#) 26... Qe2 $1 27. Re1 (27. Qc2 g2+ 28. Kh2 g1=Q+ 29. Kxg1 f2+ 30. Kh2 {
, and here the simplest is} Rh3+ $1 31. Kxh3 Qf3+ 32. Kh4 Qg3+ 33. Kxh5 Qh3# {
Again very beautiful.}) 27... g2+ {White resigned. This is the immortal (or
evergreen) game of the 21st century.} 0-1

