[Event "St Petersburg International Final"]
[Site "St Petersburg"]
[Date "1914.05.17"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Game 1"]
[Black "Alekhine - Lasker"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "89"]
[EventDate "1914.05.10"]
[EventRounds "10"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

{This game is important for my historical investigation. Future world champion
Alekhine is playing against the reigning champion Lasker at the start of one
the strongest events in the first half of the 20th century - the international
tournament in Saint Petersburg 1914. In this game, Alekhine challenges the
"father" of the exchange variation on his own territory.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 f6 $1 {Lasker knows very well from his own
experience that this is the right approach for Black.} (5... Bc5) (5... Bg4) 6.
d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd6 9. Be3 Ne7 10. O-O-O {The established way to
handle this position - castle long, then f3, Nde2 and Bf4, exchanging the
important bishop.} O-O 11. Nb3 $1 {A new idea - White is ready to play Bc5,
which is quite unpleasant, as Black counts on his bishop pair to compensate
for the troubled pawn structure. Alekhine shows a very high level of home
preparation and Lasker might have been a little worried at this point.} Ng6 (
11... b6 $2 12. Bxb6) 12. Bc5 (12. g3 $6 Bg4) 12... Bf4+ 13. Kb1 Re8 14. Rhe1
$1 {Preparing to chase Black's bishop.} (14. g3 Be5 15. Bd4 Bg4 16. Rd3 Bxd4
17. Rxd4 Bf3 18. Re1 Ne5) 14... b6 15. Be3 Be5 16. Bd4 $1 Nh4 $6 {Trying to
find a weak spot to start immediate counterplay - this was typical for
Lasker's way of defence. But here it was better to repeat moves with} (16...
Bf4 17. Be3 $1 ({The trick is that} 17. g3 $6 {is not working anymore due to}
Bd6 {, and if} 18. Bxb6 $6 Bg4 19. Rd2 Ne5 $17)) 17. Rg1 ({Exchanging one of
the bishops would be the most logical and obvious solution:} 17. Bxe5 $1 fxe5 {
The e5 pawn will be a long-term weakness in the endgame.} ({But even worse
would be} 17... Rxe5 18. g3 Nf3 19. Re3 $1 Nxh2 20. f3) 18. Rg1 Be6 19. Nc1 Ng6
20. Nd3 $14) (17. g3 $2 Nf3) 17... Be6 (17... g5 $5) 18. f4 (18. Bxe5 fxe5 19.
Nc1 {would be more in the spirit of this endgame. Creating a long-term
weakness on e5 would pass the strategic initiative to White.}) 18... Bd6 (18...
Bxf4 $4 19. g3) 19. Bf2 (19. Bxb6 $2 Bxf4) 19... Ng6 20. f5 {No way back -
Alekhine is forced to make this antipositional move, which in
Lasker-Capablanca was a well-planned idea.} (20. g3 $6 Bb4) 20... Bxb3 21. axb3
(21. fxg6 Be6 22. gxh7+ Kh8 $1 23. Bxb6 Bxh2 $17) 21... Nf8 (21... Ne5 $6 22.
Bxb6) (21... Nh8 $5 22. Bxb6 Bxh2 23. Rh1 cxb6 24. Rxh2 Nf7 $15) 22. Bxb6 Bxh2
23. Rh1 cxb6 24. Rxh2 b5 25. Re1 Nd7 26. Nd1 a5 27. Rh3 b4 28. Nf2 Nc5 {
Black has a pleasant choice at this point, but I believe that releasing
control over the e5-square is not the best solution.} (28... Ne5 29. Nd3 $11) (
28... a4 29. bxa4 Rxa4 30. Nd3 Rea8 31. Kc1) (28... Re7 29. Nd3 Rae8 30. Rhe3
g6) 29. Rhe3 a4 $1 30. bxa4 Nxa4 31. e5 $1 {After this break, Alekhine is
already better. He has no more problems with the backward pawn on e4.} fxe5 32.
Rxe5 Reb8 $1 {Avoiding the exchange of the rooks and setting up a small trap .}
(32... Rxe5 33. Rxe5 Nb6 34. g4 Nc4 35. Rc5 Nd2+ 36. Kc1 Nf3 37. b3 Ra1+ 38.
Kb2 Rg1) 33. Ne4 b3 $1 (33... Nc3+ {would only be a draw.} 34. Nxc3 bxc3 35. b3
Rb6 36. R1e3 Rba6 37. Re8+ Rxe8 38. Rxe8+ Kf7 39. Re3 Kf6 40. g4 Kg5 41. Re7
Kxg4 42. Rxg7+ Kxf5 43. Rxh7 Ke5) 34. Re2 $8 (34. cxb3 $6 Rxb3 35. Re2 Rab8) (
34. c3 Nb6 35. Nd2 $1 {would solve all problems.}) 34... Nb6 {Lasker played
for tricks, creating multiple hidden threats. Amazingly he succeeded against
such a strong calculator as Alekhine.} (34... Nxb2 {would be a draw.} 35. Kxb2
Ra2+ 36. Kc3 b2 37. Nd2) 35. cxb3 Nd5 36. g4 (36. Kc2 Nb4+ 37. Kd2 Rd8+ 38. Ke3
Rd3+ 39. Kf2 Rxb3 40. Kg1) 36... h6 (36... Rxb3 37. g5 Rab8) 37. g5 hxg5 38.
Nxg5 Nf6 39. Re7 $6 (39. Kc2 {, and White is a pawn up and has a better
position.}) 39... Rxb3 40. Rg2 (40. Ne6 $142 Rg3 $11) 40... Nd5 41. Rd7 $2 {
The final blunder. Alekhine lost focus and ran into an unexpected refutation.}
(41. Re1) 41... Rd3 $3 $19 {Threatening Nc3 and also Rd1 with Ne3. Suddenly
both white rooks are hanging.} 42. Rxd5 $8 (42. Kc1 $2 Ra1+ 43. Kc2 Nb4#) 42...
Rxd5 43. Ne6 Kf7 $1 (43... Ra7 44. f6) (43... Rd7 44. f6) 44. Rxg7+ Kf6 45. Rc7
{Despite a heroic defence, Lasker won this endgame. It might be that the
handling of the opening by Alekhine gave Lasker some food for thought, and he
took the setup with Nb3 and f4 more seriously, which brought him a decisive
victory against Capablanca and the first place in the tournament.} 0-1

[Event "Match Alekhine-Teichmann +2-2=2"]
[Site "Berlin"]
[Date "1921.??.??"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Game 2"]
[Black "Alekhine - Teichmann"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "76"]
[EventDate "1921.06.??"]
[EventRounds "6"]
[EventCountry "GER"]

{Seven years after the memorable event in Saint Peterburg, Alekhine played the
Exchange Spanish again in his match against Teichmann. It is very instructive
to see how he was slowly outplayed, starting from a seemingly much better
position.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 f6 6. d4 exd4 7.
Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd6 9. Nde2 $1 {Alekhine is not convinced of his setup with
0-0-0 and Nb3 despite the success of Lasker against Capablanca. He uses the
other, more simple way to exchange the bishops.} Ne7 10. Bf4 $1 Be6 11. Bxd6 {
Alekhine is in a hurry to swap the bishops, improving Black's pawn structure.
In case of} (11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. Rd2 {, Black may favourably avoid the
exchange with} Bc5 $5) 11... cxd6 12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. Rhe1 Bf7 14. Nd4 Rhe8 15.
f3 Kc7 {The position is about equal, but it is Black who now took the
strategic initiative. His plan is to expand on the queenside with b5, a5.} 16.
a4 b5 $1 17. axb5 axb5 18. b4 {Trying to hold off the pawns but creating a
hole on c4. Still, the position is about equal.} Nc8 $1 19. Nf5 g6 20. Ne3 {
Covering c4.} Nb6 21. Kb2 $6 {This move is obviously wrong, as it creates the
tactical idea of the fork on c4.} ({In case of} 21. Kd2 f5 {looks dangerous,
but White can defend easily.} 22. Ra1 (22. exf5 $2 d5 $1) 22... Kb7 23. exf5 d5
24. Nf1 Nc4+ 25. Kd3 d4 26. Rxe8 Nb2+ 27. Kd2 Nc4+ $11) 21... d5 (21... f5 $1
22. g3 fxe4 23. Nxe4 d5 24. Ng5 Rxe3 25. Rxe3 Nc4+ 26. Kb1 Nxe3 27. Re1 d4 28.
Nxf7 Rd7 29. Ne5 Re7 30. Nd3 Kd6 $17 {would be quite difficult to save.}) 22.
Rd4 $6 {A second blunder, and now the situation becomes critical.} (22. Ng4 $1
d4 23. Ne2 Ra8 24. Nxd4 Na4+ 25. Kc1 Nc3 26. Nxf6 (26. Rd3 Na2+) 26... Red8 27.
Rd3 Na2+ 28. Kb1 Nxb4 29. Rdd1 $1 {, and White is holding.}) 22... f5 23. Ra1
Nc8 24. g4 $5 (24. Rad1 Nd6 25. g3 Re7 {, and White is tied up.}) 24... dxe4
25. Rxd8 Kxd8 26. fxe4 f4 $1 (26... fxe4 {is not that easy to win, as White
has a tough blockade.}) 27. Rd1+ (27. Ng2 g5 28. Ne1 $1 Kc7 29. Nf3 h6 $17)
27... Kc7 28. Rf1 g5 $1 {, and White is lost.} 29. Nf5 Nd6 30. Ra1 Nc4+ 31. Kc1
Kb7 $6 (31... Kb6 $1) 32. Nd4 h5 33. gxh5 Bxh5 34. Nb3 f3 (34... Rd8) 35. Nd2 (
35. Nd1 $1 Bg6 36. Nc5+ Kc7 37. Nf2 Rh8 38. h3 g4 39. Ra7+ Kb8 40. Rb7+ Kc8 41.
Nxg4 Rxh3 $19) 35... Ne3 36. Ra3 f2 {The advanced passed pawn decides.} 37. Na4
bxa4 38. Rxe3 Rd8 0-1

[Event "American National Manhattan CC"]
[Site "New York"]
[Date "1913.01.22"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Game 3"]
[Black "Capablanca - Janowski"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C48"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "107"]
[EventDate "1913.01.19"]
[EventRounds "13"]
[EventCountry "USA"]

{This game was played one year before the famous Capablanca-Janowski game from
Saint Peterburg 1914, which was decided by a pawn storm on the queenside. Here
again, the situation was quite sharp, but instead of attacking on the
queenside, Capablanca realised another typical plan with f4. This game is
famous mostly for the long-term squeeze in the rook endgame.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 a6 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. Qe2 {The
combination of h3 and short castle would be severely punished in the 21st
century - look at the game Aronian-Kramnik in the section on opposite castling.
} Bd6 ({Someone like Nakamura would now unleash} 8... g5 9. g4 (9. d4 g4 10.
hxg4 (10. Nxe5 $2 gxh3) 10... Bxg4 11. dxe5 Nd7 12. Bf4 Rg8) 9... Nxg4 10. hxg4
Bxg4 11. Qe3 Qf6 12. Nh2 h5) ({The simple} 8... Nd7 9. d3 Qf6 {would have also
been more than enough to refute the white setup.}) 9. d3 Qe7 $6 (9... Nd7 {
/\Df6!}) 10. Nd1 $1 {There is no other way to break the pin - the knight is
heading to f5.} O-O-O 11. Ne3 Bg6 12. Nh4 $1 ({Capablanca is focusing on the
kingside first, as there is no time for a pawn storm. Black's counterplay is
coming too quickly.} 12. a3 Nh5 13. b4 Nf4 $40) 12... Rhg8 {Too passive - it
was necessary to prevent f4.} (12... Nh5 $1 13. Nef5 Qd7 14. Qf3 f6 15. Be3 Kb8
16. Rab1 Nf4 17. Bxf4 (17. b4 $2 Bh5) 17... exf4 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. b4 Rhf8 20.
a4 f5 $132) 13. Nef5 Qe6 14. f4 ({Even better was} 14. Nxd6+ cxd6 15. f4 $1
exf4 16. Bxf4) 14... Bxf5 (14... Bc5+ 15. Be3 (15. Kh1 Nh5) 15... Bxe3+ 16.
Qxe3 Kb8 17. b4 exf4 18. Qxf4 Nd7 19. a4) 15. Nxf5 exf4 16. Bxf4 (16. Nxd6+
cxd6 17. Bxf4 g5 18. Bd2 Nd7 19. Rf5 d5) 16... Bc5+ (16... Bxf4 17. Rxf4 Nd7
18. a3 Kb8) 17. Be3 Bf8 {It is difficult to justify such a move. Usually when
I ask my students what the purpose of playing moves like that is, the answer
is "I didn't know what else to do". There are no good moves to play in bad
positions and this is actually the reason why those positions are bad.} 18. Qf2
Rd7 19. Bc5 {Further chasing the bishop - White is focused on the kingside and
wants to exchange an important defender. But it was also possible to start the
pawn storm:} (19. Rab1 $5) 19... Bxc5 20. Qxc5 Kb8 21. Rf2 Ne8 22. Raf1 f6 (
22... Qxa2 $6 23. Ne7) 23. b3 Nd6 24. Rf4 Nxf5 25. Qxf5 Qxf5 26. Rxf5 {This is
the endgame for which I analysed this game. Capablanca played it perfectly and
created a model example for handling this kind of pawn structures.} Re8 27. g4
{The minority attack will create a weakness on f6 or will open the f-file and
create a strong passed pawn on e4. Meanwhile, Capablanca is immobilizing the
opponent's queenside pawns.} b6 28. b4 $1 Kb7 29. Kf2 {Centralising the king.}
b5 {Creating the first active idea in the game - a5 and Ra8.} 30. a4 $1 (30.
Ke3 a5 31. a3 Ra8 32. g5 axb4 33. axb4 Ra4 34. gxf6 gxf6 35. Rxf6 Rxb4 36. Rf7
Rbd4 37. h4 $16) 30... Rd4 (30... bxa4 {would ruin the structure completely.}
31. Ra1 Re5 32. Rxa4) 31. Rb1 Re5 (31... a5 $1 {was the last chance to stay
alive.}) 32. Ke3 $1 {, and it is over now.} Rd7 33. a5 $1 Re6 34. Rbf1 Rde7 35.
g5 fxg5 36. Rxg5 Rh6 37. Rg3 Rhe6 (37... c5 38. bxc5 Kc6 39. d4 Rh4 40. Rf4)
38. h4 g6 39. Rg5 h6 40. Rg4 Rg7 41. d4 Kc8 42. Rf8+ Kb7 43. e5 g5 44. Ke4 Ree7
45. hxg5 hxg5 46. Rf5 Kc8 47. Rgxg5 Rh7 48. Rh5 Kd7 49. Rxh7 Rxh7 50. Rf8 Rh4+
51. Kd3 Rh3+ 52. Kd2 c5 53. bxc5 Ra3 54. d5 {True to Capablanca's slogan: Play
simple and strong.} 1-0

[Event "Wien Trebitsch Memorial-06"]
[Site "Vienna"]
[Date "1914.12.07"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Game 4"]
[Black "Reti- Schlechter"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "80"]
[EventDate "1914.11.12"]
[EventRounds "14"]
[EventCountry "AUT"]

{This game was played about 6 months after Lasker-Capablanca. Amazed by
Lasker's straightforward victory, Reti also tries to adopt the plan with f4.
The great deception was that f4 is an improvement, but soon the truth will
come to the surface. Schlechter shows an improvement for Black and totally
refutes the setup with f4. Now it becomes clear that this setup is
antipositional and Lasker's great victory was just a splash of the tidal wave.
} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4
Bd6 ({In an earlier game Reti tried to be trendy and played the Exchange
Spanish the usual way. This had catastrophic results.} 7... Bd7 8. Bf4 O-O-O 9.
Ne2 Ne7 10. Nd2 Ng6 11. Bg3 c5 12. O-O-O Bc6 13. f3 Be7 14. Rhe1 b6 15. Nf1 h5
16. c3 $2 (16. Bf2 $1 $15) 16... Bb5 (16... Bg5+ 17. Kc2 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 h4 19.
Bf2 h3 20. g3 Ne5 $19) 17. Ng1 h4 18. Bf2 Nf4 19. Ne3 Nd3+ $19 {Reti,R-Dobias,
J Mlada Boleslav 1913}) 8. O-O Ne7 9. Nc3 Bd7 10. f4 O-O-O $1 11. Be3 Rhe8 $1 {
White's centre is already under severe pressure} 12. Nb3 $2 (12. Rae1 Bb4 $1)
12... Nd5 {This is good, but playing the normal way would give even better
results.} (12... b6 13. Rad1 (13. a4 a5 $1) 13... c5 14. e5 Nf5 15. Bf2 Bf8 {
, and based on modern understanding and comparing it to positions arising from
the Berlin defence, one should evaluate the position as much better for Black.}
) 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. e5 Bf8 15. Bc5 {looks like a favourable exchange for White
- Black has the bishop pair and White's Be3 is a bad bishop, as the f4 and e5
pawns are on the same colour. But in the arising endgame the remaining bishop
is superior to the knight.} Bxc5+ 16. Nxc5 Bf5 17. Rf2 b6 $1 18. Nd3 (18. Nxa6
c5 $1 19. b4 Kb7 20. b5 d4 $17) 18... c5 19. Rd2 Kc7 20. Nf2 g5 (20... f6 $5) (
{The standard} 20... h5 $1 {would also be good enough.}) 21. g3 $2 {After this
move White's defence collapses.} ({The only chance to survive is to simplify
the position.} 21. fxg5 Rxe5 22. Rf1 Be6 23. h4 $15 {is the only defence.})
21... gxf4 22. gxf4 Rg8+ {White's position is already hopeless. His pieces are
uncoordinated, his pawns are weak and his king is in danger.} 23. Kf1 Rg6 24.
Rad1 Kc6 25. Nh1 (25. c3 Rh6 26. Kg2 Rg8+ 27. Kf3 Rxh2 28. Rxd5 Rgg2 $19) 25...
Bh3+ 26. Kf2 f6 $1 $19 {Completely destroying the pawns. The realisation of
the advantage is too easy.} 27. Rg1 (27. exf6 Rxf6 28. Kg3 Rg8+ $19) 27... Rxg1
28. Kxg1 fxe5 29. fxe5 Re8 30. Re2 Rf8 31. Ng3 Kd7 32. e6+ (32. Nh5 Ke6 33.
Ng7+ Ke7 34. Re1 Rf3 $19) 32... Bxe6 33. Re5 Rf6 34. Rg5 Rg6 35. Rxg6 hxg6 36.
Kf2 Kd6 37. Kf3 Ke5 38. h4 d4 39. h5 gxh5 40. Nxh5 Bxa2 0-1

[Event "Belgrade-Moscow"]
[Site "Belgrade"]
[Date "1998.01.28"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Game 5"]
[Black "Smyslov- Gligoric"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[EventDate "1998.01.28"]
[EventRounds "2"]
[EventCountry "YUG"]

{A game between two of the greatest players of modern chess. The first game
between them was exactly 50 years ago, when Smyslov was only 27 and Gligoric
25 years old.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 exd4 6. Qxd4
Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. Be3 (9. O-O O-O 10. f4 Re8 11. Nb3 f6 12. f5 {
will be the game Lasker,E-Capablanca,J/St.Petersburg 1914, analysed in the
historical section.}) 9... O-O (9... Bd7 {and 0-0-0 would lead to game 4 Reti
-Schlechter.}) 10. O-O-O f5 $1 {This might be Black's most simple way to reach
pleasant equality.} 11. f3 fxe4 $1 $146 (11... f4 12. Bf2 Ng6 13. Kb1 Ne5 14.
Nb3 a5 15. Nc1 a4 {would be less clear.}) 12. Nxe4 (12. fxe4 $2 Ng6 $17 {
would be too bad for White.}) 12... Nd5 13. Bf2 Nf4 14. Nxd6 {There was
nothing better.} (14. g3 Nh3 15. Rhf1 c5 16. Nb3 Rxf3 17. Bxc5 Rxf1 18. Rxf1
Bxc5 19. Nexc5 b6) (14. Bg3 Nxg2 15. Bxd6 cxd6 16. Nxd6 Rb8 $11) 14... cxd6 15.
Bg3 Nxg2 16. Bxd6 Re8 17. h4 Ne3 18. Rde1 Bd7 19. b3 Nf5 20. Nxf5 Bxf5 21. Re5
{The draw is more than obvious.} Rxe5 22. Bxe5 Re8 23. f4 Re6 24. Rg1 Rg6 25.
Rxg6 Bxg6 26. Kd2 Kf7 27. a4 Bf5 28. a5 Kg6 29. c3 Kh5 30. Bxg7 Kxh4 1/2-1/2

[Event "S.Stefan/Beograd (m)"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "1992.??.??"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Game 6"]
[Black "Fischer - Spassky"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "41"]
[EventDate "1992.??.??"]

{After 20 years of absence, Fischer is coming back to play the "return" match
against Spassky. Although he had been inactive for such a long period, Fischer
reveals new dimensions in his home preparation. He won game 9 in his typical
surgical style, crushing his opponent in an endgame after 21 moves!} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O $1 f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 {*} 8. Nb3
Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bg4 {This is established as the best reply.} (9... Bd7 {is more
passive.} 10. Bf4 O-O-O 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Rxd8+ Kxd8 13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Nd5 Bxd5
15. Rxd5 {will lead to a position where White's chances are significantly
increased due to the exchange of Black's bishop and a pair of rooks.}) (9...
Bd6 $6 {is a well-known mistake which should be punished by} 10. Na5 $1 b5 (
10... Bg4 $2 11. f3 O-O-O $4 12. e5 $18 {Hort-Zheljandinov,Havanna 1967}) 11.
c4 $1 Ne7 (11... b4 $6 {Peshina-Romanischin, URS 1968} 12. Nd2 Kf7 13. Ndb3 $16
) 12. Be3 {is also very unpleasant, for example} f5 $5 (12... Rb8 13. Nd2 Be6
14. Rac1 Kf7 15. Ndb3 Rhd8 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxc5 $16 {Lukin-Kaminski,URS 1970}
) 13. Nc3 f4 14. e5 $1 {You will later see this break executed as well in the
present game.} Bxe5 $6 (14... fxe3 15. exd6 exf2+ 16. Kxf2 O-O+ 17. Kg1 cxd6
18. Rxd6 Bf5 19. Re1) 15. Bxc5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ng6 17. Nc6 Be6 $6 (17... Bd7) 18.
cxb5 axb5 19. Na7 $16 {Fischer,R-Portisch,L Havana 1966}) 10. f3 Be6 11. Nc3 (
11. Bf4 c4 12. Nd4 O-O-O {, and you can see the difference between Bd7 and Bg4
- now White must lose one tempo to solve the problem with the pin on the a7-g1
diagonal.}) 11... Bd6 12. Be3 b6 13. a4 $1 {This position is still quite
topical. The best defence for black has been found, but it's still White who
keeps an opening initiative and Black has to play carefully.} O-O-O $6 (13...
Kf7 {is one good defensive option. After} 14. a5 c4 15. Nd4 b5 16. Nxe6 Kxe6
$11 {The endgame is defensible.}) (13... a5 {is also a good choice. In the
game Mamedyarov,S -Ragger,M Vienna 2015 there followed} 14. Nb5 O-O-O 15. Nxd6+
cxd6 16. Nd2 {, and now Black should have played the simple} Ne7 $1 {,
reaching obvious equality.} 17. c4 (17. Bf2 d5 18. exd5 Bxd5 $11) 17... f5 $1 {
Black's setup is harmonious and he has nothing to fear.}) 14. a5 $1 {Creating
an unpleasant tension, but on such a level you can't really expect to win in
only 6 more moves.} Kb7 (14... Bxb3 15. cxb3 b5 {is one possible solution
which doesn't give White many chances.} 16. Nd5 Ne7 17. Rac1 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Be5
$11 {proved to be just equal in the game Nisipeanu,L -Onischuk, A Foros 2008.}
19. Rdxc5 (19. Rcxc5 Rxd5 20. Rxd5 Bxb2 $11) 19... Rd3 20. f4 Bd6 21. Rd5 Rxe3
22. Rxd6 Re8 $1 (22... Rxe4 23. Rdc6 $2 $16) 23. Rxa6 (23. Rdc6 Re7 $1) 23...
R8xe4 $11 {Black has enough counterplay and holds easily.}) 15. e5 $1 {It is
quite strange that Spassky missed this move because Fischer won against
Portisch in 1966 with exactly the same idea.} Be7 $8 (15... fxe5 16. axb6 Bxb3
(16... cxb6 17. Ne4 $18) 17. bxc7 Bxc7 18. Rxd8 Bxd8 19. cxb3 Nf6 20. Bxc5 $16)
16. Rxd8 Bxd8 17. Ne4 $1 (17. Bxc5 fxe5 18. Bf8 Bf6 19. Ne4) 17... Kc6 $4 {
An amazing blunder for such a high-level player as Spassky.} ({It was not so
difficult to find the only defence} 17... Bxb3 18. cxb3 Be7 19. b4 (19. axb6
cxb6 20. Nd6+ Bxd6 21. exd6 a5 $1 $11) 19... cxb4 20. axb6 cxb6 21. Rd1 fxe5
22. Nd6+ Bxd6 23. Rxd6 Kc7 24. Rxb6 a5 25. Ra6 Ne7 26. Rxa5 Nc6) 18. axb6 cxb6
19. Nbxc5 $1 Bc8 (19... bxc5 20. Rxa6+ Bb6 21. Bxc5 $18) 20. Nxa6 fxe5 21. Nb4+
{An incredible achievement by Fischer, but you can see that his quick victory
was due to bad play by Spassky, who missed a couple of chances for a better
defence.} 1-0

[Event "Sinquefield Cup"]
[Site "Saint Louis"]
[Date "2013.09.13"]
[Round "4"]
[White "Game 7"]
[Black "Kamsky, G - Carlsen"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "118"]
[EventDate "2013.09.09"]
[EventRounds "6"]
[EventCountry "USA"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. dxe5 (7. c3 {
will lead to more complicated positions. I will pay attention to the ideas for
both sides in this position in the section about the related pawn structures.})
7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 9. Rd3 {This is White's only chance to fight for an
advantage.} (9. Nbd2 $6 O-O-O {would be already more pleasant for Black.}) 9...
Bd6 10. Nbd2 Nf6 {The modern defence.} ({The other move} 10... b5 {is also
possible - I will mention the following game of the young Garry Kasparov, in
which he was outplayed with the white pieces.} 11. b3 Ne7 12. Bb2 Ng6 13. g3
O-O 14. Kg2 Rae8 15. c4 Rf6 16. Rc1 c5 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Ba3 b4 19. Bb2 Ra8 20.
Nc4 Raf8 21. Ncd2 Ne7 22. a4 Nc6 23. h3 Bc8 24. Nc4 Rxf3 $1 25. Rxf3 Bxh3+ 26.
Kxh3 Rxf3 27. Kg2 Rxb3 28. Ra1 Rxb2 $1 (28... Na5 29. Nxa5 Rxb2) 29. Nxb2 Na5
30. Rc1 b3 31. Kf3 c4 32. Rxc4 {Kasparov,G-Kharitonov,A Leningrad 1977. Black
was winning with the simple} Nxc4 (32... Ba3 $2 $18) 33. Nxc4 h5 34. a5 g5 35.
a6 Bc5 36. Kg2 Kg7 $19) 11. Nc4 {White is pointing on the weakened e5-pawn,
but Black's piece activity is enough to give him a perfectly good game.} O-O
12. Nfxe5 (12. Ncxe5 {is less precise.} Bh5 $1) 12... Be2 $1 13. Re3 (13. Rb3
Rae8 14. Nd3 Nxe4 15. Be3 b6) (13. Rd2 Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Bc5 15. Re2 Rae8 16. Be3
Rxe4) 13... Bxc4 14. Nxc4 Ng4 $1 {The most accurate move. At least here White
has some chances of going wrong.} (14... Bc5 {is known to be drawish.} 15. Re1
Rae8 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 Rxe4 18. Rxe4 Nxe4 19. f3 Nd6 {, and although White
should be minimally better because of the structure, it is quite difficult to
win such a position.}) 15. Re2 Bxh2+ 16. Kf1 $6 {The king is safer and better
placed on h1.} (16. Kh1 Bg3 17. f3 $11) 16... Rae8 17. Nd2 $6 {It's going to
become incredibly hard to develop because of the self-pin.} (17. c3 {Just
passing and allowing some breathing room on the second rank was much better.}
h5 18. f3 h4 19. Bg5 h3 20. Nd2 Bf4 21. Bxf4 Rxf4 22. Kg1 Ne5 23. g3 Rf7 24.
Kh2 Nxf3+ 25. Nxf3 Rxf3 26. Kxh3 $11) 17... Rd8 $1 {Carlsen now secured a pin
on the d-file that caused White's development a complete stall.} 18. f3 (18.
Nf3 Rd1+ 19. Re1 Rxe1+ 20. Kxe1 Bd6 $17) 18... Bg3 19. Kg1 Ne5 20. b3 Ng6 $1 {
Magnus' moves are all precise, with the goal of not allowing White easy
development.} 21. Nf1 Be5 22. c3 {This is losing a pawn for nothing, but there
was not much hope anyway.} (22. Rb1 Rd1 23. Rd2 Bd4+ 24. Kh2 Rxf1 25. Rxd4 Nf4
26. Rd7 Rf6 27. Bxf4 $1 Rxb1 28. Be5 Rh6+ 29. Kg3 Rg6+ 30. Kf2 Rc1 $17) 22...
Bxc3 23. Bb2 Nf4 24. Rc2 Ba5 {Carlsen keeps as many pieces on the board as
possible, which especially makes sense due to the somewhat exposed king. There
was also nothing wrong with simplifying the position and exploiting the
material advantage.} 25. Ng3 g6 26. Rf1 Rd3 27. Kh2 Bb4 28. Ne2 Ne6 29. Nc1 Rd7
30. g3 Rfd8 31. Kg2 Kf7 32. f4 h5 33. Kh3 a5 34. Kg2 Nc5 35. Kf3 Nd3 36. Re2
Be7 $2 {Allowing White some hope.} (36... Nxb2 37. Rxb2 Ba3 38. Rc2 Rd2 {
, and it will be very hard for White to hold this position, as a2 will soon
fall as well.}) 37. Nxd3 Rxd3+ 38. Kg2 Bc5 $6 {The extra pawn still gives
Black excellent chances to win, but the advantage is slipping move by move.
The bishop is not well placed on c5, as it might be forced back to b6 into a
defensive position.} (38... Rd2 39. Rxd2 Rxd2+ 40. Rf2 Rd3 $19) 39. Rc1 $6 (39.
Be5 $1 {would have at least forced Black to find an active idea to defend c7.}
Bd6 40. Bb2 {And now any move by the bishop will be met with Be5 again.}) 39...
Rd2 40. Rce1 Rxe2+ (40... Bb4 {was also more accurate.}) 41. Rxe2 {The time
control has been reached. Black is still up a pawn, but will have a tough
technical job ahead of him after missing many ways of finishing off his
opponent.} Rd3 42. Rc2 Bd6 43. Bc1 Be7 44. Kf2 a4 45. Rd2 Rxd2+ $2 {A strange
decision. The bishop endgame looks less promising than the rook endgame.} (
45... Bc5+ $1 46. Kg2 Rc3 47. Bb2 Re3 48. Bd4 Bxd4 49. Rxd4 a3 $1 {gives Black
great winning chances.}) 46. Bxd2 axb3 47. axb3 c5 48. g4 $6 {Not necessarily
losing, but why create a free passed pawn for Black? Much more tenacious was
to simply wait and keep the king on e2-d3, forcing Black to figure out a plan
of action.} b5 49. gxh5 gxh5 50. Bc3 $2 {The final blunder.} (50. Kf3 b4 51.
Be3 {should still be somehow winning for Black, but it's much more difficult
to figure out.}) 50... b4 51. Bb2 Bh4+ {Not the most precise, but also winning.
} 52. Ke2 Bg3 {The combined action between the passed pawn on h4 and the
threats of breaking on c4 and exchanging bishops gives Carlsen the win. Here
he forces the f-pawn forward, so that he will be able to easily trade bishops
later.} 53. f5 h4 54. e5 h3 55. e6+ (55. Kf3 Bh4 56. Ba1 Be1 $19) 55... Ke7 56.
Kf3 Bf4 57. Bg7 Bg5 58. Be5 c4 59. bxc4 Bf6 {White has two passed pawns, but
they are worth nothing compared to the outside passed pawns of Black, which
will soon promote.} 0-1

