{One more drawish endgame, and one more time Carlsen wins.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Nc3 $5 {Spassky used to play this way.} Bc5 ({The
other mainline goes} 5... b5) 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 {This position is very
similar to one of the main lines of the Berlin Defence. The only difference is
that the pawn is on a6. White's usual plan is connected with h3, Qe2 or Nbd2,
rather than Nc3.} Qd6 $1 (7... O-O 8. Be3 $1 Bd6 9. Bg5 {Carlsen, M -Karjakin,
S (2760) World Blitz 2017} Re8 (9... h6 10. Bd2 $1 {may create trouble in view
of the eventual g4-g5.}) 10. h3 c5 11. Nd5 Be7 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. O-O h6 14.
Be3 Nd7 15. Nd2 Nb8 16. f4 $1 exf4 17. Rxf4 Nc6 18. Qh5 b6 19. Raf1 Rf8 20. Nf3
{, and White had strong pressure.}) 8. h3 Be6 9. Be3 $1 {Initiating a
favourable exchange.} (9. O-O O-O-O 10. Ng5 Nd7 11. Kh1 f6 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13.
Ne2 Rhf8 (13... g6 $5) 14. Qe1 g6 15. b4 Bd6 16. Be3 f5 17. f3 f4 18. Bg1 g5
19. Qf2 b6 20. Rfb1 h5 21. a4 g4 {, and Black went on to win in Motylev, A 
(2686)-Jakovenko,D (2747) Yaroslavl 2014 (, again with a pawn on a7, rather
than on a6).}) 9... Nd7 10. Bxc5 Nxc5 11. Qd2 {This position seems like
nothing special for White, and if Black gets to play Nd7 and c5, he will have
easy equality. So the next two moves seem like the only ambitious alternative.}
({After} 11. O-O O-O-O {White regrets having played h3, when Black launches
the g-pawn.}) 11... Nd7 12. d4 $1 ({I don't see a good way for White to change
the pawn structure after} 12. O-O-O c5 {One can try a plan with f4, but it
will only give Black a good square for the knight on e5.}) 12... exd4 13. Nxd4
c5 {Anand is in a hurry to simplify into the endgame, which he estimates to be
simpler to defend.} (13... O-O-O 14. O-O-O Qe7 15. Qe3 Kb8 16. f4) 14. Nxe6
fxe6 15. O-O-O Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 $1 {The king belongs on e3, where it is
centralized and able to support the advance of the kingside pawn majority.} Ne5
17. f4 $1 (17. b3 g5 $1 18. f3 Ke7 19. h4 h6 {is comfortable for Black. White
cannot get a passed pawn without exchanging a lot of material.}) 17... Nc4+ 18.
Kc1 {The king is back where it came from, but the knight is floating without a
strong square.} Ke7 19. b3 Nd6 $1 20. e5 Nf5 21. Ne4 (21. g4 {looks stronger,
as it avoids the blockade of the pawns.} Nd4 (21... Nh4 $2 {fails to tactics:}
22. f5 $1 exf5 23. Nd5+ Kf7 24. e6+ $1 $18 Kg6 25. Nxc7) 22. Rhf1 Rhf8 23. Rf2
b6 24. Rdf1 {, which looks like a promising position for White,}) 21... b6 22.
g4 Nh4 $1 {The advantage of this square for the knight is that there are no
pieces that can push it away.} (22... Nd4 23. Rhf1 {is similar to the line
above.}) 23. Rhf1 Rad8 $6 (23... Rhf8 {holds the balance without too much
difficulty:} 24. Rf2 (24. Rd2 h6 25. Kd1 Rad8) 24... h6 25. Rfd2 (25. Ng3 Rad8
26. Nh5 Rxd1+ 27. Kxd1 g5 $1) 25... Rad8 $1 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Rxd8 Kxd8 28. Kd2
Ng2 29. f5 exf5 30. gxf5 Nh4 31. Ng3 Nf3+ 32. Ke3 Nxe5 33. Kf4 Nc6 34. Nh5 Ke7
35. Nxg7 Nb4 $11) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. f5 $1 {A very important achievement.} exf5
26. gxf5 Rf8 (26... Rd5 27. Rf4 Ng2 28. f6+ gxf6 29. exf6+ Kf8 $1 (29... Kf7
30. Rg4 Re5 31. Rg7+ Ke8 32. Ng5 $18) 30. Rg4 Rd4 31. Rxg2 Rxe4 32. Rg7 c4 33.
Rxc7 cxb3 34. axb3 Rh4 35. Rc6 b5 36. Rxa6 Rxh3 {, and Black is struggling.})
27. f6+ gxf6 28. exf6+ Kf7 $6 (28... Kd7 $1 29. Rg1 h6 30. Rg7+ Kc6 31. Rh7 Kd5
32. Nc3+ Kd4 33. Na4 Rxf6 34. Rxc7 Ng6 $14) 29. Rf4 (29. Rg1 $1 {looks much
better. The point is that} Rg8 30. Ng5+ Kxf6 31. Nxh7+ Kf7 32. Rxg8 Kxg8 33.
Nf6+ Kf7 34. Nd5 {is winning for White.}) 29... Ng6 30. Ng5+ Ke8 31. Rf1 h6 32.
Ne6 Rf7 33. Rd1 $1 Rxf6 (33... Rd7 34. Ng7+ Kd8 35. Nf5 Rxd1+ 36. Kxd1 Kd7 37.
Nxh6 Nf4 38. h4 Ke6 39. f7 Ke7 40. Kd2 Ng2 41. h5 Nf4 42. Ke3 Nxh5 43. Ke4 Nf6+
44. Kf5 $18) 34. Nxc7+ Kf8 35. Nxa6 Nf4 36. h4 Ng6 37. Rh1 Rf7 38. h5 $2 (38.
a4 $1 Ra7 39. Nb8 Rb7 40. Nc6 Rc7 41. Rf1+ Rf7 42. Re1 Nxh4 43. Rh1 {There is
no good way to hold on to the pawn:} Nf5 44. Ne5 Rg7 45. Nc4 $1 Rg6 $2 46. Rf1
$18) 38... Nf4 39. a4 Ke7 40. Nc7 Kf6 41. Nb5 Kg5 {Black has almost managed to
equalize.} 42. Nd6 Re7 43. Kb2 Re6 (43... Nxh5 $1 44. Rg1+ Kf6 45. Rh1 Kg6 46.
Rg1+ Kf6 {is equal.}) 44. Nf7+ Kf5 45. Rd1 $1 {To help the knight's return to
the queenside.} Kg4 46. Kc3 Kxh5 47. Rh1+ Kg6 48. Nxh6 {So White is a pawn up
again, but the knight is misplaced. Black needs to find a way to create a net
that will keep it from getting out.} Re4 $1 {This stops the king from
advancing further and keeps an eye on g4,} 49. Kb2 (49. Rh2 Nd5+ 50. Kb2 c4 $11
) 49... Re2 $1 50. Ng4 Nd3+ $6 {Another slight mistake puts Black under
pressure again.} (50... Kf5 $1 {was the way to keep the knight in the cage:}
51. Nh6+ Kg6 52. Kb1 Nd5 53. Ng4 Kg5 54. Rg1 Kf4 {, and there is not way for
White to gain coordination.}) 51. Kc3 Nb4 $6 (51... Ne1 $1 52. Rh2 Re4 53. Nf2
Re2 54. Kc4 Rxc2+ 55. Kb5 c4 56. bxc4 Rb2+ 57. Kc6 Nf3 58. Rg2+ Kf7 59. Kb7 Ne5
$11) 52. Rh2 $1 Rxh2 53. Nxh2 Kf5 54. Nf3 Ke4 55. Ne1 Kd5 56. Nd3 Nc6 (56...
Na2+ 57. Kb2 Nb4 58. c4+ $1 (58. Nxb4+ $2 cxb4 59. c3 bxc3+ 60. Kxc3 Kc5 $11)
58... Ke4 59. Nxb4 cxb4 60. Kc2 Kd4 61. Kd2 Ke4 62. Ke2 Kd4 63. Kf3 Kc3 64. a5
$1 bxa5 65. c5 Kxb3 66. c6 {, and White wins.}) 57. Nf4+ $1 Kd6 (57... Ke5 $2 {
loses to} 58. Kc4 $1 Kxf4 (58... Na7 59. Nd5) 59. Kb5 Nb4 60. Kxb6 Nxc2 61. a5
Nb4 62. Kxc5 {, and the knight is unable to stop both pawns.}) 58. Kc4 Na7 59.
Nd5 Kc6 60. Ne7+ Kd6 61. Nf5+ Kc6 62. Kd3 Kc7 (62... b5 $1 {Exchanging one of
the pawns.}) 63. Ke4 Nc6 64. Ne3 Kd6 65. Nc4+ Kc7 66. c3 Ne7 67. Ke5 Ng6+ 68.
Kf5 Ne7+ 69. Ke6 Ng6 {On the one hand, Black's position is awful, but on the
other; there is no way for White to go forward.} 70. a5 b5 $4 {A terrible
blunder in a drawn position.} (70... bxa5 $1 71. Kd5 (71. Nxa5 Nf4+ 72. Ke5 Ne2
73. c4 Kb6 $11 74. b4) 71... Nf4+ 72. Kxc5 Ne2 73. Na3 Nc1 74. Kc4 Kb6 75. Nc2
Ne2 76. Nd4 (76. Ne3 Nc1) 76... Nf4 77. Nf5 Ne6 {, and there is no way for
White to make progress.}) 71. Ne3 Nf4+ 72. Ke5 Ne2 73. Nd5+ Kc6 74. b4 Nxc3 75.
Nxc3 cxb4 76. Ne2 {A rather tragic end to an exciting game.} 1-0

[Event "RUS-chT"]
[Site "Dagomys"]
[Date "2008.04.04"]
