[EventDate "2008.04.02"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

{The following game is an amazing performance by Dmitry Andreikin, and it
confirms his image of being an acknowledged endgame expert. It is an
instructive tool to learn the extraction of small advantages and play on both
wings. The main qualities of a good endgame player are patience and accuracy.} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Qd6 $5
8. Nbd2 Be6 9. b3 Nd7 10. Bb2 c5 $1 {To stop d3-d4.} 11. Nc4 $5 {The only
active plan for White is to prepare f4. But Black hasn't castled yet and it
may be a risky affair. You can check game 10 to see how Leko treats this kind
of position.} (11. a4 O-O-O $5 12. Nc4 Bxc4 13. bxc4 g5 14. Nd2 h5 15. Re1 g4
16. Nf1 Qe6 17. Ne3 Bg5 18. Nf5 Nb8 $11) 11... Bxc4 12. dxc4 O-O ({The queen
exchange would significantly simplify Black task.} 12... Qxd1 13. Raxd1 f6 14.
Nh4 g6 15. g3 O-O-O 16. Ng2 Nb8 17. Ne3 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Nc6 $11) 13. Qd5 $5 {
Now Black would have to exchange queens under much worse circumstances. In the
arising pawn structure White has more chances to exert pressure} Qxd5 14. cxd5
Bd6 15. Nd2 $1 {The knight gains access to the excellent square c4.} b5 {
This move creates long term problems with defending against a penetration on
the a-file} 16. a4 $1 Rfb8 17. Bc3 Nb6 18. Ba5 Nd7 19. Bc3 Nb6 20. Rfb1 Kf8 21.
Kf1 f6 22. Ba5 Nd7 23. Ra2 Ke8 {Black has no active counterplay and his only
chance is to create a fortress.} 24. Rba1 Rc8 25. Bc3 Nb6 26. Ke2 Rcb8 27. Ba5
Nc8 28. Nf1 Kd7 29. Ne3 Bf8 30. f3 Bd6 {White managed the best setup, which
gives him the option to start playing on the other wing. Black's pieces are
tied up for defending the a-file.} 31. h4 $1 Rb7 $6 {A small inaccuracy which
gives White full control of the open file.} (31... h5 32. Be1 Nb6 33. axb5 axb5
34. g4 hxg4 35. fxg4 Rxa2 36. Rxa2 Rh8 37. Ra5 b4 38. Kd3) 32. Bd2 Rab8 (32...
b4 {also looks like a desperate decision.}) 33. axb5 axb5 34. h5 Ne7 35. Ra6 h6
$6 {One more inaccuracy and Black is lost because of the weakness of his
kingside pawns} 36. Kf2 Rb6 37. Rxb6 cxb6 38. Ra7+ Bc7 39. Kg3 Nc8 40. Ra2 Bd6
41. Nf5 Bf8 42. f4 $1 {Last stage - penetration and collection of the
weaknesses.} b4 43. fxe5 fxe5 44. Bc1 Nd6 45. Ra7+ Rb7 46. Rxb7+ Nxb7 47. Bb2
Na5 48. Bxe5 c4 49. bxc4 Nxc4 50. Bf4 Na3 51. e5 Nxc2 52. e6+ Ke8 53. d6 b3 54.
Be5 Nb4 55. Bxg7 Nd5 56. d7+ Kd8 57. Bxf8 b2 58. Bxh6 1-0

[Event "Dortmund SuperGM 34th"]
[Site "Dortmund"]
[Date "2006.08.04"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Game 10"]
[Black "Leko, P - Aronian"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "125"]
[EventDate "2006.07.29"]
[EventRounds "7"]
[EventCountry "GER"]
[EventCategory "19"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {The Exchange Variation has never been
too popular at top level. True, in a famous game played at Sankt Petersburg in
1914, Lasker used it to defeat his direct rival Capablanca, while in the late
'60s Fischer obtained a couple of fine wins with it, but in principle the
early capture on c6 has remained a surprise weapon.} dxc6 5. O-O Be7 $5 6. d3 (
{Having defended the e-file with the bishop, Black is ready to meet} 6. Nxe5 {
with} Qd4 {followed by ...Qxe4. Practice has shown that the lively play that
follows tends to lead to approximate equality.}) 6... Bf6 7. Nbd2 {White
concentrates his forces against the e5-pawn.} Ne7 8. Nc4 Ng6 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2
Re8 11. h3 a5 ({Black should better preserve the possibility of driving the
c4-knight away with ...b5 by playing} 11... c5 12. a4 b6) 12. a4 c5 13. Kh1 $1
{The start of White's preparations of the thematic break f4.} b6 14. Bc3 Be6 $1
{With the intention to exchange the knight and release the pressure on the
central point e5.} 15. Nh2 {The e5-pawn is poisoned.} (15. Nfxe5 $2 Bxc4) (15.
Ncxe5 Bxb3 16. Nc6 Qd6 17. e5 Qxc6 18. exf6 Bd5 19. fxg7 Nf4 $40) 15... Bxc4
16. bxc4 (16. dxc4 {will be too drawish.}) 16... Qd7 17. Qg4 $1 {A typical
idea - the exchange of queens is in White's favour, so White wins control over
this important post.} Qc6 18. g3 $1 Nf8 19. f4 exf4 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. gxf4 {
The situation becomes dangerous for Aronian and he changes his opinion and
offers a transposition into the endgame.} Qg6 22. f5 Qxg4 23. hxg4 f6 $14 {
White has an obvious advantage, but converting it into something more concrete
is anything but easy. Leko's strategy during the next 30 moves is in
accordance with the good old Soviet School regarding the conversion of minimal
but stable advantages, when the opponent has hardly any counterplay. He will
manoeuvre with his pieces in such a way that it creates small illusory threats.
Only when the opponent will be tired and somewhat confused about what the true
intentions are, will he opt for the opening of the centre with d4.} 24. Nf3
Rad8 25. Kg2 Rd6 26. Kg3 Nd7 27. Kf4 h6 28. Ke3 Kf7 29. Rad1 Rc6 30. Rg1 Re7
31. Rd2 Rd6 32. Rdd1 Rc6 33. Rde1 Rd6 34. Rg2 Rc6 35. Rb1 Rd6 36. Ng1 Ne5 37.
Ne2 Re8 38. Nc3 Rd4 39. Kf4 Rd7 40. Nd5 Nc6 41. Ke3 Ne5 42. Nc3 Rd6 43. Ne2 Rd7
44. Kf4 Red8 45. Ng1 Rd6 46. Nf3 {An interesting moment - White offers to
enter a rook endgame, which Black declines.} Nd7 $1 (46... Nxf3 47. Kxf3 Re8
48. Rd2 {, and White simply prepares the advance of the central pawns - d3-d4
and e4-e5.}) 47. Re1 Re8 48. Rge2 Re7 49. Ke3 Re8 50. Rd1 Rd8 51. Red2 Ke7 52.
Kf4 Re8 53. Ke3 Rd8 54. c3 {Finally a pawn move, preparing d4.} Ne5 {Now it is
Black who offers the exchange of the knights.} 55. Nxe5 fxe5 56. d4 Kf6 57.
dxe5+ $2 {This move brought Leko the deserved victory, but it may be not the
strongest one.} ({White would have increased his advantage with} 57. d5 $1 Kg5
58. Rh1 Rf8 59. Rg2 {, followed by Rh5+ and g5+. Once a rook is installed on
g6, Black's position becomes hopeless.}) 57... Kxe5 58. Rd5+ Rxd5 59. cxd5 ({
The pawn endgame is obviously lost for White.} 59. Rxd5+ Rxd5 60. exd5 (60.
cxd5 c4 $19) 60... h5 $1) 59... b5 $4 {An incredible blunder at such a high
level. It may be that Aronian lost the psychological fight and already
considered his position to be hopeless.} (59... Re8 $2 60. d6 $1) (59... Rd6 $1
{A simple waiting move was just enough to hold the position.} 60. c4 Rd8 61.
Rh1 Rd7 62. Rh5 Rd8 ({The only trick Black has to avoid is} 62... Rd6 $4 63.
f6+ $1 Kxf6 64. e5+ $18) 63. g5 hxg5 64. Rxg5 Rh8 65. Rxg7 Rh3+ 66. Kd2 Kxe4
67. Rxc7 Kxf5) 60. axb5 $18 a4 61. Kd3 Kd6 62. Ra1 Ra8 63. Ra3 1-0

[Event "EU-chT (Men) 16th"]
[Site "Heraklion"]
