1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 (6. d4 {offers
White nothing special - see game 11.}) 6... Bf6 $1 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. d4 (8. b3 O-O
9. Nc4 Ng6 10. Bb2 Re8 11. a4 b6 {, and the only way for White to make
progress is the thorough preparation of f2-f4.}) 8... Ng6 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5
Bxe5 11. Qh5 Bf6 12. Nf3 O-O 13. Bg5 Bxg5 14. Qxg5 Qxg5 15. Nxg5 Re8 16. Rfe1
f6 17. Nf3 Bg4 18. Nd2 Rad8 19. Nf1 {We already saw many endgames like this
with knight against bishop. I believe that White doesn't have an advantage,
but Black lacks an active plan. White is playing practically with a draw in
the pocket and can thus play a "cat and mouse" game for a long time.} a5 20. f3
Be6 21. a3 f5 {Still this move doesn't spoil anything, but Black can do better
without it.} (21... c5 22. Kf2 Rd4 23. c3 Rd3 24. Red1 Red8 25. Ne3 Bb3 26.
Rxd3 Rxd3 27. Ke2 Rd6 28. g4 Kf7 29. h4 Rb6 30. Rc1 a4 $11) 22. Kf2 f4 $1 {
Sokolov is an 1.e4 e5 expert, and I believe he knows what he is doing. He
chooses the more ambitious attempt, as the normal way would give White an
easy-to-play position.} (22... Kf7 23. exf5 Bxf5 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. Ne3 Be6 26.
Rd1 Ke7 27. h4 $14) 23. g3 (23. h4 h6 24. h5 Bf7 25. g3 fxg3+ 26. Nxg3 Re5 27.
Rad1 Rf8 $132) 23... g5 24. h4 h6 25. hxg5 hxg5 26. Rad1 Kf7 $1 {The king may
find an excellent post on e5!} (26... c5 27. gxf4 gxf4 28. Nh2 Kf7 29. Ng4 c4
30. Ne5+ Kf6 31. Ng4+ Kg7 32. Rg1 Rxd1 33. Rxd1 Rh8 $132) 27. Rd2 Rd6 {With
this move Black maintains equality, but I believe he could have played for
more.} (27... Kf6 28. Red1 (28. b3 Ke5) 28... Rxd2+ 29. Rxd2 Rh8 $15) 28. Red1
Red8 29. gxf4 gxf4 30. Rxd6 cxd6 31. Nd2 Rh8 32. Ke2 Rh2+ 33. Kd3 b5 {At this
point the position is equal, but it is White who has to be careful.} 34. b3 b4
{Releasing White's rook.} ({It was better to improve the position with} 34...
c5 $5) 35. axb4 axb4 36. Ra1 c5 37. Ra6 Ke7 38. Rb6 Rf2 39. Rb7+ Kf6 40. Rh7 d5
41. Rh6+ Kf7 42. Rh7+ Kf6 43. Rh6+ Ke7 (43... Kf7 {would be an immediate draw.}
) 44. Rh7+ Bf7 45. exd5 Kf8 $2 (45... Ke8 {would still suffice for a draw.} 46.
Rh8+ Kd7 47. Ne4 Bg6 48. Kc4 Rxc2+ 49. Kb5 Bxe4 50. fxe4 f3 51. Rf8 f2 52. e5
c4 53. Kxb4 cxb3 54. Kxb3 Rc5 55. Rxf2 Rxd5 $11) 46. Rh8+ Kg7 47. d6 $1 {
Black missed this trick.} Be6 48. Rh5 Kf7 49. Rxc5 Ke8 50. Rb5 Kd7 51. Rxb4 {
The defensive idea with f5-f4 is very original and worth remembering. It
solves all black problems and even gives him the more pleasant position.} 1-0

