[EventCountry "MKD"]

{You may get the impression that White is playing with a draw in the pocket
and that all of the lines with the Spanish exchange pawn structure are the
perfect weapon to make a draw against a stronger opponent. Before drawing this
conclusion, take a look at the following game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Be7 {The idea of this move is revealed later in the game.
Black likes to avoid f7-f6} 6. d4 {White is playing for equality, but} ({
Black's task would be more complicated in case of} 6. Nxe5 Qd4 7. Qh5 g6 8. Nf3
Qxe4 9. Qa5 Bg4 10. Re1 Qd5 11. Qxc7 Bxf3 12. Re5 Qd7 13. Qxd7+ Kxd7 14. gxf3
Bd6 $44 {Skoberne,J -Borisek,J Ljubljana 2007}) 6... exd4 7. Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4
Bd7 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Be3 {In this well-known position, Adams comes up with a
new and very original plan.} h5 $5 {Black's idea is to immobilize White's pawn
majority, an idea similar to the minority attack in the Queen's Gambit.} 11.
Nf3 {White is trying to hold the advance of the pawns.} (11. Rad1 Nh6 12. f3 g5
13. Nde2 f5 14. Bd4 Rhg8 $1 {would be the ideal realisation of Black's plan.})
11... Nh6 12. Ne5 Be8 13. Rad1 Rxd1 14. Rxd1 Ng4 $1 15. Nxg4 {This is exactly
what White shouldn't do. The pawn g4 will effectively neutralise White's pawn
majority.} (15. Bf4 g5) (15. Bd4 c5 16. Nd5 cxd4 17. Nxe7+ Kd8 18. Nxg4 Kxe7
$15) 15... hxg4 16. Ne2 f6 17. Ng3 g6 18. Bd4 c5 19. Bc3 Bc6 20. f4 {Sooner or
later White has to move the f-pawn, creating irreparable weaknesses.} gxf3 21.
gxf3 b5 22. b3 Kb7 23. f4 b4 24. Bb2 c4 $1 {A typical way of advancing the
pawn majority on the queenside.} 25. bxc4 Bc5+ 26. Kg2 Rh4 27. Bxf6 (27. Rf1 f5
28. Bf6 Rh7 29. Re1 Bd6 30. Be5 Rh4 $17) 27... Rxf4 28. Rf1 Bxe4+ 29. Nxe4 Rxe4
{The game is practically over - White's pawns are doomed to fall one after
another.} 30. c3 a5 31. cxb4 axb4 32. Rb1 Kc6 33. Rb2 Rxc4 34. Kf3 Bd6 35. Ke3
Rg4 36. h4 Kb5 37. Bg5 Ka4 38. Kf3 Rc4 39. Rg2 Ka3 40. Bd8 Rf4+ 41. Ke3 Rf8 42.
Bg5 Bc5+ 43. Kd3 Rf2 44. Bc1+ Kxa2 45. Rxg6 Bd6 46. Rg8 Rf3+ 47. Ke4 Rh3 48.
Bg5 b3 49. Bf6 b2 50. Rg2 Ba3 51. Kd5 Kb3 52. Rg1 c5 53. Rh1 0-1

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pawn Structure 1"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[Variant "illegal"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "8/1pp2ppp/p1p5/8/3PP3/8/PP3PPP/8 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{This structure appears when White advances his central pawns. When Black
trades on d4, White enjoys a pair of strong central pawns, but this is not the
end of the story. Black can achieve excellent chances by exerting pressure on
both semi-open files or by launching the f5-break. The main aim for Black is
to provoke the further advance of the e4-pawn, when Black will install a
blockade on the light squares. The plan with long castle will further increase
the pressure and create one more dangerous idea - the pawn storm g5-g4. My
conclusion is that this kind of structure is quite dangerous for White, as he
has not enough resources to protect his central pawns. Very often White is the
first to take on e5 and reconcile himself with equality.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
