[FEN "7r/1pp2ppp/p1p5/8/4PP2/8/PPP3PP/8 w - - 0 14"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{This is the most frequently seen pawn structure in the Exchange Spanish.
After trading the pawns, White creates an effective majority on the kingside.
In my view, White's best chance lies in a complicated middlegame, where he can
transform the dynamic force of his pawns e4 and f4 into dangerous pressure on
the kingside. In the endgame, the white pawn e4 may become an easy target for
Black's pieces.}  *

[Event "La Habana (ol)"]
[Site "La Habana (ol) 2/236"]
[Date "1966.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Game 1"]
[Black "Fischer, R- Gligoric"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "49"]
[EventDate "1966.??.??"]

{This is a model game for White regarding the structure # 1 with central pawns
d4, e4. It may seem that everything was crystal clear, but after going a bit
deeper, we can see that it wasn't such a one-sided affair. Gligoric missed a
couple of better options to turn the situation in his favour} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 (5... Bg4 $5 {is one of the most critical
options - see the theoretical section.}) 6. d4 Bg4 $5 {This move leads to a
more complicated fight than} (6... exd4 7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nb3 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 {
, with a risk-free endgame for White.}) 7. c3 $1 (7. dxe5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 9.
Rd3 {is another Fischer speciality, which he introduced a year later against
Smyslov in Monte Carlo 1967.}) 7... exd4 {Now structure #1 appears, but it
might be safer to preserve the tension in the centre.} (7... Bd6) ({or even} 
7... Qe7 $5 {, introduced by Ivanchuk in 2011 (see game 3).}) 8. cxd4 Qd7 $5 {
Preparing to castle long, increasing the pressure on d4. Gligoric is an
acknowledged expert of the Spanish with both colours, and he knows what he is
doing, as he is inviting Fischer into a sharp position with castling on
opposite sides.} ({It is too early for} 8... c5 9. h3 $1 Bh5 10. Qb3 $1 {
Volokitin,A -Bromberger, S Austria 2014}) ({Taking the pawn is way too risky:} 
8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qxd4 10. Rd1 Qc5 11. Bf4 $36) 9. h3 {Solving the issue of
the pin, but otherwise a doubtful decision, as it gives Black the motif g5-g4.}
Be6 $1 (9... Bh5 10. Ne5 $14 {led to a somewhat better endgame in Fischer,
R-Jimenez,E/Habana ol/1966.}) ({Taking the pawn with} 9... Bxf3 $6 {is
suicidal.} 10. Qxf3 Qxd4 11. Rd1 Qc5 12. Be3 Qa5 13. Nd2 $18) 10. Nc3 O-O-O {
We arrived at the most critical position of the game. White's attack seems to
be quicker. Fischer needs only a couple of natural moves like Bf4, Rc1 Na4,
and he will be ready to finish off Black with d4-d5. But things are not as
easy as it seems. Black could have emphasized White's weak point, the position
of the pawn on h3, which may serve as a lever to open the g-file with g5-g4.}
11. Bf4 {Fischer confidently develops the bishop under the direct attack with
g5. It would be safer to play} (11. Be3 {, but even here Black had good
counterchances after} g5 12. Rc1 g4 $1 ({In the game Rozentalis, E-Sosnicki,M
Lubniewice 1998 Black delayed this move and was immediately punished} 12... h5
$2 13. d5 $1 cxd5 14. Qd4 $1 $18) 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. d5 Qg7 15. Qe2 Ne7 {
, and the pressure on the g-file may become threatening.}) 11... Ne7 $6 {
With this move Gligoric gives up the psychological fight, missing the moment
to grab the initiative. In such positions, the first who manages to create
threats usually has the advantage.} ({I don't think that a modern player would
ever miss} 11... g5 $1 12. Bg3 (12. Bh2 g4 $1 ({There is no time for} 12... h5
13. d5 cxd5 14. Na4 $1) 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Rc1 Qg7 15. Na4 Bd6) 12... h5 13. d5
h4 $1 14. Bh2 Bxh3 $1 {Black is the first to hit the opponent.} 15. gxh3 Qxh3
16. Nd4 Bc5 $1 17. Qf3 (17. Nf5 g4) 17... Qxf3 18. Nxf3 g4 19. Nxh4 Rxh4 20.
dxc6 bxc6 {, and the endgame is clearly in Black's favour.}) 12. Rc1 Ng6 13.
Bg3 Bd6 {Gligoric neutralises the dangerous bishop, but the defensive measures
are sufficient only to postpone White's attack for a while. Black missed his
golden chance for active counterplay.} 14. Na4 $1 Bxg3 ({It was necessary to
try} 14... Qf7 $5 {, with the idea} 15. Qe2 Rhe8 16. Bxd6 Rxd6 17. Nc5 Bxh3 $1
$40) 15. fxg3 Kb8 (15... b6 $6 16. d5 $1 $18) 16. Nc5 Qd6 17. Qa4 Ka7 $4 {
A blunder, which significantly accelerates the defeat. Black could have
prolonged resistance with} (17... Bc8 18. Rc3 Nf8 19. e5 Qd5 20. Qb4 Ka7 {
, keeping the head over water for a while.}) 18. Nxa6 $18 {It is difficult to
say why Gligoric missed such an easy hit.} Bxh3 (18... bxa6 19. Rxc6) 19. e5 $1
Nxe5 (19... fxe5 20. Nc5+ Kb8 21. Rc3 $1) 20. dxe5 fxe5 21. Nc5+ Kb8 22. gxh3
e4 23. Nxe4 Qe7 24. Rc3 b5 25. Qc2 1-0

[Event "URS-ch41 Final"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1973.10.20"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Game 2"]
[Black "Smyslov - Geller"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "76"]
[EventDate "1973.10.02"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "URS"]
[EventCategory "13"]

{The 41st championship of the USSR in 1973 wasn't the most memorable for
Smyslov and Geller, both remaining far behind the winner Spassky. Playing the
Exchange Spanish four rounds before the end of the tournament and far from the
leading group sounds more like a draw offer than an invitation for a hand to
hand combat. But Geller introduced a new idea on move 11, showing that his
fighting spirit was still awake.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5.
O-O f6 6. d4 Bg4 7. c3 (7. dxe5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 9. Rd3 {would be much safer
if White wishes to play for equality.}) 7... Bd6 8. Be3 Qe7 $5 {Preparing to
castle long, raising the tension against the d4-pawn.} ({The modern treatment
of the line is} 8... Ne7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Qb3+ Kh8 11. h3 Bh5 $1 {Naiditsch,A
-Saric,I Germany 2014} 12. dxe5 (12. Qxb7 Bf7 $1) 12... fxe5 13. Qxb7 Qd7 14.
Qb3 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 Rxf3 16. gxf3 Ng6 $44) 9. Nbd2 {There is no other way to
employ the knight, as the c3-square is occupied.} O-O-O {As in the previous
game, Black castles long, exerting immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. Efim
Geller is delaying the exchange ...exd4 for a while, which is the right way to
play, as it prevents the knight from coming to c3 and keeps the c-file closed.}
10. Qc2 ({In case of} 10. Re1 {, Black can increase the pressure with} exd4 11.
cxd4 Bb4 $1 {, planning to transfer the bishop to b6.}) 10... exd4 11. cxd4 (
11. Nxd4 {looks safer, but after} c5 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 Qd7 14. Ne4 Ne7 {
Black was already better in Nisipeanu,L Grischuk,A Germany 2002.}) 11... Re8 $1
{This was Geller's home preparation. Black suddenly redirects the pressure to
the e4-pawn.} 12. e5 $6 {This is exactly what Black wants to see, as he can
now establish full control over the light squares. Instead White had to ignore
the threat of Bf3 and continue} (12. Rfc1 $1 {, without fearing} Bxf3 13. gxf3
g5 (13... Qf7 14. Nc4 Qg6+ 15. Kf1 Bxh2 16. Na5 $40) 14. Nc4 $1 Nh6 15. Qb3 Qe6
{, and now enter Fischer's footsteps:} 16. d5 $1 cxd5 17. exd5 Qe7 18. Bb6 $18
{Fressinet,L -Gustafsson,J playchess.com INT 2004}) 12... Bb4 $15 {Geller
refuses the pawn sacrifice, as this will give White some initiative, which is
the most important factor in positions like this.} (12... fxe5 13. dxe5 Bxe5
14. Rfe1 $44) 13. h3 (13. Qa4 Bxd2 $1 14. Nxd2 Be6 {would be fine for Black,
who has the better bishop and control over the important d5-square.}) 13... Be6
$1 {Preserving the bishop pair.} (13... Bh5 $4 14. Qf5+) (13... Bxd2 14. Nxd2
Be6 15. f4 Bd5 16. Nb1 $1 $13) 14. Ne4 (14. a3 Bxd2 15. Nxd2 Bd5 $17) 14... Qf7
{Freeing the e7-square for the knight.} ({Also possible was the simple} 14...
Bd5 $5 15. a3 Ba5 16. b4 Bb6 17. Rac1 Qe6 18. Rfe1 Ne7 {, with an excellent
position for Black.}) 15. a3 Bb3 16. Qb1 (16. Neg5 fxg5 17. Nxg5 Bxc2 18. Nxf7
Bb3 19. Nxh8 Ba5 $17) 16... Bf8 (16... Ba5 $1 {The bishop will be more useful
on b6.} 17. Nc5 Bd5 18. b4 Bb6 19. a4 Ne7 $40) 17. Ned2 Bd5 {White misplayed
the pawn structure by e4-e5, falling under heavy pressure. Black now only
needs to complete development and his attack on the kingside will decide the
game.} 18. b4 Qg6 $5 {An unexpected decision, but in the endgame White will
have no active plan.} 19. Qb2 {in the endgame, Black's bishop on d5 would be
ruling the board, when White's pieces were too passive to organize counterplay.
} Ne7 20. a4 Nf5 21. Rfe1 (21. b5 {is not dangerous at all and should be met
with} a5 $1 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Rfb1 Bb4 $19 {The opening of the b-file is not
at all significant.}) 21... fxe5 22. dxe5 Be7 23. Re2 Rhf8 24. Bc5 {It is
really difficult to offer advice.} (24. b5 Nxe3 25. Rxe3 a5 26. Qd4 Bb4 $19)
24... Bxc5 25. bxc5 Nd4 $1 26. Qxd4 Rxf3 27. Ne4 $6 (27. Qg4+ Qxg4 28. hxg4 Rf4
29. f3 Rb4 30. Nf1 {was the last chance to defend in a difficult endgame.})
27... Rxh3 $19 28. Ng3 Rh5 29. Rae1 Rg5 30. Rb2 Rg4 31. Qc3 h5 32. Reb1 h4 33.
Rxb7 hxg3 34. f3 Qh6 35. Rxc7+ Kxc7 36. Qa5+ Kd7 37. e6+ Kxe6 38. Qe1+ Kf6 {
Amazing game - another legendary player lost without a fight as White in the
Spanish Exchange.} 0-1

[Event "Gibraltar Masters 9th"]
[Site "Caleta"]
[Date "2011.02.02"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Game 3"]
[Black "Caruana - Ivanchuk"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C69"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "82"]
[EventDate "2011.01.25"]
[EventRounds "10"]
[EventCountry "GGB"]

{This game was played in round 9 of 2011 Gibraltar open - one of the strongest
events of the year. It was decisive for the distribution of the first places.} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O f6 ({In the previous round
Rapport prefered} 5... Qd6 {, but he wasn't successful - see game 14.}) 6. d4
Bg4 7. c3 (7. dxe5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 9. Rd3 {is very safe for White, but
doesn't offer many winning chances.}) 7... Qe7 {An extremely rare move,
prepared by Ivanchuk for this game. Practically it may be considered a novelty,
as there were played only a couple of correspondence games before that.} 8.
dxe5 $5 {Simple solution! Caruana avoids the unnecessary burden of defending
the central pawns, which, as we can see from the previous game, brings White
nothing but trouble.} (8. Be3 {is natural, but offers no advantage:} exd4 9.
Qxd4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Qe6 11. Nd2 Bd6 {, and White's damaged kingside gives Black
sufficient counterchances.}) (8. h3 Bh5 9. Re1 O-O-O 10. Nbd2 {is a very risky
approach, as White has no plan to match the pawn storm g5-g4.} Nh6) 8... fxe5
9. Re1 $6 {Too slow. Caruana is planning Nbd2-f1-g3 in order to trade Black's
light-squared bishop, but it was more important to stop Black from playing ...
Bc5.} ({Strongest is} 9. Be3 $1 Nf6 10. Nbd2 O-O-O 11. Qc2 {Now White is
planning b4, a4, b5, and Black has to be very accurate.} g5 $5 (11... Qe8 12.
h3 Bh5 {was played in Huschenbeth,N -Naiditsch,A Deizisau 2011, but after} 13.
b4 {Black seems to be far behind in the race.}) 12. Bxg5 Rg8 13. Kh1 Qg7 14.
Rg1 Be7 (14... Bc5) 15. Rae1 Nh5 (15... Rdf8 16. Be3 Nh5) 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Re3
Rdf8 $44 {, and White is a pawn up, but all his pieces are defending.}) 9...
Nf6 10. Nbd2 O-O-O 11. Qe2 Qe6 12. h3 (12. b4 Nh5) 12... Bh5 13. Nf1 ({In case
of} 13. b4 Be7 14. Nf1 (14. a4 Nd7 15. b5 a5 16. Rb1 Rhf8 {leads nowhere.})
14... Rhf8 15. Ng3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 g6 $17 {, White only created a weakness on c4.
}) 13... Bc5 14. Ng3 Rhf8 {Now White is under pressure. All Black's pieces are
aiming at the white king!} 15. Be3 {Trying to trade off some pieces, but the
problem is that Black will gain control over the d-file.} Bxe3 16. Qxe3 Bxf3 $1
17. Qxf3 Rd2 $1 18. Re2 Rfd8 19. Qe3 {Black has succeeded in his occupation of
the d-file.} ({White could have defended better:} 19. Nf1 Rd1 20. Rxd1 Rxd1 21.
Qf5 $1 {The position still looks dangerous, but Black can't create threats
with his rook alone.}) 19... R2d3 $1 {Inviting the queen to a7. It will create
threats but will also be in danger of getting trapped!} 20. Qa7 (20. Qg5 $6 g6
{, and White is suffering because Black dominates the d-file.}) 20... Qc4 $5 (
20... Nd7 21. Nf5 (21. a4 Nb8 $1) 21... g6 22. Ne3 Nb6 23. a4 Rd2 24. Rxd2 Rxd2
25. a5 Nd7 {, and White's pawns are dropping.}) 21. Re3 (21. Qa8+ $4 {loses:}
Kd7 22. Qxb7 Rxg3 23. Rd2+ Rd3 24. Qb3 Qxb3 25. Rxd3+ Ke7 $19) (21. Nf5 {
was also possible. In the ensuing play Black seems to have the upper hand, but
it's highly complex.} g6 22. Ne3 Qb5 23. Ree1 {The endgame arising after} Qb6 (
{Not} 23... Nxe4 $2 24. Ng4 {, and the tables have turned dramatically!}) 24.
Qxb6 cxb6 25. Nc4 {would be about equal.}) 21... Rxe3 22. Qxe3 g6 $1 {Black
just takes the f5-square away from the knight and now White doesn't have a
single useful move!} 23. Qa7 ({An interesting try to create counterplay would
be} 23. Qg5 $5 Qe6 24. Re1 Nd7 25. b3 Nc5 26. Nf1 Rd3 27. Nh2 Rxc3 28. Ng4 Nd7
29. Qd2 Rc5 30. Rd1 {Sacrificing a pawn to take back control of the-file.})
23... Nd7 24. Qe3 {The queen's walk proves unprofitable.} (24. Rd1 $6 Rf8 {
, and due to the dual threats of ...Nb6 and ...Qxa2 White is in serious
trouble.}) 24... Qb5 $1 (24... Nc5 $5 25. b3 Qb5 {was also possible.}) 25. b3
Qc5 $1 {After provoking b3, Black offers a trade of queens.} 26. Qd3 {Avoiding
the trade. Probably a correct decision.} (26. Nf1 Qxe3 27. Nxe3 Nc5 28. f3 Rd3
29. Nc4 Rxc3 30. Nxe5 Rc2 {Next Black will play ...Ne6-d4/f4, and then start
with ...c5, ...b5 and ...c4, creating a passed pawn.}) 26... Nf8 $1 {heading
to the f4-square.} 27. Qc2 Ne6 28. Nf1 $4 {Even top players can crack under
pressure.} (28. Ne2 Qd6 $1 {is very strong. White can't stop ...Qd2.}) (28. Rc1
$1 Nf4 29. Nf1 {would have been a tougher defence. Black is of course clearly
better, but White should hold.}) 28... Nd4 $19 {And that's it. Black wins a
pawn while maintaining full control.} 29. Qd1 (29. Qb2 Qxc3 30. Qxc3 Ne2+ 31.
Kh2 Nxc3 $19) 29... Qxc3 {The rest requires no comments.} 30. Rb1 h5 31. Ne3 b5
32. Qf1 Qd2 33. a3 Rf8 34. Rd1 Qb2 35. b4 Ne2+ 36. Kh2 Nc3 37. Rc1 Rxf2 38. Qe1
Rd2 39. Qf1 Kb7 40. a4 Rf2 41. Qe1 Nxa4 {Right after the occupation of the
centre, Caruana decided to exchange on e5. This might have been the best
decision, as otherwise defending it might have been too heavy a burden to
carry. But even his safe play didn't completely solve his problems. With the
exchange 17... Bxf3 followed by Rd2, Ivanchuk took the strategical initiative
and didn't release the pressure until Caruana blundered a pawn, which
practically decided the game.} 0-1

[Event "Tal Memorial 8th"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "2013.06.19"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Game 4"]
[Black "Anand - Nakamura"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C60"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "90"]
