[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]
[EventCategory "22"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O (4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 Bg7 6. d4 {is the usual
spanish aproach to build a strong centre with c3, d4.}) (4. d4 exd4 5. Bg5 (5.
c3 $5) 5... Be7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. Nc3 Bg4 10. O-O-O {
is considered the mainline.}) 4... Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Bxc6 $5 {A rare move which
Anand played very fast. White obviously wants to avoid the unclear modern line
with c3 and d4, but the position he is heading for is no less complex in a
strategic sense.} (6. Ba4 $1) 6... dxc6 7. d4 {As usual in the Spanish, White
advances his central pawns.} (7. d3 {is too passive. I like Black's plan from
the following game:} Ne7 8. h3 c5 9. Na3 Nc6 10. Bg5 Qd7 (10... f6 $1) 11. Qd2
O-O 12. Rfe1 b6 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. Nc4 f6 15. Bh6 Qf7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. b3 Rfe8
18. Nh2 Rad8 19. f4 b5 $132 {Zagrebelny,S -Margolin,B /Alushta/1994.}) 7...
exd4 $5 {Nakamura takes a risky but dynamic decision in accordance with his
style.} (7... Bg4 8. dxe5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxe5 10. Na3 {leads to an inferior
endgame.}) 8. cxd4 Ne7 {Black's bishop is ideally placed on g7 - pointed
against the weak pawn on d4. But the other black pieces are restricted by the
e4-pawn, so the main resource to create counterplay is a quick f7-f5.} 9. h3 {
A more or less obligatory prophylactic move. In the game Chandler,M-Spassky,B
Vienna/1986, White tried to skip it, but after} (9. Nc3 Bg4 $5 10. Be3 O-O 11.
h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 f5 $1 13. Bg5 {, Black could have equalised by} fxe4 $1 ({
instead of} 13... Qd7 $6) 14. Qxe4 Rf7 15. Rfe1 Qd7 {, and if} 16. Bxe7 $6 Re8
$15) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 h6 {Covering the g5-square and patiently preparing f5.
Although White has a mobile pawn centre, the position is not fully clear, as
advancing the pawns could enhance the strength of Black's bishop pair.} ({
It was possible to play the thematic break} 10... f5 {, and after} 11. Qb3+ Kh8
12. Ng5 Qe8 13. Re1 f4 $1 (13... h6 $2 14. exf5 $16) 14. Ne2 h6 15. Nf3 g5 16.
Bd2 a5 $1 (16... Qh5 17. Bb4) 17. Rac1 Qh5 18. Qa3 Ng6 $132 {Black develops
unpleasant pressure on the kingside.}) 11. Qb3 {Preparing Rd1 to charge the
d-pawn with energy.} ({In case of the standard} 11. Be3 {, Black will hit the
centre with} f5 12. Qd2 (12. Qb3+ Kh8 $13) 12... fxe4 (12... g5 $5 $40) 13. Ne5
(13. Nxe4 $2 Rxf3 $1 14. gxf3 Nf5 $19)) ({I believe that White could have
played much better:} 11. Bf4 $5 g5 12. Be5 f6 13. Bg3 f5 14. exf5 Nxf5 15. Be5
$1 $14) 11... g5 $5 {A dynamic and provocative reaction. Nakamura seeks more
direct counterplay on the kingside.} (11... Qd6 {looks like the natural solid
move, but after} 12. Rd1 Be6 {White has the very strong reply} 13. d5) 12. Rd1
$1 b6 $5 {Preparing Be6, but at the price of creating a potentially vulnerable
pawn on c6. With the rook on d1 the break f5 meets a strong refutation.} (12...
Kh8 13. Be3 f5 14. d5 $1) (12... Be6 $5 {is a very concrete way to solve the
problems with a pawn sacrifice in the style of the Benko Gambit.} 13. d5 (13.
Qxb7 a5 $1 {(/\ Qd7,Rfb8)} 14. d5 $8 cxd5 15. exd5 Rb8 16. Qa7 Nxd5 17. Qxa5 c6
$44 {[%csl Rg7]}) 13... cxd5 14. exd5 Bf5 15. Qxb7 (15. Be3 g4 $5 $132) 15...
Qd6 16. Qb3 Rab8 17. Qc4 Rfe8 $32 {Black has good compensation for the
sacrificed pawn, but it's not easy to opt for such a radical solution.}) 13. a4
$1 {This is the first stage of the genuine attacking plan. With the inclusion
of a4 a5 Black's queenside pawns will be fixed targets and it will create
perfect preconditions for the break d4-d5.} (13. Qc2 {allows} f5 $132) (13. Be3
Qd6 $5 (13... Be6 14. d5 $36) 14. Rac1 Qg6 $132) 13... a5 14. Be3 Ng6 {A risky
decision. Black leaves c6 unattended and releases control over f5.} (14... Qd6
$5 {deserves attention. The queen aims for g6 or even b4. After} 15. d5 g4 $132
{the position remains very unclear.} 16. dxc6 Qxc6 (16... Qb4) 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18.
exd5 Qg6 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. Bd4 Rad8) 15. d5 $5 {Anand is in a hurry to act
directly in the centre instead of attacking the weak pawn on c6. It may seem
that Black's pieces are coming closer to his king, but it was too early to
panic.} ({More dangerous for Black was} 15. Ne2 $1 {, to prepare the attack
against the c6-pawn and to transfer the knight to g3. For example} Qf6 16. Qc2
$1 Bxh3 17. Ne5 $1 $36) (15. Nh2 Qe7 16. Nf1 Qb4 $1 17. Qc2 f5 $1 {would also
be excellent.}) 15... c5 $1 {Now Black enjoys typical counterplay on the dark
squares.} 16. Nb5 {Now the d5-d6 advance is hanging like the sword of Damocles
over the Black position.} g4 $5 {A very dynamic and concrete continuation.} (
16... Ba6 17. d6 (17. Nd2 Qd7 $11) 17... Bxb5 18. dxc7 Qxc7 19. Qxb5 Rfd8 $132
{is roughly balanced - Black's active pieces compensate for the holes in his
pawn structure. Nakamura is more ambitious, though.}) 17. hxg4 Bxg4 18. Bd2 {
A safe move.} (18. d6 $2 {is too risky, although Black needs to find a couple
of precise moves to refute it.} Bxf3 19. gxf3 (19. dxc7 $2 Qh4 20. gxf3 Qh3 $19
) 19... c6 20. Nc7 Qh4 $1 21. Kg2 (21. Nxa8 Qh3 $19) 21... Rad8 22. Qxb6 Be5
23. Qxc6 Qh2+ 24. Kf1 Bd4 $3 $19) 18... Qd7 {, preparing c6.} (18... Ne5 $6 {
looks very strong, but meets a tough refutation.} 19. Nxe5 $1 Bxe5 (19... Bxd1
$2 20. Qg3 $18) 20. f4 $1 Bxd1 21. Rxd1 Bg7 22. e5 {, and White's central
pawns will smash every obstacle on their way.}) (18... Kh7 {, with the idea f5,
would be more in the spirit of his previous play, but Nakamura prefers a safer
approach and makes a couple of useful preparatory moves - Qd7 and Rad8.}) 19.
Rac1 {Loses an important tempo.} ({A more useful move was} 19. Re1 $5 {/\} c6
20. dxc6 Qxc6 21. Nh2 Be6 22. Qc2 $13 Rad8 23. Rad1 f5 24. Bc3 $11) 19... c6 {
The direct continuation, but Black should have first played} (19... Rad8 $1 {
, when after} 20. Re1 c6 21. dxc6 Qxc6 {White would be in great trouble.}) 20.
dxc6 (20. Na3 Rfe8 $5 21. Nc4 Rab8 $36 {, and White has no obvious way to
advantageously retain the central tension.}) 20... Qxc6 21. Bc3 $6 {This could
have cost White an exchange.} (21. Qe3 Rfe8 22. Re1 Bxb2 23. Rb1 Bg7 24. Bc3
$15 {/<=> Black's extra pawn doesn't play a major role yet and White has
counterplay.}) 21... Bxf3 22. gxf3 Rad8 $5 {Nakamura plays for a strategic
advantage.} (22... Nf4 $1 {, with the forced follow-up} 23. Rd6 Qc8 24. Bd2
Ne2+ 25. Kg2 Nxc1 26. Bxc1 {nets Black an exchange. Not a difficult line to
calculate, but the evaluation of the final position is not so simple.
Nevertheless it seems Black has reasonable winning chances after} Rd8 27. Qd5
$5 (27. Rxb6 c4 $17) 27... Rb8 28. Bxh6 Rxd6 29. Qxd6 Bxh6 30. Qxh6 Qe6) 23.
Rxd8 (23. Bxg7 $2 {runs into} Nf4 $1 24. Nd6 Rxd6 $1 25. Bxf8 Rd2 $3 (25...
Rxd1+ $2 26. Rxd1 $16) 26. Kh1 $8 (26. Rxd2 Qg6+ 27. Kf1 Qg2+ 28. Ke1 Qg1#)
26... Qd7 27. Rg1+ Kxf8 28. Rg3 (28. Rg4 Nd3 $19 {is similar.}) 28... Qd8 $1
29. Rg4 Nd3 $19 {Black wins all the material back and the attack continues.})
23... Rxd8 24. Rd1 Rd7 {Fights for the open file, but Black also had the simple
} (24... Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 Bxc3 26. bxc3 (26. Nxc3 Nf4 $36) 26... Qf6 $15 {
The distant passed pawn on h6 gives him an advantage in almost any endgame.})
25. Rxd7 Qxd7 26. Qd5 $6 {Transposing to a knight endgame only increases
Black's advantage.} (26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Qc3+ f6 28. Qe3 h5 29. Kh2 {, and Black
still has to overcome some technical issues.}) 26... Qxd5 27. exd5 Bxc3 28.
bxc3 Ne5 $6 (28... Kf8 $1 {is more flexible and stronger. After} 29. Nd6 {
, Black's knight has an alternative route:} Nf4 $1 30. c4 Ne2+ 31. Kf1 Nc3 $19)
29. Nd6 Kf8 30. Kh2 $2 {Decentralising the king doesn't feel right, moreover
it fails tactically.} ({It is probably insufficient to play} 30. Kf1 b5 $1 31.
Nxb5 (31. axb5 a4 $19) 31... Nc4 $17 {Black will take the a4-pawn and support
one of his passed pawns with his king - he should win this in the long run.}) (
{It seems that the best try was} 30. f4 Nd3 31. Nc8 Nxf4 32. c4 Ke8 33. Nxb6
Kd8 34. d6 Ne6 35. Kg2 Ng7 36. Kh3 Ne8 37. d7 Nf6 38. Kh4 Nxd7 39. Nxd7 Kxd7
40. Kh5 Ke7 41. Kxh6 Kf6 $19) 30... Ke7 $1 31. Nc8+ (31. Nf5+ Kd7 32. Nxh6 b5
33. axb5 a4 $19) 31... Kd7 32. Nxb6+ Kc7 33. f4 Nf3+ 34. Kg2 Nd2 $1 $19 35.
Na8+ Kb7 36. d6 {White must ditch the passed pawn for free to save his knight,
and the resulting endgame is hopeless.} Kc6 37. Nc7 Kxd6 38. Nb5+ Kd5 39. Kg3
Kc4 (39... Nc4 $1 $19 {is simpler.}) 40. Nd6+ (40. f3 f6 $5 41. f5 Nb1 42. Nd6+
Kd3 43. Ne4 c4 44. Nxf6 Nxc3 45. Nd7 Nd5 {/\} 46. f6 Nxf6 $1 47. Nxf6 c3 $19)
40... Kxc3 41. Nxf7 c4 ({An easier win was} 41... Kd4 $1) 42. f5 Kd4 43. Nd6 ({
As} 43. f6 {fails to} Ne4+ {, Black's win is already trivial.}) 43... Ke5 44.
Nb5 Kxf5 45. f3 h5 {A very complicated and double-edged game which revealed
even more strategical and tactical ideas in the structure with White pawns on
d4 and e4.} 0-1

