{Let's take a small break between analysing two of the most complicated games
in this structure.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qd6 (5...
f6 {is the standard continuation. Many people will wonder what the difference
between 5...f6 and 5...Qd6 is. This game might give an answer to this question.
}) 6. c3 $5 {White has a wide choice.} (6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 {, with a balanced
endgame or}) (6. Na3 $5 {, which is his most aggressive option.}) 6... Bg4 7.
d4 exd4 $1 {Now the difference between 5...f6 and 5...Qd6 becomes obvious.
Instead of protecting the centre, Black surrenders it to start exerting
immediate pressure.} 8. cxd4 O-O-O 9. Be3 f5 $1 {Eliminating the e4-pawn will
secure Black total control over the light squares.} 10. e5 {This move is
strategically undesirable for White, but he had nothing better.} (10. exf5 Ne7)
(10. h3 {is also insufficient.} fxe4 11. hxg4 exf3 12. Qxf3 h5 13. gxh5 Nf6 $40
) 10... Qg6 $1 {The ideal square for the queen.} 11. Nc3 (11. Kh1) 11... Ne7
12. Qe2 h6 (12... Qh5 13. Rad1 g5 {would be hopeless for White, who is short
of any useful moves while Black's attack develops by itself.}) 13. Na4 $2 {
Trying to create counterplay with Rac1 and Nc5, but this meets a strong
refutation.} f4 $1 $19 {The hanging knight a4 gave Black a hidden tactical
idea.} 14. Bc1 (14. Bxf4 Rxd4 $19) 14... Rxd4 15. b3 Rd3 $1 16. Kh1 Nf5 17.
Bxf4 Rxf3 $1 {White resigns.} 18. gxf3 Nd4 0-1

