{In the 2014 candidates tournament Karjakin finished second, one point behind
Anand, who won the event with 8,5/14. In this game Karjakin didn't manage to
trouble Aronian in the opening, although he is quite predictable against 1.e4.
} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 $1 {Anti-Berlin} Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O
Re8 $1 (6... d6 7. Nbd2 Ne7 {was Svidler-Anand from the same round, and after}
8. d4 $1 {Black would have been forced to surrender the centre.} exd4 9. cxd4
Bb6 10. Re1 {, and White enjoys full control of the centre.}) 7. Nbd2 $5 (7.
Re1 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 h6 10. Nbd2 Bb6 11. Nf1 d6 12. Ng3 Be6 13. h3 {with
pleasant equality for Black in Carlsen, M -Vitiugov,,N Karlsruhe/Baden-Baden
2018.}) 7... a6 8. Bxc6 $1 {This was the special preparation which failed to
impress.} ({Before Karjakin used to play} 8. Ba4) 8... dxc6 ({Weaker is} 8...
bxc6 $6 9. Nxe5 $1 Rxe5 10. d4) 9. Nc4 (9. Qc2 Bg4 $1 (9... Nd7 10. Nc4 Bd6 11.
d4 Qe7 12. Re1 $14 {Vachier Lagrave,M -Fressinet,L Paris 2016}) 10. h3 Bh5 11.
Re1 Bb6 12. b3 Qd7 13. Bb2 Rad8 14. d4 exd4 15. cxd4 Qe6 $1 $36) 9... Nd7 {
This move leaves White with the option to advance in the centre.} ({The
critical move for the evaluation of the line is} 9... Bg4 $5 10. h3 Bh5 11. Bg5
$1 (11. g4 $2 Nxg4 12. hxg4 Bxg4 $44 13. Kg2 Re6 $40) 11... b5 $1 {The
position is complicated and its evaluation is based on a couple of blitz games
of Nakamura.} ({Note that the normal looking} 11... h6 $6 {is a tactical error,
which should be punished by} 12. Bxf6 $5 Qxf6 13. g4 Bg6 14. Ncxe5 $1 {Caruana,
F -Nakamura,H chess.com INT 2017} Rad8 15. Nxg6 Qxg6 16. Qe2 {, and White is a
pawn up for suspicious compensation.}) 12. Na5 Qd7 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Nb3 Bb6
15. c4 c5 16. g4 Bg6 17. Qe2 Rad8 18. Rad1 Re6 19. Nc1 Rd6 20. b3 a5 21. Nh4 {
, with an amazing situation in which both Black's bishops are buried alive on
b6 and g6. Caruana,F -Nakamura,H Saint Louis 2016}) 10. b4 (10. Re1 b5 $1 (
10... Bf8 11. d4 {was played in Alekseev,E-Godena,M /EU Cup Eilat/ 2012, when
Black's best reaction would be} exd4 12. cxd4 b5 $1 13. Na5 Qf6 $132) 11. Ncxe5
$1 (11. Ne3 Bf8 12. Qc2 c5 $13) (11. Na5 Qf6 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Be3 Bxe3 14. Rxe3
c5 $11) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 13. Kxf2 Rxe5 14. Bf4 Re6 15. Qd2 c5 16. d4
cxd4 17. cxd4 c6 18. d5 cxd5 19. exd5 Rxe1 20. Rxe1 Bf5 21. d6 Rc8) ({It is
too early for} 10. d4 exd4 11. cxd4 Ba7 12. Re1 Nf6 $132) 10... Bd6 ({The
other bishop retreats are also acceptable.} 10... Bf8 11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 {
Shomoev,A -Goganov,A Yekaterinburg/2013/} c5 $1 13. Qb3 Kh8 14. Rfd1 Qe7 $11) (
10... Ba7 11. a4 f6 12. Be3 Nf8 13. h3 Be6 $11) 11. Qb3 {A novelty, directed
against the consolidating f6. Other moves don't promise White anything
tangible:} (11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 Nf8 13. Nfd2 (13. Nh4 g6 14. Nxd6 cxd6 15. Qd2
d5 $15 {Palac,M -Balogh,C BIH-chT Banja Vrucica/2009/}) 13... Be6 14. Nb3 Qd7
15. Qe2 Ng6 16. Rfd1 Bf8 {Rublevsky,S -Kurnosov,I /EU Cup Eilat/2012/}) 11...
Nf8 {Black is close to achieving the perfect setup - Ng6 and Qf6.} ({But
considering the next move, it was more precise to start with} 11... Qf6 $1) 12.
Bg5 $5 {Preventing Black's plan.} Qd7 13. Be3 Ng6 14. Nfd2 (14. Rad1 Qe7 15. h3
Be6 $11) 14... Bf8 $5 {A clever idea - Aronian is attacking the d3 pawn,
forcing White to show his hand.} ({It was possible to return to his original
plan:} 14... Qe7 15. a4 Qf6 16. b5 Bf8 $1 $132) 15. d4 {The advance of the
central pawns is one of White's main ideas in the Exchange Ruy Lopez
structures. But here it doesn't promise much, as his queenside may become
vulnerable (the c4-square). Black can use the advanced position of the pawn b4
to get rid of his doubled c-pawns.} (15. Qc2 Rd8 $36) 15... Qe7 $1 ({Studying
the previous games carefully, we should consider this the most principled
answer to the advance.} 15... exd4 16. cxd4 Kh8 $5 {Planning to hit the centre
with f5.} (16... Qe7) 17. f3 (17. f4 f5 $1 18. Rae1 Qf7 19. Qb1 fxe4 20. f5 Nh4
$132) 17... f5 18. Qc3 Qd8 19. Rad1 Be6 20. a3 Qh4 $132) 16. dxe5 {It's
difficult for White to advantageously retain the central tension:} (16. Qc2
exd4 17. cxd4 f5 $1) 16... Be6 {Avoiding the massive simplifications, which
are obviously in White's favour:} (16... Nxe5 17. Bc5 Qe6 18. Bxf8 Nxc4 19.
Qxc4 Qxc4 20. Nxc4 Kxf8 21. f3) 17. Qc2 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 Nxe5 19. Nd2 ({Possibly
the best chance was} 19. Nxe5 Qxe5 20. f3 Bd6 (20... c5 $11) 21. g3 a5 22. Bd4
Qe6 {, but even this would offer Black a free hand on both wings.}) 19... a5 $1
20. a3 ({The exchange operation} 20. Bc5 $6 {would give Black too much
activity.} Qh4 21. Bxf8 Kxf8 22. a3 Rad8 $36) 20... axb4 21. axb4 Qe6 {Taking
control over the c4-square.} 22. f3 ({The exchange of the knight also doesn't
bring full equality.} 22. Bd4 b6 23. Bxe5 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Qxe5 25. Ra7 g6 $15)
22... Nc4 23. Bf4 (23. Bf2 Bd6) 23... c5 $1 {If Black manages to undouble the
pawns, the strategic advantage will pass into his hands.} 24. b5 Nd6 25. Rxa8 (
{Sooner or later White has to give up the open file.} 25. Qb2 Be7 26. Rfe1 b6)
25... Rxa8 26. Rb1 (26. c4 g6 27. Qb3 Bg7 28. b6 Bd4+ 29. Kh1 c6 $15) 26... b6
$1 (26... Ra2 27. Rb2 Ra5 28. b6 {looks unclear, therefore Aronian prevents
this advance.}) 27. e5 {Limits the bishop, but there was no other defence
against Ra5.} (27. c4 g6 28. g3 Bg7 29. Kg2 Be5 30. Be3 Bd4 31. Bf4 Ra3 {
Black establishes full domination.}) 27... Nc4 (27... Nf5 28. Qe4 Ra2 29. Nf1
c4 $1 {also deserved attention.}) 28. Qe4 (28. Nxc4 Qxc4 29. Bg3 Ra3 $36) 28...
Ra4 29. Rc1 (29. Nxc4 $2 Rxc4 30. Qe3 Qf5 $19) 29... h6 ({Aronian is not in a
hurry to resolve the pin with Nb2 and makes a useful move.} 29... Nb2 $5 30. c4
Qd7 $15) 30. h4 ({White doesn't need an airhole immediately.} 30. Bg3 $5 Nb2
31. Qc2 $15 {is more resilient.}) 30... Nb2 $1 31. c4 $8 Qd7 32. Rb1 (32. Rc2
Nd3 $17) 32... Ra2 {The threat is to exchange White's centralised queen with
Qd4.} 33. Be3 $6 {This is a serious error, missing unexpected idea.} (33. Nb3
$5 {was obviously not a pleasant decision, as from b3 the knight can only go
back.} Nd3 34. Bg3 Nb4 35. Kh2 $15) 33... Na4 $1 {Creating the double-threat
of Nc3 and Rd2.} 34. Rb3 $2 {Now Black's material advantage will decide the
issue.} ({In case of} 34. Re1 Nc3 $1 {is more precise than} (34... Rxd2 35. e6
fxe6 36. Bxd2 Qxd2 37. Qxe6+) 35. Qg4 Qd3 36. e6 Ne2+ 37. Kf2 Nd4 38. exf7+
Kxf7 39. Qd7+ Kg8 $19) ({But it was impossible to avoid material losses anyway.
} 34. Qf4 Nc3 35. Re1 Ra1 $1 $19) 34... Rxd2 35. Bxd2 Qxd2 36. Rd3 Qc1+ 37. Kh2
Nb2 $1 {Consistent. White's counterattack is insufficient.} 38. Rd8 (38. Rd7
Qxc4 39. Rxc7 Qxe4 40. fxe4 g6 $19) 38... Qxc4 39. Qa8 Qxh4+ 40. Kg1 Qe1+ 41.
Kh2 Qxe5+ 42. g3 (42. Kh3 Kh7 43. Rxf8 Nd3 $40) 42... Qe2+ 43. Kh3 Nd3 $3 $19
44. Rxf8+ ({A more exciting try was} 44. Re8 $5 Nf2+ 45. Kh4 Qf1 $1 46. Rxf8+
Kh7 47. Rh8+ Kg6 48. Qc6+ Kf5 49. g4+ Ke5 $19 {, but here Black also wins, as
his king escapes to the queenside.}) 44... Kh7 45. Re8 Nf2+ 46. Kh4 Qxb5 47. g4
Qc4 $1 48. Qc8 (48. Kh5 g6+ 49. Kh4 {Black has} Qd4 $19) 48... Qf4 $19 49. Qf5+
(49. Rh8+ Kg6 50. Qf5+ Qxf5 51. gxf5+ Kxf5 $19) 49... Qxf5 50. gxf5 c4 51. Re7
(51. Kg3 Nd3 $19 {[%cal Rc4c1]}) 51... c5 52. Rxf7 c3 53. f6 Kg6 $1 (53... Kg6
54. Rxg7+ Kxf6 55. Rg1 Nd3 56. Rg2 $8 b5 $19) 0-1

[Event "Christmas Congress 1961/62-37 Premier"]
[Site "Hastings"]
[Date "1961.12.27"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Game 7"]
[Black "Botvinnik - Wade"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C77"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[EventDate "1961.12.27"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "ENG"]

{Botvinnik played only a couple of games with the Spanish Exchange structure.
Obviously, it was not his favourite, at least not from the white side.
Botvinnik is acknowledged as a titan of classical play because of his
preferences for centralisation at any price. It is not a surprise that in this
game as well he executes the plan connected with the advance of the central
pawns.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 Nd7 (6...
Bd6 $1) 7. Nbd2 f6 8. O-O Bc5 ({Usually Black's plan is to transfer the knight
to d4 via e6 or c6.} 8... Nc5 {But there is one interesting and sharp idea to
change the character of the fight completely.} 9. Nxe5 fxe5 10. Qh5+ Kd7 11.
Nc4 Bd6 12. Nxe5+ Bxe5 13. Qxe5 Ne6 14. f4 Qf6 15. Qh5 $44 {, with interesting
complications.}) (8... Be7 9. Nc4 Nf8 10. Nh4 Be6 11. Nf5 Bxc4 $1 12. dxc4 Qxd1
13. Rxd1 Ne6 $11 {would be quite fine for Black.}) 9. c3 $5 {The start of the
central invasion. Six years later in the game against Stein, Botvinnik
introduced a new idea connected with pressure on the queenside. Here he goes
for the central strategy, remaining true to his classical approach.} ({The
modern treatment of this position would be something like} 9. Nh4 O-O 10. Nf5
Kh8 11. h4 Re8 12. h5 Bf8 13. Qg4 Nc5 $13 {, with rather unclear consequences.}
) 9... Nf8 10. d4 {Thanks to this early aggression in the centre, White is
establishing central domination, as Black is obliged to resign his central
post on e5. But as we saw from the previous game, this might be the best
strategy for Black - to give up the centre, but then exert pressure on the
central pawns.} exd4 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. Nfxd4 $1 {Much stronger than} (12. cxd4
Bg4 13. Be3 Qe7 14. Re1 O-O-O $17 {would lead to a situation where White has
certain trouble with the defence of his central pawns.}) 12... Ng6 13. Be3 O-O
{This structure might be the most promising for White, as he has a mobile pawn
majority on the kingside while Black's pawn majority on the other wing is
devaluated. But this might be an important factor in the endgame, while in the
middlegame Black has plenty of ideas to create active counterplay. First of
all, he has a bishop pair in an open position and second, he may create
unpleasant pressure down the e- and d-files. In other words, positions of this
kind, factor # 1 of the evaluation is piece activity.} 14. Qc2 Qe7 15. Nf5 $1 (
15. c4 c5 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 Ne5 18. Rfe1 {should also be fine, but
Botvinnik realises a very original idea.}) 15... Bxf5 $6 {Exchanging the
powerful knight, completing development and doubling White's pawns. But this
helps White in the realisation of his plan.} (15... Qf7 16. Bxb6 cxb6 17. Rad1
Qc7 18. Rfe1 Be6 {would be also better for White, but far less problematic.})
16. exf5 Ne5 17. Bxb6 cxb6 18. Nd4 $1 Qf7 19. Ne6 {Botvinnik's plan now
becomes clear - the knight on e6 will be a thorn in Black's position, it will
control the d8 square and will help White to win the fight for the open file.}
Rfc8 20. Rfe1 ({It would be more consistent to take the d-file immediately.} 
20. Rad1 b5 21. Rd6 Nc4 22. Rd4 Re8 23. Rfd1 $18) 20... b5 21. Re3 Kh8 22. Rae1
Rg8 {Black has no idea what to do - the octopus on e6 is sucking the last drop
of life from Black's position.} 23. f4 Ng4 (23... Nd7) 24. Rh3 {The simple
winning plan was to penetrate on one of the central files. But Botvinnik is
playing for total domination} Rae8 $2 (24... Nh6 $1 {would avoid the following
idea.}) 25. Qe2 $1 Nh6 26. g4 $1 {Now Black's knight is out of play and
Botvinnik can smoothly go back to the central invasion.} Qd7 27. Rd3 $1 Qc8 28.
Kf1 $1 {A great prophylactic idea.} ({In case of the immediate} 28. Red1 {
, Black has the unpleasant} Nxg4 $1 29. Qxg4 g6 $11) 28... c5 29. h3 g6 {
This speeds up the defeat, but otherwise Black's knight can't go back.} (29...
Re7 30. Rd5 b6 31. Rd6) 30. fxg6 hxg6 31. Re3 $1 Qc6 32. Qg2 Qd7 (32... Qxg2+
33. Kxg2 b6 34. Nc7 Rxe3 35. Rxe3 Rd8 36. Re2 Nf7 37. Nxa6 Ra8 38. Nc7 Rxa2 39.
Nxb5 $18) 33. Nxc5 $18 Qf7 34. Rxe8 Rxe8 35. Rxe8+ Qxe8 36. Qe4 Qd8 37. Qd4 Qe7
38. Ne4 Ng8 39. g5 {A model game for creating and exploiting a weak square
deep in the opponent's camp (octopus).} 1-0

