{Sakaev,K: "This game clearly shows that taking the centre with c3, d4 doesn't
automatically bring White dividends and it can even be a very dangerous
decision." (Inf 80/(350))} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6
dxc6 6. d3 Bd6 7. Nbd2 Be6 $1 ({As can be seen in the theoretical section, the
best move is} 7... Bg4 $1) 8. d4 $6 {Who can blame White for such a logical
move? White is willing to take control of the centre by eliminating Black's
e5-pawn with tempo.} ({The usual way is} 8. b3 Nd7 9. Bb2 Qe7 $1 {, and White
can't avoid the complicated middlegame arising after} 10. O-O O-O-O $13) 8...
Nd7 ({Of course not} 8... exd4 $2 9. e5) 9. c3 {White is protecting the pawn,
ready to meet exd4 by cxd4.} (9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. O-O Qf6 $1 12. Nf3
Bg4 {would also be better for Black.}) (9. O-O exd4 10. Nxd4 Qh4 $1 {would be
awkward to meet.} 11. N4f3 (11. N2f3 Qxe4) (11. h3 $2 Bxh3 $1 $19) 11... Qh5
$40) 9... O-O ({More challenging would be} 9... Qe7 $1 10. O-O O-O-O 11. Re1 f6
{Planning to start a pawn storm with g5-h5-g4.}) 10. O-O Re8 {It looks like
White enjoys an ideal centre, but looks can be deceptive. In fact, the centre
is under severe pressure and sooner or later White will be forced to take on
e5.} 11. Qc2 Qf6 $1 12. b3 {There is just no other way to complete development.
} Qg6 $1 13. Kh1 (13. dxe5 $6 Bxe5 $1 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. f4 Bh3 $1 16. Rf2 Ng4
17. f5 Qd6 18. Nf1 Nxf2 19. Qxf2 Rxe4 $1 (19... Bg4 20. h3 Bd1) 20. gxh3 Rae8
$36) 13... Bg4 ({The time has come for a direct assault on the centre.} 13...
exd4 $1 14. cxd4 Bd5 $1 15. Re1 Re6 $40 {, and White's centre should fall.})
14. Re1 (14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 16. Re1 (16. f3 $4 Rh5) 16... Rae8 17. f3
Bc8 18. Nf1 f5 19. Bf4 R5e6 20. Bxd6 cxd6 $17) 14... Qh5 $6 ({Missing the
chance to start direct pressure with} 14... exd4 15. cxd4 Qh5 $17 {, and White
is completely tied up on the kingside, while Black is planning to increase the
pressure with Re6, Rae8 and Rh6.}) 15. dxe5 {White finally surrenders the
centre, but here this offers him no more than drawing chances.} Nxe5 16. Nxe5
Bxe5 17. Nf1 $1 Rad8 (17... f5 $5) 18. Be3 Bd6 19. f3 Bc8 20. Rad1 f5 $1 {
Black's activity starts a little bit too late, as White is already out of
danger.} 21. exf5 Qxf5 (21... Bxf5 22. Qf2 Bg6 23. c4 a5 24. Bd4 a4 $15) 22.
Qf2 $1 (22. Qxf5 Bxf5 23. Bf2 Rxe1 24. Rxe1 Kf7 25. Ng3 Bg6 26. Ne4 Be7 $15 {
The endgame would be in Black's favour.}) 22... Qa5 23. b4 $6 ({Here White
misses his chance to fight for an advantage.} 23. Ng3 $1 Be5 (23... Qxc3 24.
Ne4 Qa5 25. Bg5 $1 Rxe4 26. Bxd8 $18) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Bd4 $1 Bxd4 26. cxd4
$14) 23... Qh5 24. Bd4 Be6 25. Re4 Qf7 26. Rde1 Bf5 27. Rxe8+ Rxe8 28. Rxe8+
Qxe8 29. Qe3 Qxe3 30. Nxe3 Be6 31. a3 {Despite the bishop pair, the position
is some sort of fortress} b6 32. c4 c5 33. bxc5 bxc5 34. Bc3 Bf4 35. Bd2 {
The endgame with opposite coloured bishops would be an easy draw.} Kf7 36. g3
Be5 37. Kg2 Ke7 38. Kf2 Bb2 39. a4 Bd4 40. Ke2 {Black twice missed his chances
to punish White for his early action in the centre (8.d4). The first
opportunity was on move 9, to castle long with better chances in the
forthcoming sharp middlegame. The second one was on move 15, to take exd4,
starting concrete actions against White's central pawns.} 1/2-1/2

