1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 $5 {The main
difference between the delayed Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez Defence and
the Exchange Variation (4.Bxc6) is that Black has already developed his
kingside light pieces. The most popular reply for Black against the Exchange
Variation of the Ruy Lopez Defence is 4...f6. In this position, Black cannot
play f7-f6 anymore, and his dark-squared bishop is located on e7, which is not
ideal.} dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. b3 {White fianchettoes his dark-squared
bishop to carry out the breakthrough d2-d4 in the centre.} f6 10. Bb2 Nc5 ({
After} 10... c5 {, White has to switch from the centre to the kingside and
carry out f2-f4:} 11. Nh4) 11. d4 exd4 12. Nxd4 Re8 {Black understands that
one of the main white plans is to carry out e4-e5 with a preliminary f2-f4.
Therefore, Black creates pressure along the e-file.} ({Also possible is} 12...
Bd6 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Rae1 Ne6 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. f4) 13. Qe2 Bd6 14. Rae1 {It is a
novel idea to place the rooks on the e- and f-files} (14. Rad1 Qe7 15. f3 Qe5
$6 {In this game, Black helped White to choose a better position for his
queenside rook.} 16. f4 Qe7 17. Rde1 Qf7 18. e5 f5 19. h3 Bf8 20. g4 $36 {
1-0 Dorfman,J-Hazai, L/Budapest 1988/CBM 09 (60)}) (14. Rfe1 a5 15. Rad1 Qe7
16. Nc4 Qf8 17. Nxd6 cxd6 18. Qf3 Be6 19. Qg3 Rad8 20. f3 $14 {1-0 Kasparov,
G-Cesetti,C/Italy 1990/ EXT 2002 (47)}) 14... Qe7 15. f4 {White threatens the
breakthrough e4-e5.} Bd7 {Black prevents White's e4-e5, securing the 8th rank.}
16. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Ye4e5,Yb3b4] White improves the position of his queen,
creating some threats like e4-e5, as well as b3-b4 followed by Qb3.} Qf7 {
covering the a2-g8 diagonal.} 17. Nc4 {White improves the position of his
pieces. In the near future, the breakthrough e4-e5 can be dangerous. Also,
there is the option to capture on d6 followed by Ba3, which should promise
White some advantage.} (17. e5 fxe5 18. fxe5 Qxf3 19. N2xf3 Be7 {, and Black
is OK.}) 17... f5 $2 {It is a strategic mistake to open the long diagonal for
White's dark-squared bishop.} ({The least of the evils was a waiting strategy:
} 17... Rad8 $14 {, but it is clear that the position favours White.}) 18. exf5
Bxf5 19. Nxf5 Qxf5 20. Qc3 $1 $16 {Emphasizing the defect of Black's 17th move.
White's advantage is obvious, thanks to his better pawn structure and very
active bishop.} ({After} 20. Qg3 {Black can response with} Qg6) 20... Qd7 {
Other continuations are not better:} (20... Qf7 21. Ne5 Bxe5 (21... Qf6 22. b4
$16) 22. fxe5 Qe7 23. e6 $18) (20... Bf8 21. Ne5 $16 {[%cal Yg2g4]}) 21. Ne5 {
Eliminating Black's dark-squared bishop, which will make White's one even
stronger.} Bxe5 (21... Qf5 22. Nxc6 $18) 22. Rxe5 Rxe5 (22... b6 23. Rfe1 Rxe5
24. Qxe5 {See the game.}) 23. Qxe5 b6 24. Re1 {Taking control over the e-file.}
Rf8 25. g3 Rd8 (25... Nb7 26. Qe7 (26. Qe2 $5 $16) 26... Rf7 27. Qe8+ Qxe8 28.
Rxe8+ Rf8 29. Re6 Nd6 (29... c5 30. Be5) 30. Be5 Re8 31. Rxe8+ Nxe8 32. g4 $16)
(25... Rf5 26. Qe8+ Rf8 27. Qxd7 Nxd7 28. Re6 c5) 26. f5 Qf7 27. g4 Rd2 28.
Qe8+ Qxe8 29. Rxe8+ Kf7 30. Rc8 $18 {Now Black is defenceless against White's
piece activity. As a result, he cannot maintain the material balance.} Rxc2 (
30... Rd7 31. Be5 $18) 31. Rxc7+ Kg8 32. Bxg7 Ne4 33. Bh6 c5 34. g5 Nd6 35.
Rg7+ {Winning further material.} (35. Rg7+ Kh8 36. Rd7 $18) 1-0

[Event "FIDE World Cup"]
[Site "Tromso"]
[Date "2013.08.17"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Game 10"]
[Black "Adhiban - Nakamura"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "84"]
[EventDate "2013.08.11"]
[EventRounds "7"]
[EventCountry "NOR"]

{This game was played at the 2013 Fide World Cup in Tromso. Black is one of
the favourites of the tournament while White is also a strong player, who will
soon become one of the best from India, right after Anand and Harikrishna. We
were teammates in Spanish team championships for more than five years and he
amazed me mostly by his aggressive, combinative style and his seemingly
infinite energy and fighting spirit. Here for some unknown reason he chose to
challenge Nakamura in the Exchange Spanish. Was that an inspired decision?
Let's take a look the game and judge for ourselves.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1
Be6 10. Bf4 O-O-O {is the theoretical continuation.}) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9.
Be3 O-O-O 10. O-O-O {This position is completely harmless for Black, which was
proved in many games before.} Ne7 (10... Bb4 {will be met by} 11. Nde2 Ne7 12.
a3 Bd6 13. Bf4) ({The well-known equaliser is} 10... Bd6 {Spassky,B-Antoshin,V
Sochi 1966} 11. Nb3 Ne7 12. Nc5 Ng6 13. Nxd7 Rxd7 14. f3 Re8 (14... Nh4 $1 {
Putting some pressure on White's pawns.} 15. Rd2 g5 16. Rf2 Re8 17. g3 Ng6) 15.
g3 Ne5 16. Rhf1 Red8 {Even if White manages to trade the knight for the
light-squared bishop, all the endgames are easy to defend because of the
activity of all black pieces.}) 11. Nb3 b6 12. f4 {I analysed a very similar
position in the Endgame and Historical sections.} Ng6 13. a3 {With the idea to
avoid Bb4, which will expose the e4-pawn.} c5 $1 {Limiting the Nb3 and Be3 and
preparing Bc6 to pressure the weak pawn e4.} 14. Rhf1 Bd6 15. Nd2 Rhe8 16. Nc4
Bf8 $1 {Black completed his setup and it is now up to White to show his hand.}
17. f5 $5 {Inspired by Lasker's and Fischer's games, which however didn't
really prove that f4-f5 is that strong.} Nh8 $1 {You do not often see that
moving the knight into the corner is much stronger than centralising it. This
might be an idea for a further article - Centralisation vs Decentralisation.} (
17... Ne5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Bf4 Ree8 20. g4 Bc6 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. Re1 b5 {
also promises White no more than equality.}) 18. a4 {Trying to stop b5-b4,
which is vital for the survival of the central pawn e4.} Nf7 19. Bf4 b5 $1 20.
axb5 axb5 21. Nd2 Bc6 22. Rde1 Nd6 $1 ({It was already possible to win a pawn.
} 22... b4 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. exd5 Rxe1+ 25. Rxe1 Rxd5 26. Re8+ Rd8 27. Rxd8+
Kxd8 $17) 23. Bxd6 {A sad necessity.} Bxd6 24. g3 Be5 25. Nd1 {This equals
resignation, as such passive moves only postpone the inevitable. Black's
bishop pair is ruling over the board while White's knights and rooks create a
pitiful impression.} Kb7 26. Nf3 Bd6 27. Nf2 Ra8 $1 28. Kd2 Ra2 (28... Red8) (
28... b4) 29. Ra1 $1 {Grabbing the chance to trade a pair of rooks for the
price of one pawn.} Rxa1 30. Rxa1 Bxe4 31. Nxe4 Rxe4 32. Kd3 (32. Re1 Rxe1 33.
Kxe1 Kc6 34. Ke2 Kd5 35. Ke3 h5 $19 {should be easily winning.}) 32... Rb4 33.
Kc3 Kc6 34. Rd1 g5 $1 {Playing for second weakness - a typical tool in the
realisation of the advantage.} 35. fxg6 hxg6 36. b3 g5 $1 $19 37. Rf1 g4 38.
Nd2 Rd4 $3 {Immediate execution - such an idea is easy to miss, but not for a
player like Nakamura!} 39. Nb1 Be5 $1 {Creating a devastating threat.} 40. Rf5
Rd8+ 41. Rxe5 b4+ 42. Kb2 fxe5 {One more game in which f4-f5 didn't impress
too much.} 0-1

[Event "Gibraltar Masters 9th"]
[Site "Caleta"]
[Date "2011.02.01"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Game 11"]
[Black "Caruana, F - Rapport"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "2011.01.25"]
[EventRounds "10"]
[EventCountry "GGB"]

{One of the best players of modern times, Fabiano Caruana, is adopting the
Exchange Spanish for the first time in his career. Soon it will become his
trademark to meet the Berlin Defence (3.Bb5 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bc6), bringing him
many important victories. I recommend you to study his amazing game against
Anand in the section about opposite-side castling.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qd6 {In the theoretical section I will turn your
attention to the move 5...Bg4, which in my opinion is the most challenging
reply. Black has many other interesting moves like 5...Qf6, 5...Be7 and even 5.
..Ne7. The idea of Qd6 is to skip the move f6, which apart from defending the
pawn is rather useless.} 6. Na3 $5 {Developing the knight with tempo.} (6. d4
exd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Be3 Nh6 10. h3 Qg6 11. Qf3 f5 $1 {Castaneda,N
-Hjartarson,J Winnipeg 1997 will reveal one of the ideas of 5...Qd6.}) 6... Qe6
({Modern theory considers it Black's best reply to keep the knight on the edge
by} 6... b5 $1 7. c3 c5 8. Nc2 Bb7 9. a4 $5 {, with a complicated struggle, in
which Black has to play carefully, as White has a huge lead in development.})
7. b3 (7. d4 Bxa3 8. bxa3 exd4 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Bb2 O-O 11. Ne5 b6 12. f4 c5 13.
Qe3 {, with an extremely sharp position in Evans,L-Lein,A New York 1977} Bb7 (
13... Qe8 $5) 14. f5 $1 {Here f4-f5 is very strong.} Qe7 15. Rf4 Rad8 16. Qg3 (
{Better was} 16. Ng4 $1 Nxg4 17. Rxg4 f6 18. e5 $1) 16... Nh5 (16... Rd2 $2 17.
Ng4 Nxg4 18. Bxg7 $1 h5 19. Re1 f6 20. Bh6 Rf7 21. h3 $18) 17. Qg4 f6 18. Qxh5
fxe5 19. Rh4 h6 {, and Black managed to repel the attack.}) 7... Ne7 8. Nc4 Ng6
9. d4 $1 {With this early opening of the centre, Caruana took the initiative
and manage to hold it until the end.} exd4 10. Nxd4 Qg4 11. Bb2 ({It was
possible to keep the queens, but Caruana has no reason to reject a better
endgame.} 11. Qd3 Bc5 12. h3 Qd7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Rad1 Re8 15. Rfe1 f6 16. Qc3
$5) 11... f6 12. f4 (12. f3 $5 {White's queen is much better placed and may
create nasty threats, for example} Qh5 13. Qe1 Bc5 14. Rd1 O-O 15. Kh1 Bd7 16.
Ne2 Rad8 17. Ng3 Qh4 18. Qa5 $5 $36) 12... Bc5 (12... Qxd1 13. Raxd1 Bc5 14. h3
O-O 15. Kh2 Re8) 13. h3 ({Seul,G -Fleck,J Germany 2004 is also a model game
for White, in which a similar idea was executed.} 13. Kh1 $5 Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Bd7
({The only way for Black was} 14... O-O $1 15. f5 Nh8 $1 {A motif used in game
1 Adhiban-Nakamura.}) 15. f5 $1 b5 (15... Ne7 16. e5 $1) 16. Na5 Ne7 17. Nb7 $1
Bb6 18. Ba3 $1 Kf7 19. e5 $1 fxe5 20. Nf3 Bc8 21. Ng5+ Kf6 22. Ne4+ Kf7 23.
Nd8+ $18) 13... Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Kf7 $6 {A suspicious idea - placing the king on
the same file as the rook f1 gives White additional tactical ideas.} (14... O-O
$5 15. f5 Nh8 $5) (14... Bd7 $5) 15. Kh1 $1 {Moving the king away from the pin
and preparing the following original idea.} ({The direct} 15. e5 {would be met
by} f5 $1 16. g4 Rd8 $132) 15... Re8 {Here f4-f5 is very strong and probably
was underestimated by Rapport.} 16. f5 $1 {Caruana shows that he studied the
historical heritage carefully and executes the Lasker idea under much better
circumstances.} ({Black was probably counting on} 16. e5 fxe5 17. fxe5+ Kg8 $15
) 16... Ne5 (16... Nf8 17. e5 fxe5 18. Nf3 {would be also quite unpleasant.})
17. Nxe5+ Rxe5 (17... fxe5 {is also hopeless due to} 18. Nf3 Bd6 19. c4 $1 b6 (
19... c5 20. Rd5) 20. c5 $1 bxc5 21. Ba3 {, and Black is strategically lost.})
18. Ne6 $1 {Transposing to a technically winning endgame.} Rxe6 19. fxe6+ Bxe6
20. Rd3 (20. e5 f5 $1) 20... h5 21. Be5 $1 {The touch of the big maestro!} Rc8
22. Bg3 Ke7 23. e5 $1 f5 24. Bh4+ $18 {The transfer of the bishop to f4 was a
very inspired idea.} Kf7 25. Rd8 $1 {Exchanging the last rook significantly
reduces Black's chances to create counterplay.} Be3 26. Rxc8 Bxc8 27. Bd8 Be6
28. h4 $1 {the rest is easy} b5 29. Bxc7 g5 30. hxg5 Kg6 31. Bd8 h4 32. Rd1 Bc5
33. c3 Bd5 34. b4 Bf8 35. Kh2 f4 36. Kh3 Bxa2 37. Ra1 Bd5 38. Rxa6 Kf5 39. Bf6
c5 40. bxc5 Bxc5 41. g6 1-0

