{In this Chapter I would like to focus your attention on the dynamic features
of the Spanish Exchange structure middlegames and more precisely on the
opposite side castling positions. In the other chapters I have already
analysed many games featuring opposite side castling, but here I will
concentrate on the typical ways of building an attack for both sides and the
creation of various combinational motifs. Many players, including the father
of the Exchange Spanish himself, the world champion Lasker, were looking to
create dynamic positions rather than playing boring endgames. The simple
explanation is that converting the minimal advantage in the endgame requires a
lot of patience and great technical skills, while in positions with opposite
castling often the outcome is decided by one single error, or sometimes by
losing just one tempo in the attack. On the other hand, playing this way
involves a much higher degree of risk, as you can easily lose control of the
position and get mated. In the first four games it is Black who intentionally
created this situation by waiting for the opponent to castle short, hoping to
outrun him in the forthcoming mutual pawn storms. In games 5-10 it is White
who tries the same waiting approach, starting the pawn storm immediately after
Black castles short. It is more clever to keep the white king in the centre
until enough preconditions for a successful attack have been achieved. Game 9
shows what can happen otherwise: Yu Yangui was severely punished after
castling too early. Very soon he had to meet the attack bravely with his
king's bare chest. I hope that from reading this chapter carefully you will
learn many new attacking ideas and make your game more dynamic. When you feel
ready, you can take the challenge and test your tactical skills, solving the
puzzles at the end of the chapter.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6
5. O-O Qd6 {Before the 12th game of the quarterfinal match between Kortschnoi
and Mecking in 1974, the result was 2-0 for Kortschnoi with 9 draws. In the
second and the fourth games of the match, Mecking didn't achieve much against
the Open Spanish and in the rest of his white games he switched to the English.
In game 12, Mecking came back to 1.e4, going for an Exchange Spanish, which
already brought him a couple of good victories in 1968 and 1969. Of course,
Kortschnoi was excellently prepared and responded in his typical aggressive
way, making the collision inevitable. True to his aggressive style Kortschnoy
did his best to avoid the endgame although he was leading 2-0.} (5... f6 6. d4)
6. d3 f6 7. Be3 Bg4 {The most aggressive approach.} ({The other main direction
is} 7... c5 {, when best for White is} 8. Nbd2 Be6 9. a3 $1 {Rozentalis -
Krasenkow POL t ch 1996.} Qd7 (9... Ne7 10. b4 $5) 10. Qe2 Bd6 11. c3 Ne7 12.
b4 cxb4 13. axb4 Ng6 14. Rfb1 O-O 15. Nb3 {, with pressure for White.}) 8. Nbd2
O-O-O {Castling long looks like the most natural continuation. Black has a
strong bishop pair and is preparing the pawn storm g5-g4. But it was much
safer to start rolling the pawns, keeping the king in the centre. This will
prevent White's counterattack on the queenside.} ({The safer} 8... Ne7 9. Nc4
Qd7 10. h3 Be6 (10... Bh5 $5) 11. Qe2 Ng6 12. Rfd1 {also led to White's
advantage in Playa,M -Brito Garcia,A Asuncion 1992.} O-O-O (12... c5 $5 13. c3
Qf7 14. b3 {/\ d4}) 13. d4 Qf7 14. Na5 $1 {, and White's attack is quite
strong, for instance} Nf4 15. Bxf4 exf4 16. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 17. d5 $3 cxd5 18.
Qxa6+ Kb8 (18... Kd7 19. exd5 Bf5 20. Nd4) 19. Rd3 $18 {, with mate.}) ({
In case of} 8... c5 9. Nc4 Qd7 10. h3 Be6 11. Qe2 {Rozentalis,E-Mikhalevski,A/
Israel 1999 Black allowed the following typical combination:} g5 $2 ({Better is
} 11... O-O-O $1 {, and after} 12. a3 $1 g5 13. b4 h5 14. bxc5 g4 15. Nh4 {
the position becomes extremely complicated.}) 12. Nfxe5 $5 fxe5 13. Nxe5 Qg7
14. Qh5+ Kd8 (14... Bf7 15. Nxf7 Qxf7 16. Qxg5 Be7 17. Qe5 O-O-O 18. Bxc5 Bf6
19. Qf5+ Kb8 20. c3 Nh6 21. Qf3 Rhg8 22. d4) 15. Bxg5+ Be7 16. Bxe7+ Nxe7 17.
f4 Rg8 {, and now after} 18. Rf2 {White preserves the better chances.}) 9. Rb1
$1 ({White also has other ways to develop activity on the queenside. For
example after} 9. a3 $5 {, played in Rozentalis,E -Sulskis,S Vilnius 2002,} Kb8
(9... g5 $5 10. b4 h5 11. Qb1 $5) 10. b4 Ne7 11. Qb1 Nc8 12. Bc5 Qd7 13. a4 Ka8
14. Qb2 Nd6 15. Rfb1 {, the white attack is coming much faster.}) (9. Qb1 $5 {
is also a very original idea - look at the next game.}) (9. b4 $5 {It looks
double-edged to just offer a pawn to increase the speed of the attack, for
instance after} Qxb4 10. Rb1 Qa4 11. Nc4 Be6 (11... b5 $6 12. Ncd2) 12. Nfd2 b5
13. Nb2 Qa3 14. c4 $1 {White has very good attacking prospects.}) 9... Ne7 (
9... c5 {would only help White.} 10. a3 Be6 11. b4) ({After the most natural} 
9... g5 10. b4 h5 11. a4 Bd7 12. Nb3 $1 h4 13. Nfd2 {, White has excellent
prospects on the queenside, for instance} Nh6 14. Nc5 Ng4 15. Nc4 Qe7 16. Na5
b6 17. d4 $1 $18) 10. b4 g5 11. a4 Ng6 ({It is too late to try to hold White's
attack with} 11... b6 12. a5 $1 b5 13. Nb3 Kb8 14. Nc5 Bc8 15. d4 $1 g4 16.
dxe5 $1 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Rxd1+ 18. Rxd1 gxf3 19. Rd8 Ng6 20. Nxa6+ Kb7 21. exf6 {
, and White has a winning endgame, for example} Bd6 22. Rxh8 Nxh8 23. Nc5+ Bxc5
24. Bxc5 fxg2 25. Kxg2 Nf7 26. Kg3 $18) (11... Qd7 $6 {doesn't really stop
b4-b5} 12. b5 cxb5 13. axb5 axb5 14. c4 $1 {White attack is decisive}) 12. b5
$1 {White is the first to hit the opponent, which is the most important
condition in such double-edged positions. Black is forced to defend and divert
his attention away from the kingside.} cxb5 13. axb5 axb5 14. Rxb5 Qc6 ({
No better is} 14... Be6 {White's attack develops itself.} 15. Qb1 Qa6 16. Nc4
Bxc4 17. dxc4 Nf4 18. Qb3) 15. Rb2 $1 {Planning Qa1! or Ra2, to penetrate on
the open file.} (15. Qb1 {was also more than enough to hold the intiative in
the game Ermenkov,E-Radev Iordanov,N Pernik 1975.} Nf4 16. Re1 Bxf3 (16... Rg8
17. Ra5 b6 18. Ra7 Be6 19. d4 g4 20. d5 $1) 17. Nxf3 Ne6 18. Qb3 Bc5 {, and
now White missed the decisive} 19. Rxb7 $1 Bb6 20. Bxb6 Kxb7 21. Bc5+ Kc8 22.
Be7 $18) 15... Bc5 {Korschnoi is hoping to minimise White's attacking
potential, as it is obviously too late to launch a counterattack.} (15... h5
16. h3 Be6 17. d4 $1) 16. Nb3 $1 (16. Qa1 Nf4 17. Qa8+ Kd7 18. Qxb7 {wins a
pawn, but Mecking is playing for more.}) (16. Nc4 $5) 16... Bb4 {Black's
defensive task is already very difficult.} (16... Bxe3 17. fxe3 {would isolate
the knight on g6, as in case of} Nh4 {there is} 18. Nxe5 $18) (16... Bb6 17. c4
$1 Nh4 $6 18. Nxe5 $18) 17. Nfd4 $6 {This looks like a clever trick, but} (17.
Ra2 $1 {would be more decisive.} Kb8 18. Qa1 b6 19. Ra4 Bd6 20. Rb1 {, and
Black's king is doomed.}) 17... exd4 $6 {Falling for a clever trick.} ({
Stronger was} 17... Bxd1 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Rxd1 Kd7 {, and White would have
only a minimal advantage.}) 18. Qxg4+ Qd7 19. Qxd7+ Rxd7 20. Nxd4 (20. Ra1 b6
21. Bxd4 Rxd4 22. Nxd4 Bc3 23. Ra8+ Kb7 24. Ra7+ Kxa7 25. Nb5+ Kb7 26. Nxc3)
20... Bc3 21. Ra2 $1 Rxd4 22. Ra3 $1 {It may be that Korschnoi missed this
move. Now White remains a healthy pawn up in the endgame.} Rb4 (22... Bb2 23.
Rb3) 23. Rxc3 Re8 24. f3 Kd7 25. Ra1 Rb5 26. Kf2 Kd6 27. Raa3 h5 28. Ra4 c6 29.
Rca3 g4 30. Ra5 Ree5 31. Rxb5 Rxb5 32. fxg4 hxg4 33. Kg3 $18 {, and White soon
won. It was not easy to define in which moment Black made the decisive mistake
and how to improve on Black's play. Luckily Korschnoi won the next game,
qualifying for the semifinal match with Petrosian.} 1-0

