1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Qd6 6. d3 f6 7. Be3 Bg4 8.
Nbd2 O-O-O {For the first time this position appeared on the highest level in
the game Mecking-Kortschnoi in 1974, in which Mecking launched an irresistible
attack by simple means: Rb1, b4, a4 and b5. In this short game, grandmaster
Petrushin shows an even more direct way to handle this position - to open two
files against Black's king by sacrificing a pawn.} 9. Qb1 $1 {Escaping from
the pin and preparing b4-b5.} Qd7 ({In case of} 9... Kb8 {or any other move
instead of Qd7, White can rearrange his pieces with} 10. Nc4 $1 Qd7 11. Nfd2)
10. b4 $1 g5 11. a4 Nh6 {, and now Petrushin is wiping up the queenside by} 12.
b5 $1 cxb5 13. axb5 Qxb5 14. Qa2 $1 {Modern treatment of the Exchange Spanish
in the style of the Benko gambit. Don't believe anyone who claims that he can
save this position.} Bxf3 (14... Qc6 15. Nc4 Bxf3 16. Na5 Qd7 17. gxf3 b5 18.
Nb7) 15. Rfb1 $1 Qc6 16. Nxf3 (16. gxf3 $1 {would finish the game at least two
moves earlier (Nxf3 and Nd2 back.)}) 16... Ng4 17. Ba7 $1 {This bishop is the
first piece to invade Black's camp. When the first enemy breaks into the house
it is time to leave it urgently.} h5 (17... Kd7 18. d4 Ke8 19. d5 Qd7 20. Rxb7)
(17... Bc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. Qe6+ Rd7 20. Qxg4) 18. h3 Nh6 19. d4 g4 $2 ({
The only way to stay in the game was} 19... exd4 20. Nxd4 Rxd4 $1 21. Bxd4 Be7
{, but White should be winning anyway after} 22. Qb3 $1 Rd8 23. c3 g4 24. Ra5
$1 Qxe4 25. Rxh5 Nf5 26. Rxf5 Qxf5 27. Qxb7+ Kd7 28. hxg4 $18) 20. d5 $1 Qc3
21. Rb3 Qc4 22. Nd2 Qe2 23. Rxb7 $5 {The following mating combination has one
serious drawback, which luckily for White passed unnoticed. It had to be
prepared with} (23. c4 $1 gxh3 24. Rxb7) ({or} 23. Qa4 Qxd2 24. Rxb7) 23...
Kxb7 24. Nc4 Rd6 $2 (24... Ba3 $3 {could possibly save the day.} 25. Bc5 Qxe4 (
25... g3 $5 {is also difficult to refute.}) 26. Rb1+ Kc8 27. Ne3 Kd7 28. Qxa3
Rb8 29. Rd1 Ke8 {, and White has to put some more efforts into finding the win,
as Black's king is hiding on g6.}) 25. Bc5 $1 {Now White's attack decides.} Kc8
26. Bxd6 Bxd6 27. Qxa6+ Kd8 28. Qa8+ Ke7 29. Qxh8 Nf7 (29... Qxc4 30. Ra8 $18)
30. Qc8 g3 (30... Qxc4 31. Ra8 $18) 31. fxg3 Qxc4 32. Ra8 1-0

