1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 {A surprising
idea. It is always strategically risky to part with the bishop pair too early
while remaining with a problematic pawn structure. Usually Black continues} (
6... h5 $1 {or even}) (6... Bh5 $5 {, as can be found in the theoretical
chapter.}) 7. Qxf3 Qd7 $5 {Now Black's idea becomes clear. Only a dynamic
approach may justify the trade of Black's strong light-squared bishop. In
opposite side castling positions, the evaluation depends on which attack is
faster. Black's play is based on the assumption that he can use the pawn h3 to
increase the impact of the pawn storm with g5-g4. At the same time such an
approach is not a safe walk, as Black's king's position is also far from ideal.
Back in 1914, Capablanca demonstrated the dangers awaiting Black on the
queenside in his game against Janowski. White's pawn storm is easy to prepare
and execute - after b4, a4 and b4-b5 it is hardly possible to prevent the
opening of files against Black's king. The outcome of the fight is going to be
decided in the next few moves and it depends on who will develop the attack
faster.} (7... h6) 8. d3 O-O-O 9. Nd2 $1 ({Worse is} 9. Be3 f6 10. Nd2 h5 11.
Nc4 g5 {, when Black is already threatening g5-g4, while White didn't even
start his actions on the other wing.}) 9... f6 10. Nc4 h5 $1 {This is the
precise move order, as in case of} (10... g5 {White can block the pawns with}
11. Qh5 $1 ({, or exchange queens with} 11. Qg4)) (10... c5 {is senseless
because of} 11. Be3) 11. Qe3 $1 {The justification of this rather strange move
is that the queen steps out of the way of g5-g4, while at the same time asking
Black to react to the threat Qa7.} Kb8 (11... c5 $6 {Only helps White to open
files with} 12. b4) ({In case of} 11... b6 {, White can continue with the
clever} 12. Qe1 $1 g5 13. Be3 Kb7 14. Qc3 $36 {, when White is ready to open
the centre with Rd1 and d4 - look at the next game.}) 12. b4 $1 {There is no
doubt that such sacrifices are correct and better rejected.} g5 ({Too naive is
} 12... Bxb4 $6 13. Rb1 $40) 13. a4 $1 {White is ready for b4-b5.} g4 (13... b6
$2 {was played in Guseinov,G -Abdulov,O Baku 2015, when White missed an easy
solution.} 14. Nxb6 $1 $146 cxb6 15. Qxb6+ Kc8 (15... Ka8 16. Be3) 16. Qxa6+
Qb7 17. Qc4 Bd6 18. b5 Kd7 19. Be3 Ne7 20. b6 Ra8 21. a5 Ra6 22. d4 {, and
Black is helpless.}) 14. h4 $1 {This is a typical tool to hold the attack by
keeping the files closed.} Bh6 ({Again} 14... Bxb4 $6 15. Rb1 {is too risky,
for example} Bc3 (15... c5 16. Bb2 Ne7 17. Rfd1 Qxa4 18. c3) 16. Qc5 $1 Qe7 (
16... Ka8 17. Nb6+ cxb6 18. Qxc3) (16... Bd4 17. Qb4) 17. Nd6 Qxd6 18. Qxc3 Ka8
(18... Ne7 19. Ba3 Qd7 20. Qb4 $18) 19. Rb3 Rb8 20. Ba3 Qe6 21. Bc5 {The
threat is Qa5 and Rxb7.} b6 22. Rfb1 Nh6 23. g3 $1 (23. Bxb6 cxb6 24. Rxb6 Rxb6
25. Rxb6 Rb8 26. Rxc6 $2 Rb1+ $19) 23... Nf7 24. Bxb6 $18 cxb6 25. Rxb6 Rxb6
26. Rxb6 Rb8 27. Rxc6 $18) 15. Qg3 $6 {The queen is misplaced on this square.}
({The best continuation was} 15. Qc5 $1 Bxc1 (15... b6 $2 16. Nxb6 $1 cxb6 17.
Qxb6+ $40) (15... Bf8 16. Qa5) 16. Rfxc1 Qd4 17. Rab1 $1 (17. Qa5 $6 g3) 17...
Nh6 18. Qxd4 Rxd4 19. b5 {, and White keeps the initiative in the endgame}) (
15. Qe2 $14 {was also a better option than Qg3.}) (15. Qe1 $5) 15... Bxc1 16.
Rfxc1 Ne7 {Although White missed the best continuation on move 15, his
position is still preferable.} 17. Qe3 $1 {After this move, White's position
is better. White is planning to stabilize the kingside with g3 and then
continue with the action on the other wing.} ({The immediate breakthrough} 17.
b5 {was principled, but unfortunately it only leads to a draw.} cxb5 18. axb5
axb5 19. d4 $1 bxc4 20. Qa3 c6 21. Rcb1 b5 22. Qa8+ Kc7 23. Ra7+ Kb6 24. Ra6+)
(17. Re1 $6 {was the game continuation.}) (17. Rcb1 $5) 17... Ng6 (17... Nc8
18. Rcb1 b6 19. Ra3) (17... Qd4 18. Qxd4 $1 {The endgame is in White's favour
due to Black's pawn weaknesses on the kingside.} Rxd4 19. g3 Nc8 20. Rd1 Nb6 (
20... Rhd8 21. a5 $14) 21. c3 Rd7 22. Nb2 Rhd8 23. a5 Nc8 24. f3) 18. g3 $1 (
18. b5 $5) 18... Qd4 19. Qxd4 exd4 20. Rf1 $1 Ne5 21. Nxe5 fxe5 22. f3 Rdg8 23.
fxg4 Rxg4 24. Kh2 Rhg8 25. Rf3 $16 {With a much better endgame for White (the
plan is Rg1 followed by Rf5).} *

