{In this game, Mamedyarov is repeating the same aggressive approach which he
introduced against Nataf in 2005. As in the previous game, Mamedyarov is a
clear favourite, as he has a 200 points higher rating and he shows his
willingness to pay any price to complicate the game to increase his winning
chances.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7.
Qxf3 Qd7 8. d3 f6 9. Nd2 O-O-O 10. Nc4 $1 (10. Rb1 c5 11. a3 Ne7 12. b4 cxb4
13. axb4 Nc6 $132) 10... h5 (10... Ne7 11. b4) (10... c5 11. Be3) (10... g5 {
could lead to the same, but White has the option} 11. Qh5 $5 {, blocking the
pawns.}) 11. Qe3 $1 {Introduced at GM level in the game Nataf,I - Mamedyarov,S
Warsaw 2005. White's queen steps away from the eventual g5-g4, creating the
threat Qa7.} (11. Bd2 g5 12. Qe3 c5) 11... b6 {Mamedyarov comes up with a new
idea, but I am doubtful that it is an improvement.} (11... Qd4 12. Qe1 $1 Ne7 (
12... g5 13. Be3 Qd7 14. b4) 13. Be3 Qd7 14. b4 g5 15. a4 Ng6 16. b5 cxb5 17.
axb5 Qxb5 18. Rb1 (18. Qd2 Qxc4 19. dxc4 Rxd2 20. Bxd2) 18... Qa4 (18... Qd7
19. Qa5) (18... Qc6 19. Na5) 19. Na5 b6 20. Bxb6 cxb6 21. Qc3+ Kd7 22. Rxb6 $18
) (11... Kb8 {looks like the safest option (Nataf,I - Mamedyarov,S Warsaw 2005)
, but the position is in White's favour after} 12. b4 $5 ({Also possible is
the slow} 12. Bd2 g5 13. b4 g4 14. h4 Bh6 15. Qe1 Bxd2 16. Qxd2 Ne7 17. a4 Ng6
18. g3 Nf8 19. Rfb1 $40 {, with a strong White initiative.})) (11... c5 $5 {
Kagan - Stepak Israel 1967} 12. b4 $1 $146 Qd4 13. Qxd4 cxd4 14. Bd2 g5 15. a4
$14) 12. Qe1 $1 {Amazing! It is the second move in a row with the queen - and
it is going backwards. The justification this time is that the queen makes way
for the bishop to go to e3 and at the same time supports b2-b4.} g5 (12... Ne7
13. Be3 Kb7 14. Rd1 (14. b4 $5 g5 15. a4 Ng6 16. Qc3 $40)) 13. Be3 $1 {Winning
a tempo by threatening Bb6.} Kb7 14. Rd1 $1 {White suddenly changes the
direction of the attack, preparing to open the centre, when most of the black
pieces are undeveloped.} c5 {Holding off the break for a while.} ({If} 14...
Ne7 15. d4) ({In case of} 14... Qe8 {, White can try} 15. f3 g4 16. Qf2 $1 c5
17. b4 {, opening the queenside.}) 15. c3 (15. b4 cxb4 16. d4 Qc6) 15... g4 $1
(15... Qc6 16. b4) (15... Ne7 16. d4) 16. h4 $1 Ne7 17. d4 $1 {Black was just
one move (Nc6) short to prevent the catastrophe. The opening of the centre
underlines White's huge advantage in development.} exd4 (17... cxd4 18. cxd4
Nc6 19. d5 Nd4 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Rxd4 Bc5 22. Rd3) 18. cxd4 Qe6 (18... Qb5 19.
Qc3) 19. Qc3 Qxe4 {Burning all the bridges.} 20. dxc5 Nd5 {The game comes to
its critical point.} ({In case of} 20... Rxd1 21. Rxd1 Nd5 22. Na5+ Kc8 23. Qd2
bxa5 {White has to find the very important move} 24. c6 $1 ({If} 24. Qxd5 Qxd5
25. Rxd5 c6 {is only equal.}) 24... Bd6 25. Qxd5 Qxd5 26. Rxd5 $18 {White
should be able to win this.}) 21. c6+ $2 ({Glek misses to finish the attack in
style with} 21. Rxd5 $1 Rxd5 22. cxb6 $18 {, completely ruining the black
king's position.} Rh7 (22... c6 23. Qxf6) 23. Na5+ Rxa5 24. bxc7 Rxc7 25. Qxa5
Rc6 26. Qxh5) 21... Kc8 $1 ({Probably Glek was counting on} 21... Ka7 {, when
after} 22. Qd3 Qxd3 23. Rxd3 Bb4 24. Rfd1 Nxe3 25. Rxd8 Rxd8 26. Rxd8 Nxc4 27.
Rd4 $1 {the endgame should be winning for White.} b5 28. b3 Bc3 (28... Bc5 29.
Rd5 $1) 29. Rd3 Be5 30. bxc4 bxc4 31. Rd5 $1 Kb6 32. Kf1 Kxc6 33. Rd8 $18) 22.
Qb3 Nxe3 23. Rxd8+ Kxd8 24. Nxe3 Qxc6 25. Qd3+ Kc8 26. Qxa6+ Kb8 27. g3 Bc5 $15
{Although Mamedyarov gets off lightly in both games, the risky approach with 5.
..Bf3 and long castle didn't find many followers. The reason is more than
obvious: While it is true that Black can manage h5, g5 and g4 quickly, White
can move the queen away from f3 and answer g5-g4 with h4, keeping the kingside
closed. But when such a situation appears on the queenside and White executes
the break b4-b5, there is no such easy and safe way for Black to prevent the
opening of the files. Even if Black somehow avoids the catastrophe, White can
execute the alternative plan - the breakthrough in the centre with d3-d4.} *

[Event "URS-ch26 Final"]
[Site "Tbilisi"]
[Date "1959.01.27"]
