{.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. Bxc6 ({The only advantage of
taking on c6 on move 5 instead of move 6 is that White preserves the option to
castle long.} 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3) 5... dxc6 6. d3 Nd7 (6... Bd6 $1 {
is more precise - see the theoretical section.}) 7. Nbd2 Be7 ({In case of} 7...
Bd6 8. Nc4 O-O {White could try the similar aproach} 9. h4 $5 Re8 (9... b5 10.
Ne3 Nb6 11. h5) 10. h5 $1 h6 (10... Nf6 $2 11. h6 $1) (10... Nf8 11. Nh4 Be6
12. h6 g6 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Qf3 d5 15. Bd2 f6 16. O-O-O {, with a sharp
position with mutual chances.}) 11. g4 $1 (11. Nh4 Nf8 12. Qf3 Ne6 13. Nf5 Nd4
$11) 11... Nf8 12. g5 Bg4 13. Ne3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 {, with a devastating attack.}
Qxg5 (14... hxg5 15. h6 $18) 15. Nf5 Qf6 16. Rg1 $18) 8. Nc4 Bf6 (8... f6 $6 {
is a typical inaccuracy, allowing White to activate his knight toward f5.} 9.
Nh4 $1 {/\ Qh5} (9. Ne3 Nc5 10. O-O Ne6 11. Nf5 O-O 12. N3h4 g6) 9... Nf8 10.
Nf5 (10. Qf3 h5 $1) 10... Bxf5 11. exf5 Qd7 12. Qh5+ g6 13. fxg6 Nxg6 14. Bd2
O-O-O 15. O-O-O {, and White should preserve at least a small advantage due to
his better pawn structure.}) 9. Qe2 $1 {Preparing long castling is the most
aggressive approach. Before Black manages his piece coordination with 0-0, Re8,
Nf8-g6 and Be6, White intends to start the kingside pawn storm g4-g5.} c5 {
Black postpones short castling to prevent the possible opening of the central
files with d3-d4.} ({In case of the immediate} 9... Qe7 {, preparing Nf8, very
unpleasant is} 10. Bd2 $1 Nf8 11. d4 $1 Ng6 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Ncxe5 Bxe5 14.
Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bc3 {, and White has the advantage}) 10. Bd2 (10. a4 {, blocking
the queenside pawns, has one significant drawback: If Black castles long, it
will be difficult to build an attack there.} b6 $1 (10... O-O $6 11. b3 Re8 12.
Bb2 b6 13. h4 Bb7 14. g4 $1 b5 15. Ne3 $40) 11. b3 Bb7 12. Bb2 Qe7 $1 13. Ne3
O-O-O $1) (10. g4 $5 {is an interesting option, but Gufeld didn't want to show
his hand too early.}) 10... O-O $6 {Analysing the game, one can easily
conclude that this is the decisive mistake.} ({Much safer would be to play
useful moves, waiting to castle to the same side as White.} 10... Qe7 11. g4 h6
12. h4 Qe6 13. Rg1 b5 14. Ne3 Bb7) 11. g4 $1 {Having the better piece activity,
White can start a crushing attack immediately. The threat is g4-g5, so Black
practically has no choice but to weaken his kingside - considerably
facilitating the attack.} b5 12. Ne3 g6 13. h4 Nb8 14. O-O-O Nc6 15. Rdg1 $1 {
White sets everything ready for the final assault.} Be6 16. Kb1 ({Very strong
was the immediate} 16. Nf5 $1 Kh8 17. g5 Bg7 18. h5 $1 gxf5 19. h6 $18) 16...
Nb4 {Tal is trying to create counterplay and distract the opponent's attention
from the kingside.} (16... a5 17. g5 Bg7 18. Ng4) 17. Bxb4 {There is no way to
tolerate the knight, which in the hands of the "great magician" Tal may
suddenly turn into a dragon.} (17. a3 $1 a5 18. Nf5 $1 Ba2+ 19. Ka1 gxf5 20.
gxf5+ Kh8 21. Ng5 $18) 17... cxb4 18. g5 $6 (18. Nf5 $1 Kh8 19. Qe3 {is the
most precise, for instance} gxf5 20. gxf5 Bd7 21. Qh6 Rg8 22. Rxg8+ Kxg8 23.
Rg1+ Kh8 24. Ng5 {leads to a quick mate.}) 18... Bg7 19. Ng4 $6 {Giving Tal
the chance to escape.} (19. h5 Qd7 20. Nh2 {was the most natural way to
continue the attack.}) 19... f5 $2 {Breaking the rule to avoid pawn moves on
the flank where the opponent is attacking. The correct solution was to trade
one of the bishops, trying to slow down White's attack.} (19... Bxg4 $1 20.
Rxg4 Qd7 21. Rg3 a5 22. h5 a4 23. Rgh3 Rfd8 $1 {Threatening b3, to take over
the initiative.} 24. Qd1 Kf8 $1 25. Nd2 c5 26. Nf1 a3 27. b3 Qd4 28. Qc1 c4 $40
) 20. gxf6 Bxg4 21. Rxg4 (21. f7+ Rxf7 22. Rxg4 Qf6 23. Rg3 Raf8 24. h5) 21...
Qxf6 22. Rh3 a5 23. h5 {Black's kingside collapses.} Ra6 24. hxg6 hxg6 25. Rg2
{/\ Nh4} b3 {Desperado.} 26. axb3 a4 27. Nh4 axb3 28. Rxg6 Rfa8 {Tal even
manages to create a threat of mate in 1.} 29. cxb3 Qf7 30. Rxg7+ $1 $18 {
Gufeld concludes the attack with a fine combination.} Kxg7 31. Nf5+ Kg8 32.
Qg4+ Rg6 33. Ne7+ Kg7 34. Nxg6 Qxb3 (34... Qxg6 35. Qd7+ $18) 35. Nxe5+ Kf6 36.
Qg6+ Kxe5 37. d4+ 1-0

