1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Nc3 $5 {Nowadays it is not at all
easy to trouble the Berlin Defence. Having unsuccessfully tried all the
classical ways, now White is going back to long-forgotten lines by combining
the Spanish with the Four Knights. The main idea of 5.Nc3 is to wait for Black
to castle short and raise the tension on the kingside. Later on, White may
castle long, but there is also the option of leaving the king in the centre,
to ensure oneself against possible counterattacks on the queenside.} O-O {
Anand is going for the mainline. Of course Black can avoid the aforementioned
plan.} (5... a6 $5 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Qd4 (7... Bxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Qd4+ 9. Be3
Qxe5 10. h3 O-O 11. Rf1 Rd8 12. Qf3) 8. Be3 Qxe5 9. d4 Qe7 10. dxc5 Nxe4 11.
Qd4 Bf5 12. O-O-O {Karjakin- Onischuk Baku 2015. Although Black is not lost,
he will not have an easy time defending his slightly worse opposite-coloured
bishop ending.}) (5... d6 6. Na4 $5 {gains the bishop pair, but I am doubtful
that this is sufficient for an advantage.} Bb6 7. Nxb6 axb6 8. c3 Bd7 9. Ba4
Ne7 $1 (9... O-O 10. Bc2 Ne7 11. Bg5 Ng6 12. h4 $1 {Short,N -Aronian,L
Reykjavik 2004}) 10. Bc2 Ng6 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O {, and Black didn't have any
problems in Carlsen,M -Anand,V London 2012}) 6. Bxc6 $1 dxc6 7. h3 ({One idea
worth analysing is} 7. Bg5 $5 {Bartel,M -Balogh,C Budapest 2014} h6 8. Bh4 Bg4
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Be7 11. g4 $1 Nd7 12. Bg3 Bh4 13. O-O-O $40 {This is
analysed in the theoretical section.}) (7. Be3 $5 {is also worthy of attention.
Look at the following performance by Carlsen at the recent online top event.}
Bd6 (7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 Re8 9. h3 {White would have all the play}) 8. Bg5 $1 Qe7
(8... Re8 9. h3 c5 10. Nd5 {Carlsen,M -Karjakin,S /Riadh 2017}) 9. h3 Re8 10.
g4 Qe6 11. Nh4 Nd7 12. Nf5 Nc5 13. h4 Bf8 14. h5 f6 15. Be3 Qf7 16. f4 exf4 17.
Bxf4 b5 18. Qf3 Ne6 19. Be3 Bb7 20. O-O-O b4 21. Na4 c5 22. h6 g6 23. Ng7 $1 {
, with a decisive attack for White in Carlsen,M -Grischuk,A chess24.com 2020})
7... Nd7 ({In a later game, Grischuk shows the right move order.} 7... Re8 {
Caruana,F -Grischuk,A Saint Louis 2017} 8. Ne2 (8. Be3 {Dominguez Perez,L -So,
W Saint Louis 2017} Bd6 9. Ne2 c5 10. Ng3) 8... Nd7 9. Be3 Bb4+ 10. c3 Bf8 11.
Qc2 c5 12. O-O-O Nb8 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Kb1 f6 15. Nf5 Qd7 16. g4 Qf7 17. Rhg1 Be6
18. b3 Kh8 19. g5 a5 {, and it looks like Black's attack develops faster.}) 8.
Be3 Bd6 ({In case of} 8... Bxe3 9. fxe3 Re8 10. Qe2 $1 Nf8 11. Qf2 $1 {,
preparing Nh4-f5,} Ng6 12. O-O-O $1 b5 13. g4 a5 14. g5 a4 15. h4 b4 16. h5 Nf8
17. Nb1 Ra5 18. g6 $1 {, and White is the first to break open the kingside.}
fxg6 (18... hxg6 19. h6 $1) 19. hxg6 Nxg6 20. Rdg1) 9. Ne2 $1 Re8 10. g4 Nc5 (
10... Nf8 11. Ng3 Ne6 12. Nf5) 11. Ng3 Ne6 12. Nf5 c5 13. h4 {Both sides
succeeded in their middlegame plans - White provided an excellent square for
his knight, just in front of Black's king, while Black completed the manoeuvre
Nd7-c5-e6 and is ready to jump to d4.} a5 $1 {Preparing a4-a3 and employing
the queenside rook.} (13... Nd4 {will be met by} 14. c3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Be6 16.
c4 $1 {, and White has the ideal situation, as Black's counterattack cannot
reach his king, for instance} Bf8 17. Rd1 b5 18. h5 c6 19. h6 g6 20. Ng7 Qa5+
21. Kf1 Re7 22. Nh5 $1 Rb7 23. Nf6+ Kh8 24. Kg2 bxc4 25. dxc4 Rxb2 26. Rd7 $1
$18) 14. h5 $1 {Caruana is not in a hurry to castle, as his king feels safe in
the centre.} (14. a4 Nd4 15. Nd2 Bf8 16. h5) 14... Ra6 (14... a4 $1 {was more
precise.} 15. g5 Nd4 16. N3h4 $1 Bf8 17. g6 Ra6 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. gxf7+ Kxf7
20. Qf3 Kg8 21. Rg1 Rb6 $132) 15. Qd2 ({It was better to start with
stabilising the position on the queenside by playing} 15. a4 $1 Bd7 (15... Nd4
16. Nd2 $1) 16. Rg1 (16. b3 Nf4 17. Rg1) 16... Nf4 17. Nd2 $1) 15... Nd4 $1 (
15... a4 16. O-O-O Nd4 17. N3h4 Be6 18. g5 Bxa2 19. g6 Bf8 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21.
Rdg1 {would be very difficult to evaluate, but one thing is clear - White's
attack was faster.}) 16. Rh3 {This looks ugly, but there is nothing better.} (
16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Kf1 a4 18. Kg2 Rb6 19. b3 h6) (16. N3h4 Bxf5 17. gxf5 c4)
16... Bf8 17. O-O-O {White's king can become a target on the queenside, but
there was no other way to increase the attacking potential.} Be6 (17... b5 18.
Kb1 a4 19. Rdh1 b4 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21. g5) 18. Kb1 {The only way to protect the
pawn, as} (18. c4 a4 19. Rg1 b5 {would be quite bad for White.}) 18... f6 $1 ({
Avoiding} 18... Nxf3 19. Rxf3 c4 20. dxc4 Qxd2 21. Bxd2 Bxc4 {, with a more or
less equal endgame.}) 19. c3 Nxf3 (19... Qd7 20. cxd4 cxd4 21. Bxd4 exd4 22.
N3xd4 Bf7 23. Qc2) 20. Rxf3 c4 ({Here Black missed the best defence} 20... h6
$1 {, freezing the kingside, when the only way to continue the attack is to
sacrifice a piece.} 21. Rg3 Qd7 22. f4 exf4 23. Bxf4 Qf7 24. a3 b5 25. Bxh6 {
A desperate attempt, however rather incorrect.} gxh6 26. Nxh6+ Bxh6 27. Qxh6
Qg7 28. Qf4 Qg5) 21. Qc2 $1 {With this move Caruana takes over the initiative.}
(21. g5 Qxd3+ 22. Qxd3 cxd3 23. gxf6 gxf6 24. Rg3+ Kf7 25. Rxd3 {is only equal,
while}) ({, of course,} 21. dxc4 {loses on the spot after} Bxf5 22. Qxd8 (22.
gxf5 Rd6) 22... Bxe4+ 23. Kc1 Rxd8 24. Rxd8 Bxf3 25. Bc5 Rd6 $19) 21... cxd3
22. Rxd3 Qc8 23. g5 $1 {Caruana grabs his chance.} fxg5 (23... Qb8) 24. Bxg5
Bf7 (24... h6 25. Bc1 Bf7 26. Rg3 Kh7 27. Rd1 Qe6 28. b3 a4) 25. h6 $1 {
Now White is back in the game.} gxh6 {A sad moment for Black, as he is forced
to completely ruin his kingside.} (25... g6 26. Ne3 $1 {/\ Nd5-f6} c6 {is
refuted by} 27. Rxf7 Kxf7 28. Qb3+ Qe6 29. Qxb7+ $18) 26. Bc1 Qe6 27. b3 a4 (
27... b5 28. Ne3) 28. c4 axb3 29. axb3 Qc6 30. Rg3+ Kh8 31. Rd1 b5 {The
tension is very high, everything depends on who will be the first to create
mating threats.} 32. c5 $1 (32. Bb2 bxc4 33. Rd8 Ra5 $1) 32... b4 $2 {Having
protected everything, Anand loses his sense of danger. The idea of his last
move is to play Ra5 and take with the rook, defending on e5. But he runs into
a sudden refutation.} (32... Qxc5 $1 {practically forces a draw.} 33. Qxc5 Bxc5
34. Rd7 Bg6 35. Bxh6 Bf8 $11) 33. Bb2 $1 {It is all over now, Black's defence
collapses.} Bg6 {Blocking the g-file does not solve the problem.} ({
Unfortunately,} 33... Ra5 {meets a beautiful refutation:} 34. Rd8 $1 Qxc5 (
34... Rxc5 35. Bxe5+ $3 {Double pin!}) 35. Rxe8 Bxe8 36. f4 $1 Bg6 37. fxe5 Kg8
38. e6 Qxc2+ 39. Kxc2 Bd6 40. Rf3 Bxf5 41. exf5 $18) (33... Qxc5 34. Qxc5 Bxc5
35. Rd7 Bg6 36. f4 Bd6 37. fxe5 Bxe5 38. Bxe5+ Rxe5 39. Rd8+ Be8 40. Ng7 Rxe4
41. Rxe8+ Rxe8 42. Nxe8 Rg6 43. Rd3 c5 44. Nd6 $18) 34. Rd5 $1 Qb5 35. Rg1 $1
c6 36. Rxe5 Rxe5 37. Bxe5+ Kg8 38. Bd4 (38. Bb2 Kf7 39. Qd1) 38... Kf7 39. Nh4
$18 {Black's king is defenceless.} 1-0

