1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 (5. c3 {and}) (5. O-O {
are other lines.}) 5... dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O {We are going to see that castling
early is not as safe as it looks.} (6... Bg4 $1 {is known to be an equaliser
since Anand,V-Carlsen,M Chennai 2013.} 7. h3 Bh5 $1 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 Nd7 9.
Qg3 Qf6 10. Nc4 O-O 11. O-O Rfe8 12. a4 $14) 8. Nf1 (8. Nc4 Nd7 9. g4 Bg6 10.
Qe2 Qe7 11. Bd2 O-O-O 12. O-O-O) (8. g4 Bg6 9. Nxe5 $2 {does not work because
of} Qd4 $1) 8... Nd7 9. Ng3 Bxf3 $1 10. Qxf3 g6 $11) (6... Be6 $1 {is also
more precise than 0-0.}) 7. Nc4 $1 Nd7 8. Be3 $1 Bxe3 (8... Bd6 9. h4 $5 (9.
O-O Re8 10. a4 Nf8 11. a5 Ng6) 9... b5 {Yu,Y -Erdos,V Tsaghkadzor 2015} 10.
Nxd6 $1 cxd6 11. h5 h6 12. g4 Nb6 13. Rg1 f6 14. Qd2 Kh7 15. O-O-O {White's
attack develops much faster.}) 9. Nxe3 f6 10. h4 $1 {Underlining the advantage
of not having castled yet. This is the only way to trouble Black's position.
White's idea is to play h4-h5 followed by Nh4 and Qf3. If he manages to
establish control of the f5-square, he will have the pleasant choice between
the initial plan with long castling and short castling followed by the break
f2-f4.} (10. Qd2 Nc5 11. O-O-O {, with sharp play in Buksa,N-Doluhanova,E Kiev
2018}) 10... Nc5 (10... Qe7 11. Qe2 Nc5 12. h5 $1) 11. h5 $1 h6 {I am doubtful
that Black should play this move, as it only creates more weaknesses. But
White has good attacking chances anyway.} (11... Be6 12. Nh4 Qd7 ({Black must
be aware of the trick} 12... Qe7 $2 13. Ng6 $1 $18) 13. O-O $1 {White can now
combine the kingside attacking plan with the rather positional approach based
on f2-f4.} Na4 14. Qe1 $1 b5 15. b3 Nb6 16. f4 $1 $36) (11... Ne6 12. Nf5 Qe8
13. N3h4 c5 14. Qg4 $1 Kh8 $2 15. Ng6+ $1 $18) 12. Qd2 {White goes for the
initial plan with long castling. But there was another less risky option.} (12.
O-O Be6 13. Nh4 Qd7 14. Ng6 Rfe8 15. Qf3 a5 16. Qg3 a4 17. f4 $36 {, with a
White initiative.}) 12... Be6 13. Nh4 (13. Qc3 $1 {was a better option again,
and if} Qd6 (13... Na4 $6 14. Qa5 Nb6 15. d4 exd4 16. O-O-O $40) 14. Nh4 Rfd8
15. O-O {, with the idea f4.}) (13. O-O-O a5) 13... Qd7 14. Nef5 {White is
playing very smartly: First he increases the pressure on the kingside, waiting
for the best moment to castle long.} Bxf5 15. Nxf5 Ne6 16. O-O-O (16. O-O {
is already not that strong due to} Nd4 $1 (16... Qf7 17. Qd1 Nf4 18. g3 Nxh5
19. Kg2 $40) (16... Nf4 $2 17. g3 Nxh5 18. Kg2 $16) 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 $11) 16... c5
17. g3 Nd4 18. Nh4 $5 {Avoiding the trade of knights is obligatory if White
wants to create an attack.} (18. Ne3 b5 19. c3 Ne6 20. f4 a5 21. Rhf1 a4 {
is unclear.}) 18... Qf7 {Naturally Black goes for the pawn, but it is a
double-edged decision. Anyway, White is going to push f4, with unpleasant
pressure.} (18... Rfe8 19. c3 Ne6 20. f4) 19. Kb1 $5 ({There was a much better
way to sacrifice a pawn. In case of} 19. c3 Nc6 20. Kb1 {Black can't just take
the pawn,} Qxh5 {, due to} 21. Qe3 $1 b6 22. Nf5 {, with a crushing attack.}
Qg6 (22... Qf7 23. Rxh6 $18) 23. Rh4 $1 Rf7 24. Qf3 $18) 19... Qxh5 20. c3 Ne6
$1 21. Nf5 ({The immediate} 21. f4 $1 {was much stronger.} Rad8 $1 (21... Rfd8
22. Nf5 Qf3 23. fxe5 fxe5 24. Nxh6+) 22. f5 $1 (22. Nf5 Qf3 23. fxe5 fxe5 24.
Nxh6+ gxh6 25. Qxh6 Rf6) 22... Ng5 23. Ng6 Qf3 24. Nxf8 Kxf8 25. Rhf1 Qxg3 26.
Qe2 b6 27. Rg1 Qf3 28. Qxf3 Nxf3 29. Rh1 Ke7 30. Kc2 Ng5 {, and White only has
some technical difficulties with the realisation of the advantage.}) (21. Qe3
$1 {was also much stronger than Nf5, for instance} Qg5 22. Qe2 Rad8 23. Nf5
Rfe8 24. f4 $1 {, and Black is busted.}) 21... Qf3 $1 22. Nh4 Qh5 23. Nf5 $6 {
Taking the draw.} (23. f4 $1) (23. Qe3 $5) 23... Qf3 24. Nh4 Qh5 25. Nf5
1/2-1/2

[Event "CHN Team Men 2016"]
