{In this game Li Chao reveals a new and very aggressive Anti-Berlin concept.} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O {What could
be safer than castling quickly? But Li Chao proves that early castling is
quite a risky affair here.} ({I don't believe in White's advantage after} 6...
Bg4 $1 7. h3 Bh5 {, for instance} 8. Nf1 (8. Nc4 Nd7 9. g4 Bg6 10. Qe2 Qe7 11.
Bd2 O-O-O) 8... Nd7 9. Ng3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 g6 {Anand- Carlsen - 7th game Chennai
2013}) 7. Qe2 Nd7 {This move always looks very passive to me. Black should
avoid blocking the bishop when possible.} ({For example Black could start with
} 7... Re8 $5 {, and in case of} 8. Nc4 {respond with the immediate} b5 {
Anand, V -So,W Leuven 2016} 9. Ne3 (9. Ncxe5 Qd6 10. g3 $1 (10. c3 Bb6 11. d4
c5) 10... Bb6 $1 ({But not} 10... Rxe5 11. Bf4 Ng4 12. h3 $1) 11. Bf4 Nh5 $132)
9... a5 (9... Nh5 $5 10. g3 Bh3) 10. O-O Nh5 11. g3 Bh3 12. Rd1 Qf6 13. Nh4 Nf4
$1 14. Qf3 Bxe3 ({It was better to try} 14... h5 $5) ({or} 14... Qg5 $5) 15.
fxe3 Bg2 16. Qg4 Bh3 17. Qf3 Bg2 {, and a draw was agreed.}) (7... Bg4 8. h3
Bxf3 9. Nxf3 Nd7 {would be in White's favour - see game 10
Sijugirov-Pridorozhni - Russia 2018.}) 8. Nc4 Bd6 (8... Re8 $1 9. Bd2 b5 10.
Ne3 Nf8 {was played in the highly important game Vitiugov,N -Karjakin,S
Khanty-Mansiysk 2019} 11. h4 $1 a5 12. a4 Bb6 13. h5 Ne6 14. Qd1 $1 Nd4 {
looks like Black is doing fine, but Vitiugov reveals some hidden resources.}
15. h6 $1 g6 16. Nxd4 Qxd4 (16... exd4 17. Nf1 Be6 18. Qf3 Qe7 19. Nh2 f5 20.
O-O $16) 17. axb5 (17. Qf3 Qd8 18. O-O $14) 17... cxb5 18. Qf3 Qd8 19. Nd5 $14)
9. Bd2 Re8 ({Black can start immediate counterplay, as in the game
Vitiugov-Karjakin.} 9... b5 $1 10. Ne3 $1 (10. Na5 Nc5 11. Nxc6 Qe8 12. Ncxe5 (
12. Na5 f5 $1) 12... Bxe5 13. d4 Nxe4 14. dxe5 Bb7 $44) 10... Nc5 11. h4 (11.
O-O $1 {would be safer.}) 11... Ne6 12. Nf5 {Now in the game
Oparin-Loprarizangeneh Aeroflot 2016 Black went for the aggressive} Nf4 {
, but after} (12... a5 $5 13. g3 Re8 14. h5 b4 $13) 13. Bxf4 exf4 14. Nxd6 cxd6
15. Qd2 Qf6 16. Qc3 $1 {White achieved an advantage in the endgame.}) 10. h4 $1
{With this move White reveals his aggressive intentions. The whole concept is
based on starting an anticipatory pawn storm, and the intention to castle only
when there are certain preconditions for the final assault on the black king.
The idea is to avoid Black's queenside counterattack in case of an early long
castling.} Nf8 (10... Nf6 11. Nh2 $1) (10... b5 11. Na5 Nb8 12. h5 h6 13. Nh4
c5 14. g4 $5) ({Another fine attacking game was Wei Yi-Navara,D Wijk aan Zee
NED 2016, which continued} 10... c5 11. h5 h6 $6 {Creating a lever on h6.} 12.
O-O-O $1 Nb8 13. Rdg1 Nc6 14. g4 f6 {, and now there follows a beautiful
finish.} 15. g5 $1 fxg5 16. Nxg5 Nd4 (16... hxg5 17. h6 g4 18. hxg7 Nd4 19. Qe3
Qf6 20. Rh8+ Kxg7 21. Rh6 $18) 17. Qd1 hxg5 18. Bxg5 (18. h6 Qf6 19. hxg7 Kf7
20. f4 $18) 18... Be7 19. Be3 Bf6 20. h6 Re7 21. hxg7 Rxg7 22. Qh5 {, with a
quick mate.}) 11. h5 $1 h6 $6 {This is what White was looking for. In the game
Wei Yi-Navara Black made a similar mistake, while in the Caruana-Anand game we
saw the correct way to handle Black's defence, f7-f6!, and h7-h6 only when it
was necessary.} (11... Ne6 {is the most logical continuation , when after} 12.
O-O-O c5 13. Qf1 f6 14. Nh4 Nd4 15. c3 Nc6 16. Nf5 $36 {White's attack has
already started in Caruana, Fabiano - Karjakin,Sergey Tata Steel-A 78th Wijk
aan Zee (9), 26.01.2016.}) 12. O-O-O $1 {It is time to activate the last
attacking unit - the rook a1! After Black played h7-h6, White has ideal
conditions to finish the game quickly by g4-g5. Castling long will make it
possible to support the attack with Rdg1.} Qf6 ({It looks like g2-g4 is
already a strong threat, for instance} 12... c5 13. g4 $1 Bxg4 14. Rdg1 Qd7 15.
Rh4 $1 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qe6 17. Rhg4 $18) ({It is too late for the counterattack} 
12... b5 13. Ne3 Ne6 14. Rdg1 Nd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 16. Nd1 f5 17. f4 $1 Qe7 18.
Nf2 $1 {/\ g4} fxe4 19. dxe4 Qf7 20. Kb1 Bxf4 21. g4 $1 Bxd2 22. Qxd2 Re5 23.
g5 $1 hxg5 24. h6 $18 {, with a winning attack.}) 13. Rdg1 $1 b5 (13... Bg4 {
only helps White. After} 14. Ne3 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Kh8 {White has} 16. f4 $1 exf4
17. Bc3 Be5 18. Ng4 $18) 14. Ne3 Qe6 (14... Ne6 15. g4 $1 Nd4 (15... Nf4 16.
Qd1 $1) 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Nf5 Bf8 (17... Bxf5 18. gxf5 $40) 18. Nh4 Qe6 19. Kb1
f6 20. f4 $18 {, and Black will be smashed on the kingside.}) 15. Kb1 {The
last moment of calm before the storm - Black has no way to defend against
g4-g5.} Nh7 16. Nf5 Bf8 17. N3h4 $1 Qf6 ({The situation is really bad for
Black, as in case of} 17... f6 {White has} 18. Qg4) 18. g4 Ng5 19. Nf3 (19.
Bxg5 $1 {was the most simple way.} hxg5 (19... Qxg5 20. Nf3 $18 {/\ g5}) 20.
Nf3 c5 21. Qe3 $18) 19... Nxf3 20. Qxf3 Bxf5 21. gxf5 Kh7 {Black manages to
simplify the position, eliminating some of White's most dangerous pieces. But
without any active counterplay on the other wing, Black's king is doomed.} 22.
Qg4 ({Again the more straightforward plan was to triple the heavy pieces on
the g-file and play f4.} 22. Rg4 c5 23. Rhg1 Rad8 24. Qg3 c4 25. f4 cxd3 26.
cxd3 b4 (26... c5 27. Bc3) 27. fxe5 Qxe5 28. Bf4 Qd4 29. f6 $1 Qxf6 30. e5 $18)
22... Bd6 (22... Bc5 23. Rg2 b4) 23. Rg2 Rg8 24. Qh3 Kh8 $1 {Black is alert,
as White had a very nasty threat.} (24... c5 $2 25. Rg6 $1 $18) 25. Rhg1 ({
Missing another ideal opportunity.} 25. d4 $1 c5 26. dxe5 Bxe5 27. f4 Bxb2 28.
e5 $18) 25... Rae8 $1 {Preventing both f4 and d4.} 26. Be3 {One possible idea
to break Black's defense could be f3, Bf2-h4.} Be7 $1 {Preparing to install
the bishop on f6.} 27. Rg4 c5 28. Qh2 (28. f3 c4 29. Bf2 cxd3 30. cxd3 Qd6) (
28. Qf1 a5 29. f4 $1 b4 30. Qf2 $18) 28... a6 (28... c4 29. f4 Bd6 30. Qf2 exf4
31. Bxf4 Bxf4 32. Rxf4 Rd8 33. Rf3 a5 $16) 29. f3 ({Everything is set to start
the second wave of the attack.} 29. f4 Bd6 30. Qf2 exf4 (30... c4 31. fxe5 Bxe5
32. d4) 31. Bxc5 $18) 29... c4 $1 30. dxc4 bxc4 31. Qd2 Rd8 32. Qc3 Qc6 33. a3
({Avoiding the possible counterattack after} 33. Qxe5 Bf6 34. Qc5 Qb7) 33...
Bf6 34. R4g2 Kh7 35. b3 Rb8 36. Ka1 Rgd8 (36... Be7 $5) 37. Qxc4 Qxc4 38. bxc4
{In the end White was happy to achieve a much better endgame.} c6 39. Rd2 Be7
40. Rxd8 Rxd8 41. Kb2 (41. c5 $1) 41... Bg5 {Trying to get counterplay, but it
is too late.} (41... Rb8+ 42. Ka2 Rd8) 42. Bxg5 hxg5 43. Rxg5 Kh6 44. Rg1 Rd2
45. c5 Rf2 46. Rd1 $1 Rxf3 47. Rd6+ Kxh5 48. Rxc6 Kg5 49. Rxa6 Rh3 50. f6 $1 {
Blocking the path of the king.} gxf6 51. Ra8 f5 52. c6 Rh6 53. c7 {The amazing
thing about this game is that Li Chao, who is an outstanding tactician, like
most of the Chinese players, prefered to avoid the risk and to convert his
advantage by transition to the endgame.} 1-0

[Event "Jiayuguan (m/4) 133/124"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2017.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Game 9"]
[Black "Yu, Yangyi - Grischuk"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "72"]
[EventDate "2017.??.??"]

{After so many nice games won by White, it is time to see the following
powerful demonstration of Black's attacking chances on the queenside.} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Be3 ({Usually White plays} 6.
h3 $1) ({or} 6. Nbd2) 6... Bd6 $1 7. h3 Nd7 ({It is strange that in the vast
majority of games Black prefers 7...Nd7 over the most natural and probably
stronger option} 7... Be6 {Anand,V -Nakamura,H Zuerich 2017} 8. Nc3 $5 Nd7 9.
Ng5 Nf8 10. O-O f6 11. Nxe6 Nxe6 $11) 8. Nbd2 O-O (8... c5 9. Nc4 Qe7 {
/\Nb8-c6 or Nf8-e6, preserving the option of castling long.}) 9. Qe2 ({Before
this game White usually played} 9. O-O {Nakamura,H -Kasimdzhanov,R Baku 2014,
but Black achieved comfortable equality after} Re8 10. c3 c5 11. a3 a5 12. Re1
Nf8 13. d4 cxd4 14. cxd4 exd4 15. Nxd4 Be5 $11) 9... Re8 10. O-O-O {Because
White already spent a tempo on h2-h3, it looks inappropriate to adopt the plan
with h3-h4-h5 and Nh4, g4 and Nf5. So White basically has no other choice but
to enter a classical opposite side castling position.} Qe7 11. g4 $1 {White's
obvious goal is to transfer the knight to f5: Nf1-g3-f5.} Nc5 $1 {After this
move it becomes obvious that White's king is quite vulnerable on c1. White is
obliged to take some defensive measures, which gives Black time to start his
attack.} 12. Kb1 (12. Nf1 Na4 $1 13. c4 Ba3 $1 {is the essence of Black's idea.
} 14. Rd2 Nc3 15. Qe1 Qb4 $19) 12... Na4 $1 13. Nc4 {Another obligatory move,
which gives Black another tempo for his attack.} (13. g5 $2 Ba3 $1 $19) (13.
Nb3 b5 14. Bc1 a5 {is also not much fun for White.}) 13... b5 14. Nxd6 (14. Bg5
$5 f6 15. Nxd6 cxd6 16. Bd2 $11) 14... cxd6 15. Qd2 $5 {Preparing Nh4-f5.} (15.
Rdg1 d5 16. Bc1 b4 {would not change the course of the game by much.}) 15... c5
$1 16. Nh4 $1 b4 ({Of course not} 16... Qxh4 $2 17. Bg5 $18) 17. Nf5 Qe6 18.
Qe2 $1 {Yu Yangui is trying his best to combine attack and defence, hoping to
stay as solid as possible while creating obstacles for Grischuk on every move.}
(18. f4 d5 19. Qf2 d4 20. Bc1 Nc3+) 18... d5 19. Bd2 (19. exd5 {The only way
to keep the fight open was to look for counterplay in the centre.} Qxd5 20. Bd2
$13) 19... d4 $1 20. Rdf1 Rb8 {Nc3 is already hanging over White's head like
the sword of Damokles.} 21. Ka1 Qa6 (21... b3 $1 {was winning on the spot.} 22.
cxb3 Rxb3 23. axb3 Qxb3 24. Bc1 Be6 $19) 22. Qd1 Nc3 {There was one more
winning idea: c5-c4.} (22... Be6 23. b3 c4 $1 24. dxc4 Bxc4 25. bxc4 Nc3 $19)
23. Bxc3 (23. bxc3 bxc3 24. Ne3 Qxa2+ $3 25. Kxa2 Re6 $19) 23... bxc3 24. b3
Rb5 $1 (24... c4 $5) 25. Ng3 {Sad necessity - to avoid a quick disaster on the
queenside, the knight retreats to c1 to help the defence.} (25. f4 exf4 26.
Rxf4 Be6 27. Rf2 Ra5 28. Qb1 Ra3) 25... Ra5 26. Qb1 Ra3 $19 27. f4 exf4 28.
Rxf4 Be6 29. Ne2 Rb8 30. Nc1 Qb6 {White has no defence against a5-a4. The game
is a complete disaster for White and a demonstration of the danger awaiting
him if he castles queenside castling too early.} 31. h4 a5 32. g5 a4 33. Rhf1
Qa7 34. R1f2 g6 35. Rf6 axb3 36. cxb3 Bxb3 0-1

[Event "71st ch-RUS HL 2018"]
[Site "Yaroslavl RUS"]
[Date "2018.06.28"]
[Round "3.4"]
[White "Game 10"]
[Black "Sjugirov, S - Pridorozhni"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "2018.06.26"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nbd2 O-O (6... Bg4 $1
{in my view is the most precise reply.}) 7. Qe2 Bg4 {Black prefers to part
with the bishop pair.} (7... Nd7 {is the most frequently played, while there
is also}) (7... Re8 8. Nc4 b5 $5 {, an original counterattacking idea,
realised in the game Anand-So 2016.}) 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Nxf3 Nd7 {The position is
already slightly better for White, who has the better structure. The logical
development would be to castle short and prepare f4. Instead, Sijugirov opts
for a more aggressive approach.} 10. h4 $1 {It might look like anti-chess to
move with the h-pawn twice during the first 10 moves, but as we have seen
already in games 8 and 9, it is the start of an original plan to create
weaknesses on the kingside before castling queenside} Re8 11. Bg5 $1 {Another
clever idea which Black didn't quite understand or just underestimated. White
wants to provoke f7-f6, which will serve as a lever to open files on the
kingside after g4-g5.} f6 ({It was preferable to try} 11... Qc8 {, but
nevertheless White's attack develops faster after} 12. O-O-O (12. h5 a5 13. Nh4
$5) 12... a5 13. g4 b5 14. Kb1 a4 15. Bc1 b4 16. g5 b3 17. h5 Qa6 18. g6 $1 $40
) 12. Bd2 Nf8 13. g4 $1 Ne6 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Rdg1 {White's attacking concept
is fully realised. The threat is g4-g5, forcing Black to switch to a passive
defence.} c5 16. g5 Rf8 17. Rh3 ({White could have tried} 17. g6 $1 {, which
in my view was the most principled way to finish the game with a mating attack.
} h6 18. Nh2 $1 {With the simple idea Qh5 and Ng4.} Nf4 (18... Nd4 19. Qh5 $18)
19. Bxf4 exf4 20. Qh5 f5 $1 (20... Bd6 21. Ng4 Qe7 22. Qd5+ Kh8 23. Nxh6) (
20... Qd7 21. Ng4 $18) 21. Nf3 {, and White has both a very strong initiative
and a huge positional advantage.} a5 (21... c4 22. dxc4 fxe4 23. Rd1 Qe8 24.
Qd5+ Kh8 25. Ne5 $18) 22. Ng5 Rf6 (22... Ra6 23. Nh7 Re8 24. Qxf5) 23. Nf7 Qd7
24. Re1 $1 fxe4 25. Rxe4 Bf8 26. Qf3 Re8 27. h5 $18) 17... Qd6 18. Rhg3 b5 $1 {
Catch me if you can! Black goes for a counterattack to distract White's
attention. It looks like White has achieved all he was dreaming of, but the
question is how to progress further and complete the attack.} 19. Kb1 a5 $1 {
Black is still a long way from creating threats, but rolling his queenside
pawns forward makes White a bit nervous.} 20. gxf6 (20. h5 {is pointless.} a4
21. h6 g6) ({It is too late for} 20. g6 h6 21. Nh2 Nf4 22. Bxf4 exf4 23. R3g2
a4 24. Qh5 a3 $1) ({, so White had the choice between the move in the game and
the sharper and riskier} 20. Nh2 Nd4 21. Qh5 $5) 20... Bxf6 21. Bg5 {
Exchanging the defender of g7 will definitely increase the power of White's
attack, but in a strategical sense it is a huge concession.} a4 $6 {Missing a
clever trick.} (21... Bxg5 22. Nxg5 Nf4 23. Qg4 Qe7 24. Nh3 $1 {would also be
somewhat better for White, for instance} Nxh3 25. Qxh3 Rf7 26. Rg5 Kh8 27. Qg3
Re8 28. Rf5 $1 {, but Black position looks defensible.}) 22. Bxf6 Rxf6 23. d4
$1 {A good attacking player should keep every single point of the board under
control. Here Siugirov finds a sudden opportunity to break Black's position,
using the hanging pawn on b5.} cxd4 24. Qxb5 {Now Black has certain problems
with the defence of his central pawn.} Raf8 $1 25. Nxe5 Rxf2 26. a3 $1 {
Stabilising the queenside and avoiding a catastrophe on the first rank.} Kh8 $1
{Black is definitely in the game, but White's king looks much safer.} 27. Rg4 (
27. Nd3 Rf1+ 28. Ka2 Rxg1 29. Rxg1 Qh2 30. Rc1 Qxh4 31. Qxa4 Qxe4 {, with an
extra pawn for Black.}) (27. h5 $1 {would be the most logical continuation.}
R2f4 28. Nc4 Qd8 29. Qxa4 Rxe4 30. h6 g6 31. Nd2 {, with a huge advantage for
White due to his better king's position.}) 27... Qb6 ({There was a sudden
chance to trouble White's king on the second rank.} 27... c6 $1 28. Nxc6 d3 $1
29. cxd3 Qh2 $1 {, and White can't avoid the idea 30...Nd4 31 Nd4 Rb8}) 28. Qc4
(28. Qxa4 $1 {Snatching the pawn.} Rb8 29. Nd3 Rf3 30. b3 {looks like the most
simple solution, but White doesn't want to give up the initiative so easily.})
28... Rb8 29. Nd3 Rf3 30. R4g2 $1 {Everything is covered. Black's
counterattack comes to a standstill.} c5 31. Qxa4 Qb7 32. Ka2 ({More precise
was} 32. Qc4 Qxe4 33. Re1 Re3 34. Rxe3 Qxe3 35. Rf2 $18) 32... Qxe4 33. Qd7 $1
{Increasing the tension in time trouble.} Rg8 34. h5 $1 Rf6 $1 {Defending
against h5-h6.} ({The counterattack does not work:} 34... c4 35. h6 g6 36. Re1
Re3 37. Rxe3 Qxe3 (37... dxe3 38. Rg4 $3) 38. Rg3 Qe4 (38... Qe2 39. Nf4 $1)
39. Rg4 Qe3 40. Qe7 Qxh6 41. Ne5 $18) ({In case of} 34... h6 {, White can
transpose to an easily winning endgame with} 35. Rg6 Ng5 36. Qc6 $18) 35. b3 $1
{, stopping the only threat c5-c4, when Black is in some kind of zugzwang.} (
35. h6 Rxh6 36. Rf2 {was also quite unpleasant.}) 35... Qe3 $2 (35... h6 36.
Rg6) (35... Rf5 36. h6) 36. Re1 (36. Qe7 $1 Qh6 37. Ne5 $18) 36... Qh6 37. Re5
(37. Rge2 Nf8 38. Qd5 $18) 37... c4 38. bxc4 Nf4 39. Re8 Ne6 (39... Nxg2 40.
Qc8 $18) 40. Ne5 Nf8 41. Nf7+ {Although White missed the best continuation of
the attack on move 17, he nevertheless enjoyed the much better chances in the
following sharp middlegame. But only a clever mind and the better observation
on Sijugirov's side helped him to overcome Black's resistance by suddenly
penetrating on the queenside.} 1-0

