[Event "HUN-ch10"]
[Site "Budapest"]
[Date "1954.12.14"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Game 1"]
[Black "Benko, P - Hajtun"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C85"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "57"]
[EventDate "1954.11.20"]
[EventRounds "17"]
[EventCountry "HUN"]

{The plan with f4 is the most aggressive tool in White's attacking repertoire
in the Exchange Spanish structures. White completely leaves the idea of
converting his pawn structure advantage in a later endgame behind. Instead he
looks for attacking chances in the arising dynamic and double-edged positions.
The plan with f4 is a very nice option for the following reasons: 1. After
eliminating the strong central pawn e5, White increases his central influence,
getting the option to build a strong central pawn duo e4&d4.2. White may
achieve a huge space advantage on the kingside after an eventual f4-f5.3.
White gets the semiopen f-file and may either create an outpost on f5 or
transfer his rook to the kingside via the third or fourth rank. Let's start
with some classical games, which clearly show the general ideas and themes in
White's concept. Pal Benko was one of the greatest theoreticians of the 20th
century. Many of his ideas, the most successful of which being the Benko
Gambit, have passed the test of time and are valid even now. In this game he
revealed the simple strategic concept behind the plan with f2-f4.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 $5 {The delayed Spanish
Exchange variation. The justification for losing a whole tempo (4.Ba4 and then
6.Bxc6) is that in the arising pawn structure, the knight on f6 is not on its
ideal place and Black has to spend time on its improvement.} dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 {
This is the most frequently played reply. Black defends the e5-pawn and starts
the strategically favourable transfer of the knight to d4 via f8-e6 or b8-c6} (
7... Bd6 $5) ({and} 7... Qd6 {are the logical alternatives}) ({, while} 7...
Bg4 {is also possible, but after} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {White fixes a small
advantage due to his better pawn structure.}) 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nc4 Bf6 {This
move looks a bit artificial, but Black hopes to improve the bishop by playing
g6, Bg7. The reason Black is avoiding the classical defence with f7- f6 is
that it gives White the option to start the fight for the initiative with an
immediate Nh4!?} (9... f6 10. Nh4) ({But} 9... Bd6 {is a playable alternative,
which however may cost Black the bishop pair advantage. Analysing White's
attacking models, we would see how to deal with the positions in which Black's
bishop is developed to d6 instead of e7.}) 10. b3 $1 {The idea is very simple:
By placing his bishop on the long diagonal, White will: A) increase the
pressure on e5 and B) after f2-f4 and Black's capture exf4, achieve a
favourable trade of the dark-squared bishops.} c5 {Black usually makes this
move to increase his control of the centre and stop the possibility of d3-d4
once and for all.} 11. Bb2 Re8 12. a4 $1 {Stabilising the knight on c4 is an
important part of White's plan.} b6 ({The following short game, played in 1950,
was the first clear sign that Black must pay special attention to this new
concept with f2-f4.} 12... Qe7 13. Ne3 Nf8 $2 14. Nd5 Qd6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 (15...
gxf6 16. Nh4 {is also not very pleasant.}) 16. Nxe5 $1 {, and Black was dead
lost in Taimanov,M-Pogats,J Szczawno Zdroj 1950.}) ({The first top game in
this line was Gligoric, S-Reshevsky,S New York 1952. Gligoric achieved a large
advantage after adopting the new and revolutionary concept} 12... g6 13. Kh1 $1
Bg7 14. Qe1 Qe7 15. Ng1 $1 f6 (15... Nf8 16. Ne2 $1 f5 17. exf5 Bxf5 (17...
gxf5 $6 18. f4) 18. Ng3) 16. f4 $6 ({White had to play f2- f4 one move later,
after the preparatory} 16. Ne2 $1) 16... Nb8 $6 {Now it is Black who missed a
strong reply.} (16... exf4 17. Rxf4 f5 $1 $132) 17. fxe5 (17. f5 $1 {is even
stronger - getting a space advantage and chances for an attack on the kingside.
}) 17... fxe5 18. Nf3 Nc6 19. Qg3 Bd7 20. a5 Nd4 21. Nxd4 cxd4 22. Ba3 $1 {
Gaining full control over the open f-file.} Qe6 23. Rf3 Bb5 24. Raf1 Bxc4 25.
bxc4 Rad8 {Gligoric,S-Reshevsky,S New York 1952, when after} 26. h4 $16 {
White will enjoy an overwhelming advantage.}) 13. h3 $1 {This is an
improvement over the Gligoric game. White is preparing Nh2 and f2-f4.
Obviously, the knight is doing better on h2 than on g1} g6 14. Nh2 Nf8 15. Ng4
$1 (15. f4 $2 {is still not working properly.} exf4 $1) 15... Bxg4 (15... Bg7
$2 16. Ngxe5) 16. Qxg4 {White accumulates small advantages and is now ready
for f2-f4.} Bg7 ({In case of} 16... b5 $6 17. Ne3 {, Black always has to watch
out for the possibility axb5.}) 17. f4 $1 exf4 (17... f6 {is a very sad move
to make - White has the pleasant choice between} 18. f5 ({and the more direct} 
18. fxe5 fxe5 19. Rf2) {, and if Black blocks the kingside with} 18... g5 $6 {
, then after} 19. h4 h6 20. hxg5 hxg5 21. Kf2 $18 {White has a mating attack.})
18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qxf4 {White realises the plan with f4 and enjoys its
positive results. The open f-file, the weakness of f6 and the issue of the
king's safety will be a constant source of trouble for Black. Soon the growing
activity of White's pieces will decide the game. Black tries to get out of the
pressure, but at a high price - losing a pawn and transposing to a lost
endgame.} f6 20. Rf2 $1 Ne6 21. Qg3 Rf8 22. Raf1 (22. Ne3 c6 23. Raf1 Ra7 24.
e5 $18) 22... Qd4 23. Ne3 $1 {The standard manoeuvre - the knight goes to d5,
attacking both weaknesses on f6 and c7.} Kh8 (23... Qe5 24. Qxe5 fxe5 25. Ng4
$18) 24. Nd5 f5 25. c3 $1 Qg7 26. exf5 Rxf5 27. Rxf5 gxf5 28. Qxg7+ Kxg7 (28...
Nxg7 29. Nxc7 Rd8 30. Rf3 $1 $18) 29. Rxf5 {, and White didn't have any
problems converting the material advantage. We can separate White's actions
into the following three stages: 1. White stops Black's counterplay and the
manoeuvre Nf8-e6-d4 by pressuring e5 and stabilising the knight on c4 (moves
7-12). 2. White completes his development and starts the preparation of f2-f4 
(moves 13-17). Here it is important to prevent a possible counter break by
controlling the f5 square (in the game it was White's queen on g4 which
fulfilled this task 3. After f4, Black didn't have much choice and took on f4.
The alternative is to protect the pawn on e5 by f7-f6, which would offer White
two options that are basically a matter of taste: Either exchange on e5,
creating a weakness there (as in Gligoric-Reshevsky 1952), or fix the space
advantage with f4-f5, creating a wedge and planning a kingside attack. After
exf4, White had a position which is a model for the effective execution of the
plan f2-f4. The third and decisive stage started by doubling the rooks on the
f-file and the transfer of the knight to d5 (moves 20-24).} 1-0

[Event "Prague Armies-ch03"]
[Site "Prague"]
[Date "1966.??.??"]
[Round "12"]
[White "Game 2"]
[Black "Hort, V - Geller"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C85"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "81"]
[EventDate "1966.08.22"]
[EventRounds "15"]
[EventCountry "CZE"]

{In this game Vlastimil Hort, one of the pioneers of the delayed Exchange
Spanish, crushed no one lesser but Efim Geller, twice champion of the USSR and
six-time participant of the candidate matches, one of the greatest
theoreticians of the Russian chess school.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4.
Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 ({Let's see how White should fight
to achieve f2-f4 in case Black goes for other defensive setups.} 7... Bg4 {
, as mentioned above, is in White favour. After the trade of the bishop for
the knight, White can more easily execute the plan with f4. Let's look at the
following model game.} 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 O-O 10. Nd2 Nd7 11. Nc4 Bf6 12. Qg3
Re8 13. f4 $1 b5 14. Ne3 exf4 15. Qxf4 Ne5 16. Nf5 Kh8 17. Qf2 Ng6 18. Rb1 $1
Re6 19. Be3 Qd7 20. g4 $1 Rae8 21. g5 Bd8 22. h4 $16 {, with a powerful
initiative for White in Forcen,D -Gretarsson,H Benasque 2015}) ({In case of} 
7... Bd6 $5 {, White may continue in the same fashion.} 8. Nbd2 Be6 9. b3 Nd7
10. Bb2 c5 11. Nc4 {, when after} Bxc4 {in the game Chigaev,M -Gabrielian,A
Sochi 2015 White successfully managed to play f2-f4.} 12. dxc4 Qe7 13. Qe2 Nf8
14. g3 $1 f6 15. Nh4 g6 16. f4 $1 exf4 (16... O-O-O 17. f5 $1) (16... Ne6 $6
17. f5 $1) 17. gxf4 O-O-O {, and now White should have played the precise} 18.
Qg4+ $1 Kb8 (18... Qd7 19. f5 $1) (18... Nd7 19. e5 $1 fxe5 20. Rae1 Rhe8 21.
fxe5 $40) 19. e5 $1 fxe5 20. fxe5 Bxe5 21. Rae1 $18) ({After} 7... Qd6 8. Nbd2
Be6 9. Ng5 $1 {in the game Hess,R - Sokolov,I - Reykjavik 2012 Black made an
inaccuracy, which was severely punished.} Bg4 $6 ({Better was} 9... Nd7 10.
Nxe6 Qxe6 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Qf3 Rae8 13. a4 $14) 10. f3 Bc8 11. Nc4 Qd8 12. f4 $1
exf4 13. Bxf4 Ng4 (13... O-O 14. Qd2 $14) 14. Qd2 Bc5+ 15. Kh1 $16 {, and
Black is soon going to lose his activity.}) 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nc4 Bf6 (9... f6 $1
{is the most frequently played move. It was much later when Black found the
right way to deal with the dangerous knight manoeuvre Nh4-f5.} 10. Nh4 $1 {
This is the move which Black is trying to prevent by playing Bf6 and not f6.}
g6 $1 {, and now White should try} (10... Nc5 11. Nf5 {is in White's favour.})
11. Qg4 $5 {See game 5 Simonian,H-Eljanov,P Alushta 2011.}) 10. Bd2 {The only
difference between b3 and Bb2 and the move chosen by Hort is that the bishop
on c3 is defended, which eliminates ideas of a temporary sacrifice of the
e5-pawn in some lines.} Re8 11. Bc3 c5 (11... b5 12. Na5 Nb6 {Livshits,G
-Romanishin,O Vlissingen 2005 is an original attempt to create immediate
counterplay by chasing the strong Nc4.} 13. Nxc6 Qd6 14. Na5 Na4 $1 {One of
the drawbacks of Bd2-Bc3 compared to b3 and Bb2.} 15. h3 c5 16. a3 $6 {And now
after} Nxc3 17. bxc3 c4 $1 {, Black could have achieved huge compensation for
the sacrificed pawn.}) 12. a4 $1 {Preserving the strong c4-square for the
knight.} b6 13. h3 $1 {Everything is well-known. Players are repeating the
previous game Benko-Hajtun with one small difference: White's bishop is on c3
instead of b2.} a5 $5 {Black should avoid blocking the queenside, as it is the
only source of active counterplay.} (13... Bb7 $6 {is what White would like to
see, as Black's bishop is doing nothing on b7.} 14. Nh2 $1 Bg5 15. Ng4 b5 (
15... f6 16. g3 $1) 16. Na5 $14) (13... g6 14. Nh2 Bg7 15. f4 $1 exf4 16. Rxf4
Ne5 (16... Bxc3 17. bxc3 $16 {is also good for White.}) 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. Bxe5
Rxe5 19. Qf3 Re7 20. Rf1 Be6 21. b3 $1 {was the game Mestel,A-Ekstroem,R Graz
1981. It is very similar to the Benko-Hajtun game, with the difference that
Black has the bishop instead of a knight, which doesn't change the evaluation
by much.} b5 22. e5 $1 Qd5 23. Qe3 Bd7 24. Re4 Rae8 25. c4 Qb7 26. Qh6 $1 {
The bad king's position is the decisive element.} Rxe5 27. Rh4 Rf5 28. Qxh7+
Kf8 29. Qh6+ Ke7 30. Re4+ Be6 {, and here the most simple way was} 31. Rfe1 $1
$18 {with a mating attack.}) 14. Qd2 ({I don't know why Hort didn't continue
with the classical move} 14. Nh2 $5 {, for instance.} Nb8 (14... Ba6 15. b3 $1
Nb8 16. Ng4 Nc6 17. f4) 15. Ng4 Bxg4 16. Qxg4 Nc6 17. f4 (17. g3 $5) 17... exf4
18. Qxf4 Nd4 19. Rf2 Qe7 20. Raf1 Rf8 21. Qg4 Kh8 22. g3 Rae8 23. h4 $16 {
, when White enjoys total control of the situation.}) 14... Re6 (14... Bb7 15.
Nh2) (14... Qe7 $5) 15. b3 {The last preparation before moving to the second
stage - execution of f2-f4.} Qe8 {With his last moves, Black defends the
e5-pawn, freeing the knight to complete the manoeuvre Nf8-g6 or Nb8-c6-d4.} 16.
Ng5 (16. Nh2 $1 {in my view looks preferable.} h6 (16... Nb8 17. Ng4) (16...
Nf8 17. Ng4 Ng6 18. f4) 17. g3 $1 h5 (17... Bg5 18. f4) 18. f4 $40) 16... Bxg5
(16... Re7 17. f4 exf4 18. Bxf6 Nxf6 19. Qxf4 {would be excellent for White.})
17. Qxg5 f6 18. Qg3 Nf8 ({Of course in case of} 18... Qg6 {, White will avoid
the trade with} 19. Qh2 $1) 19. f4 $1 {Black is in great trouble. Even Efim
Geller couldn't escape from White's heavily loaded guns.} exf4 20. Rxf4 Ng6 21.
Rf2 Re7 22. Ne3 $1 {As in the previous game, the transfer of the knight to the
kingside decides.} Be6 23. Raf1 (23. h4 h5 24. Nf5 Rd7 25. Raf1) 23... h6 (
23... Kh8 24. Rxf6 gxf6 25. Bxf6+ Kg8 26. h4 $18) 24. h4 $1 Kh7 25. h5 Nh8 26.
Nf5 (26. e5 fxe5 27. Qxe5 Bc8 28. Qd5 Bd7 29. Nf5 $18) 26... Bxf5 (26... Rd7
27. e5 Qxh5 28. exf6 gxf6 29. Qe3 Bxf5 30. Rxf5) 27. Rxf5 Rd8 (27... Nf7 28.
Qg6+ Kh8 29. Bxf6) 28. e5 $1 {Opening the diagonal for the beast on c3.} fxe5
29. Rxe5 Rxe5 30. Bxe5 Rd7 31. Bxc7 $18 {, with decisive material gains.} Qxh5
32. Bxb6 Rb7 33. Bxa5 c4 34. Qf3 (34. b4 cxd3 35. Qxd3+) 34... Qxf3 35. Rxf3
cxb3 36. cxb3 Rxb3 37. d4 Rb1+ 38. Rf1 Rb2 39. d5 Rb3 40. Bc7 Rd3 41. a5 {
A classical game, which highly increased the popularity of the line with 6.Bc6,
as it revealed the great potential of the White concept.} 1-0

[Event "UKR-chT Clubs"]
[Site "Alushta"]
[Date "2011.05.14"]
[Round "2.1"]
[White "Game 3"]
[Black "Simonian, H - Eljanov"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C85"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "53"]
[EventDate "2011.05.13"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "UKR"]

{In my view the following game has certain theoretical value. Eljanov is an
outstanding theoretician and he knew the best way to handle the line as Black.
Nevertheless, he met some trouble passing through the opening stage.} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 8. Nbd2 O-O
9. Nc4 f6 ({In games 1 and 2 we have seen White's attacking method after} 9...
Bf6) 10. Nh4 $1 {The most critical move and the main idea of the 6.Bc6 delayed
Exchange Spanish.} g6 $5 ({The established mainline is} 10... Nc5 11. Nf5 Bxf5
12. exf5 {, but it doesn't automatically solve Black's opening problems. White
has the very simple plan to chase away or trade Black's knight, getting the
excellent outpost on e4. For instance} Qd5 (12... Qd7 13. Qg4 $1 {In case of}
Rfe8 (13... b5 14. Ne3 (14. Na5 {is also fine for White. The game Pacher,
M-Petkov,V Czechia 2012 continued} g6 15. Be3 Kh8 16. Qf3 $1 gxf5 17. Qxc6 Qxc6
18. Nxc6 Bd6 19. f4 $1 $14 {, and White enjoyed the better pawn structure in
the arising endgame.}) 14... Rfe8 15. h3 $1 {White defends his queen in case
of g7-g6, planning to capture with the pawn in case Black trades queens on g4.}
Bf8 16. Rd1 Rad8 (16... e4 17. dxe4 Qe7 18. f3) 17. b3 $1 Qd4 (17... e4 18. d4
$1 Nb7 19. Bb2 Nd6 20. c4 $1) 18. Rb1 (18. Ba3 e4 19. Bxc5 Bxc5 20. dxe4 Qe5
$44) 18... Qxg4 (18... e4 $2 19. Bb2) 19. hxg4 $1 Nd7 {, and in the game
Williams,A-Clarke,P Coventry/ West Midlands, 1970, White had the slightly
better chances in the endgame.} 20. Kf1 Nb6 21. Bd2 Nd5 22. f3 $1) 14. Be3 (14.
h3 $5) 14... g6 {Very strong is} 15. f4 $1 {Andreikin,D -Bigaliev,R Moscow 2008
} e4 (15... b5 16. Nd2 e4 17. dxe4 Bd6 18. e5 $14) 16. b4 $1 Na4 17. dxe4 Bxb4
(17... Nc3 18. Rad1 $1 Nxd1 19. Rxd1 Qc8 20. Bd4 Bd8 21. Qg3 Rxe4 22. fxg6 Qf5
23. gxh7+ Kxh7 24. Ne3 Qxf4 25. Qh3+ Qh4 26. Qf5+ Kh8 27. g3 Qh7 28. Qf3 Be7
29. Nf5 $40) 18. Rad1 $1 Qf7 19. e5 $1 Qxc4 20. fxg6 fxe5 21. Rd7 $18 {, and
Andreikin smashed his opponent with a direct attack.}) 13. Re1 $1 Rfe8 (13...
e4 $6 14. b4) 14. Qg4 Bf8 15. Nd2 $1 Rad8 16. b4 $1 Nd7 17. Ne4 Qf7 18. Bd2 {
, and in the game Annageldyev,O -Belosvetov,N Alushta 2005 White realised the
main idea of the line and achieved an excellent position.}) 11. Qg4 $5 ({
Unfortunately, the attempt to achieve an immediate f4 is not very successful.} 
11. Bh6 Rf7 $1 12. f4 exf4 13. Rxf4 {, and now Black can refute White's
concept with the new idea} (13. Bxf4 $6 f5 14. Nf3 fxe4 15. Nfe5 Rxf4 16. Rxf4
Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qd4+ $19 {Kiewra,Keeton - Bojkov, D - Los Angeles 2011}) 13...
Bc5+ $1 14. d4 (14. Kh1 b5 15. Na5 Ne5 (15... Be3 16. Nxc6 Qe8 $17) 16. Rf1 Ng4
17. Nb7 Qe7 $17) 14... Bf8 $1 15. Bxf8 Nxf8 {/\ Ne6, /\g6-g5} 16. Rf2 (16. c3
g5 $1) 16... f5) (11. f4 exf4 12. Rxf4 b5 13. Na5 (13. Ne3 f5 14. Nhxf5 gxf5
15. Nxf5 Ne5) 13... Ne5) 11... Kh8 (11... Nc5 12. Qg3 Ne6 {was the most
principled defence, as Black is holding off f2-f4. But Eljanov prefers to
avoid the dangerous looking knight sacrifice on g6.} 13. Nxg6 (13. Nf5 $1 Bc5
14. Be3 $14) 13... hxg6 14. Qxg6+ Ng7 $1 (14... Kh8 15. f4 Bc5+ 16. Kh1 exf4
17. Bxf4 Qe7 18. Bh6 Rg8 19. Qh5 Qh7 20. Rxf6 $18) 15. Bh6 Rf7 16. Kh1 $1 (16.
f4 exf4 17. Rxf4 Qd4+ 18. Kh1 f5 19. Bg5 Bxg5 20. Qxg5 Be6 $17) 16... Be6 17.
Ne3 Bd6 (17... Qd4 $2 18. g4 $1 Kh8 19. Rg1 Rg8 20. g5 $40) 18. f4 exf4 19.
Bxf4 Qe8 {, and now White should continue the attack with} 20. g4 $1 Rf8 21.
Qh6 $44) 12. f4 $1 {Let's go!} Rg8 $6 {Eljanov prevents the sacrifice on g6,
which most probably leads to a draw after the best defence.} ({In case of} 
12... exf4 {White intended to sacrifice a piece:} 13. Nxg6+ ({There is just no
other choice as} 13. Bxf4 $6 Ne5 {is too bad.}) 13... hxg6 14. Qxg6 Ne5 (14...
Qe8 {would prevent the immediate draw, but it doesn't change the evaluation.}
15. Qh6+ Kg8 16. Bxf4 Ne5 (16... Qf7 17. Bxc7 $44) 17. h3 $1 {transposes to 14.
..Ne5.}) 15. Qh6+ Kg8 16. Bxf4 $1 ({White has a perpetual after} 16. Nxe5 fxe5
17. Qg6+ $11) 16... Qe8 17. h3 $1 Bc5+ (17... Qg6 18. Nxe5 Qxh6 19. Bxh6 fxe5
20. Bxf8 Bxf8 21. Rf3 $14) 18. Kh1 Nxc4 $1 (18... Qe7 19. Nxe5 fxe5 20. Qg6+
Qg7 21. Qxg7+ Kxg7 22. Bxe5+ Kh7 23. Bxc7) 19. Rf3 Ne5 20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qg6+
$11) 13. Nf3 Nc5 14. Qg3 $1 {White got what he wanted, now his attack is
developing smoothly.} exf4 15. Bxf4 Ne6 16. Bd2 $1 {White transfers the bishop
to the a1-h8 diagonal!} c5 17. Bc3 ({Even stronger was} 17. Rae1 $1 g5 (17...
Ng7 18. Bc3 $1) (17... Nd4 18. Nxd4 Qxd4+ 19. Rf2 $16) 18. Bc3 Nd4 19. e5 f5
20. e6 $1 $40) 17... Nd4 18. Qf2 $1 {The knight on d4 has no solid base and is
forced to return.} Nb5 19. Bd2 ({Most precise was} 19. Be1 $1 {, and after} Be6
20. a4 $1 Nd4 21. Bc3 $1 {Black is forced to release the block on d4.}) 19...
Be6 (19... Nd4 $1) 20. a4 $1 Nd4 21. Bc3 $1 Nxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Rf8 23. Ne3 $1 {
White achieved his goals for the plan with f2-f4. Black's king's position is
shattered and White's Bc3 exerts tremendous pressure on the long diagonal.} c6
24. Ng4 ({White has a huge initiative and should have simply followed the
usual plans for the second stage: 1. double the rooks on the f-file, 2. induce
more weaknesses with an eventual h4-h5.} 24. Rf2 $1 b5 25. b3 $1 {Defending
against b5-b4.} Qd7 26. Qg3 Rf7 27. Raf1 Raf8 28. Kh1 Bd8 29. h4 Bc7 (29... Kg8
30. Nf5) 30. Rxf6 $3) 24... Kg7 25. Qf4 Bxg4 26. Qxg4 Bd6 27. Rf3 ({The last
chance to fight for an advantage was} 27. Qe6 Qe7 28. Qxe7+ Bxe7 29. g4 $1 $14)
1/2-1/2

[Event "ESP-chT Div Honor"]
[Site "Monzon"]
[Date "2016.09.28"]
[Round "3.4"]
[White "Game 4"]
[Black "Dominguez, L - Adhiban"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C77"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[EventDate "2016.09.26"]
[EventRounds "7"]
[EventCountry "ESP"]

{In 2016 I played for the last time in the Spanish Top 10 team Championship 
(Division de Honor). In 2015 my team won the title, but in the next year we
had severe problems staying in the league. All the foreign players, including
Harikrishna, Adhiban, Ganguly and myself had a bad tournament. We managed to
save ourselves from relegation only by coincidence, as in 2016 for the first
time a woman board was introduced. The heroical performance by Ana Matnadze
enabled the team to continue the 15 years of presence in the highest Spanish
league. In the following game, Adhiban was severely punished for his carefree
handling of the Exchange Spanish. Leinier Dominguez played an amazing game and
proved one more time that he fully deserves his place in the top 20.} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 (5... b5 6. Bb3 Bc5 {is the great
Arkhangelsk - one of the lines of the Ruy Lopez which definitely passed the
test of time.}) 6. Bxc6 $5 {The arising position is more typical for the
Berlin Defence: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bb5 Nf6 4.d3 Bc5 5 Bc6 dxc6. There are two
differences: Instead of d3 White has already castled short and the pawn is on
a6 instead of a7.} dxc6 7. d3 Nd7 {White was certainly happy to see this, as
Black is blocking the diagonal for the bishop c8, so he doesn't have to take
care of the pin Bg4 anymore.} (7... Bg4 $6 {is not yet possible, as after} 8.
h3 $1 {Black has to part with the bishop.} Bxf3 9. Qxf3 $14) (7... Qe7 {
is the most principled option, when White should better allow Bg4, as in case
of} 8. h3 {we will arrive at the position from Aronian-Kramnik 2018 (see the
History section), in which after} Rg8 $1 {Black had a dangerous initiative.})
8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nc4 Re8 10. Kh1 $5 {The purpose of this move will be revealed
much later. For now White is just making a useful move, waiting to see how
Black will arrange his pieces.} Bf8 11. Bd2 $5 ({White is going to play} 11. b3
{anyway, so the purpose of playing Bd2-c3 may be to hold off counterplay
connected with a6-a5.}) (11. a4 $5 {is the standard way to prevent Black's
queenside counterplay.}) 11... c5 (11... b5 $5 {is definitely more in
Adhiban's style, who is always looking to create activity as early as possible.
} 12. Ne3 (12. Na5 c5 13. a4 $6 Nb6) 12... Nc5 13. b3 f6 14. Ng1 Ne6 15. Ne2 c5
$132) 12. b3 b6 (12... b5 $5 13. Ne3 Nb8 {/\ Nc6-d4}) 13. Bc3 Bd6 {Very
strange things are happening - Black is making one more bishop move,
apparently having lost his sense of danger, as he was probably lulled by the
quiet handling of the game by White (Bd2, b3, Bc3, a4).} ({Adhiban was afraid
to play} 13... f6 {because of the standard} 14. Nh4 $1 Nb8 15. f4 exf4 16. Qh5
Nc6 17. Rxf4 Be6 18. Nf5) 14. a4 {White continues his wait-and-see strategy,
hoping for f7-f6.} Bb7 $6 {And this was already too much, as the bishop has
nothing to do on b7.} ({There was nothing to fear after} 14... f6 15. Nh4 Nf8
16. Qh5 (16. Nf5 Ne6 17. Qg4 Kh8 $132) 16... Ne6 17. g3 g6 $1 (17... Nd4 18. f4
Be6 $1) 18. Qd1 Nd4 $132) 15. Nfd2 Nf8 {Black built an ultra-solid setup and
it looks like nothing can shake his composure.} (15... Qg5 $5) 16. Qg4 Ng6 (
16... Qd7 {As usual, going into the endgame is the safest solution.} 17. Qxd7
Nxd7 18. Nxd6 cxd6 19. Nc4 Re6 20. Ne3 Bc6 21. f4 exf4 22. Rxf4 f6 {, and
White has only a small advantage.}) 17. Ne3 Bf8 {One more time the bishop goes
back to f8.} (17... Bc8 18. Nf5 Kh8 19. f4) 18. Nf5 Bc8 19. g3 $1 {Black chose
a rather passive setup, and now White has all the time in the world to slowly
build his attacking plan.} f6 20. f4 Kh8 21. Nf3 $6 {With this move White
increases the pressure on the kingside. Adhiban realises that passive defence
will not be enough to save the day and moves forward.} ({Better was} 21. Qh5 $5
) ({or} 21. Nc4 $5 {, avoiding Black's tactical opportunities connected with
the pin of his f5 knight.}) 21... exf4 $1 {Quite a risky decision, as it opens
the g-file, leaving White with total domination in the centre. To justify such
a move, Black should have a concrete solution in mind.} 22. gxf4 Bxf5 $6 ({
Missing} 22... Be6 $1 {, which was basically the refutation of White's concept.
} 23. Rg1 ({White cannot escape from the pin:} 23. Qh5 $2 Nxf4) (23. Qg3 $6
Bxf5 24. exf5 Ne7 $17) 23... Qd7 24. Rg3 Bxf5 25. exf5 Ne7 26. Nh4 Qc6+ 27. Rg2
Nd5 28. Bd2 Kg8 $1 {, and Black is strategically winning, the sacrifice is not
working.} 29. Ng6 $6 hxg6 30. fxg6 Bd6 31. Qh5 Bxf4 32. Qh7+ Kf8 33. Qh8+ Ke7
34. Qxg7+ Kd8 $19) 23. Qxf5 Bd6 $2 {Playing Bd6 for the second time, Adhiban
shows he is a tireless and a persevering player. But objectively the move is
just a terrible blunder, after which Black's position quickly collapses.} (
23... Qc8 24. Qxc8 Raxc8 {was again the best defence, but now White's
advantage is more visible than four moves ago.} 25. f5 Nf4 26. Ng1 Bd6 27. Rf3
Be5 28. Bxe5 fxe5 29. Nh3 Ne2 30. Ng5 $14) 24. Rg1 $1 Qc8 {Too late.} ({
The pawn f4 is untouchable} 24... Nxf4 25. Rxg7 $1 Kxg7 26. Rg1+ Ng6 27. Nh4)
25. Qh5 $3 {At this moment I was playing next to Adhiban and the final attack
made a great impression on me.} Nxf4 26. Qh6 $3 Ne6 27. Bxf6 (27. Rxg7 Nxg7 28.
Ng5 {was the most beautiful way to finish the game.}) 27... Bf8 28. Rxg7 Bxg7
29. Ng5 {Mate in 11 moves.} Kg8 30. Qxh7+ Kf8 31. Rf1 (31. Nxe6+ Rxe6 32. Qxg7+
Ke8 33. Rf1) 31... Re7 32. Nxe6+ Rxe6 33. Bxg7+ (33. Qxg7+ Ke8 34. Bh4 {
[%emt 0:00:03] mate in 3.}) 33... Ke7 34. Be5+ Ke8 35. Qf7+ Kd8 36. Bf6+ (36.
Rg1 {[%emt 0:00:03] Again mate in 3.}) 36... Rxf6 37. Qxf6+ Kd7 38. Qf7+ Kd8
39. Rg1 {In this game White realised the basic ideas of the f2-f4 break and
won a nice game, not without some assistance from his opponent, though. At
first Black was handling the position in a very passive way, instead of
completing the knight transfer to d4 or initiating counterplay on the
queenside. Black was very close to realising his ambitious but very risky plan.
Had he played 16... Be6 with the idea 17...Qd7, Adhiban would have
successfully executed his main idea to counterstrike against White's weakened
kingside.} 1-0

[Event "Saint Louis Showdown Blitz"]
[Site "Saint Louis"]
[Date "2016.11.14"]
[Round "5"]
[White "Game 5"]
[Black "Anand, V - Topalov"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "59"]
[EventDate "2016.11.14"]
[EventType "blitz"]
[EventRounds "24"]
[EventCountry "USA"]
[EventCategory "22"]

{I would like to conclude my investigation with this blitz game, which is full
of twists, played between Anand and Topalov at the famous 2016 Saint Louis
Champions showdown tournament won by Anand.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4.
d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. h3 Bd6 7. Nc3 $5 {In the previous round, Topalov lost
in a similar line against Caruana. There was only a small difference: The
inclusion of 4...a6 5.Ba4. You can see the game as one of my model examples
with the bishop on d6. Nc3 is a new concept - before this, White invariably
played Nbd2.} c5 (7... O-O 8. Bg5 $5 h6 9. Be3 {may be an original idea: To
create a weakness on h6, White is planning to follow up with Qd2, 0-0-0 and
g4-g5.}) 8. O-O ({When Black hasn't castled yet,} 8. Bg5 {has no point and
only helps Black.} h6 9. Be3 Be6 $11) 8... O-O 9. Nd2 {White's idea is quite
straightforward: He wants to play Nc4 and f4.} Be6 10. Nc4 Nd7 (10... Bxc4 {
doesn't bring Black equality.} 11. dxc4 c6 12. Qf3 $1 h6 13. Ne2 $36 {with the
initiative.}) 11. Nxd6 $1 {Executing the main idea.} cxd6 12. f4 $1 f5 $6 {
Topalov is trying his best to stay active, but this move meets severe
punishment. It was more resilient to play} (12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne5 {, but
here too after} 14. Qe1 Qd7 15. Qg3 f6 16. Rad1 $1 b5 17. d4 $14 {White is
firmly holding the initiative.}) 13. exf5 Rxf5 (13... Bxf5 14. Qf3 $1) 14. g4
$1 Rf8 15. f5 Bf7 16. Qf3 {There is a good chance that all this was home
preparation. At first sight, the position doesn't look so terrible for Black,
but he still has many pending issues to solve, like the threat of the kingside
pawn storm with g5-g6 and the weakness of the d5 square.} c4 {This reaction is
predictable.} ({Black would also have problems in the endgame in case of} 16...
Qb6 17. Rf2 Kh8 18. b3 Rad8 (18... Qc6 $2 19. Qxc6 bxc6 20. Ne4 d5 21. Nd6 $1)
19. g5 Qc6 20. Qxc6 bxc6 21. Ne4 Nb6 22. c4 $1) (16... Nb6 17. g5 $1) 17. Be3
$1 cxd3 18. cxd3 Rc8 19. d4 ({Anand avoids the unclear consequences of} 19.
Qxb7 d5 $1 20. Nxd5 Rb8 $132) ({, but it may be that} 19. Rad1 $5 {was more
precise than the move in the game.}) 19... b5 $6 (19... Qb6 $5 {was the most
unpleasant reply.} 20. Nd5 $1 (20. dxe5 Qxb2 21. e6) (20. Qf2 Qc6) 20... Bxd5
21. Qxd5+ Kh8 22. Qb3 $5 $14 {Keeping some pressure in the endgame.}) 20. Nxb5
{Why not to have both - the material advantage and the attack? But Anand could
have paid a very high price for releasing the beast from the cage.} ({A more
simple solution was} 20. Rad1 $5 b4 21. Ne4 Bd5 (21... d5 22. Nd6 e4 23. Qg3)
22. dxe5 Nxe5 23. Nf6+ Qxf6 24. Qxd5+ {, with total control of the position.})
20... exd4 (20... Qb6 21. a4 $1) 21. Nxd4 (21. Bxd4 Ne5 22. Qg2 Bc4 23. Rfc1 $1
Bxb5 24. Qd5+ Kh8 25. Rxc8 Qxc8 26. Bxe5 dxe5 27. Qxb5 e4 $132) 21... Ne5 22.
Qg3 Qd7 23. Bf4 Qb7 $1 24. b3 Qb4 $1 {Topalov enjoys playing positions like
this, with counterplay against the opponent's open king.} 25. Bxe5 $1 ({
Avoiding} 25. Rad1 Rc3 $1) 25... dxe5 26. Qxe5 Rfe8 27. Qf4 Rc3 (27... Bd5 28.
Rad1 Re4 29. Qd2 Qb8 30. Qh2 Qb6 {was also quite unpleasant.}) 28. Kh2 $4 {
Anand cracks under the pressure, but there is no advantage anymore anyway.} (
28. f6 Rxh3 29. fxg7 Qb7 $1) (28. Rae1 Rxe1 29. Rxe1 Rxh3 30. Rc1 h6 31. f6 Rc3
$1) 28... Bd5 (28... Ree3 $1 {was winning on the spot, but White's position is
still very unstable.}) 29. f6 (29. Rae1 $1 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Rd3 31. Re8+ Kf7 32.
Re2 Qc3 {, and White has to find the only way to make a draw.} 33. Re7+ Kxe7
34. Qe5+) 29... Ree3 $4 {Too late!} (29... gxf6 30. Qxf6 Qb8+ 31. Qf4 Qxf4+ 32.
Rxf4 Ree3 {was at least equal.}) 30. f7+ 1-0

[Event "Olympiad-41"]
[Site "Tromsoe"]
[Date "2014.08.11"]
[Round "9.3"]
[White "White's attacking model"]
[Black "Bartel, M - Georgiadis"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/2pnqppp/1pp5/p3p3/2N1PP2/1P1P2Q1/1PP3PP/R4R1K b - - 0 18"]
[PlyCount "40"]
[EventDate "2014.08.02"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "NOR"]

{In the following series of examples I would like to focus on the dynamic
possibilities in the positions arising after f2-f4 and more specifically on
White's attacking patterns. In this example, we have a standard position very
similar to the game Benko-Hajtun, but with one significant difference: Black's
king's position is not yet weakened with g7-g6. This increases Black's chances,
as with f7-f6 he creates a solid obstacle on the semi-open f-file.} 18... exf4
(18... f6 {is the more solid defence, but White is firmly holding the
initiative anyway after} 19. Ne3 Kh8 20. Rf3 ({or} 20. Nf5 Qf7 21. fxe5)) 19.
Rxf4 {Suddenly the situation gets really unpleasant, as White's pieces are
well-coordinated and ready to start the attack.} Ne5 {Black is looking for
simplifications, but this move meets a sudden refutation.} ({Again more
stubborn was} 19... f6 {, but after the logical} 20. Ne3 Kh8 21. Nf5 Qf7 22.
Rg4 g6 23. Ne3 {White has a serious advantage.}) 20. Raf1 $1 {A simple
decision: The last piece joins the attack and prevents a trade of the knights.}
Rf8 {The only move to avoid material losses.} (20... Nxc4 21. Rxf7 $18 Qxf7 22.
Rxf7 Kxf7 23. Qxc7+ Re7 24. Qxc6 $18) 21. Ne3 h6 ({The last hope was in} 21...
f6 22. d4 Ng6 23. Nf5 Qf7 {, but even here White has a very strong initiative
after} 24. R4f3 Rae8 25. e5 $18) 22. d4 (22. h4 $18 {was winning on the spot.
Taking the g5-square under control would avoid Black's last defensive idea.}
Kh8 (22... f6 23. Nf5 Qd7 24. d4 $18) 23. d4 Ng6 24. Nf5 Qd7 (24... Qf6 25. e5)
25. h5) 22... Ng6 23. Nf5 Qe6 (23... Qg5 $2 24. Rg4) 24. h4 (24. Rg4 $18) 24...
h5 25. Qg5 Qe8 $8 {The threat was g4.} 26. e5 $1 {Simple and decisive. White
stops f6 and raises the tension.} f6 (26... c5 27. Qxh5 $1 (27. g4 $2 Qd8 $1)
27... Nxf4 (27... cxd4 28. Qg5 $1 Qd8 29. Qg4 {With an unstoppable h4-h5.}) 28.
Rxf4 f6 29. Qg4 $18) 27. exf6 Rxf6 28. Ne7+ $1 ({Also winning was} 28. Nxg7
Rxf4 29. Nxe8 Rxf1+ 30. Kh2 Rxe8 31. Qxg6+ Kf8 32. Qh6+ Kg8 33. Qxc6 {, but
the move in the game looked simpler to me.}) 28... Qxe7 29. Rxf6 gxf6 30. Qxg6+
Qg7 31. Qxh5 (31. Rxf6 Qxg6 32. Rxg6+ {was probably the most technical way.})
31... Rf8 32. Rf4 Qh7 33. Qe2 Kh8 34. Kh2 {A useful move, as the king is much
better on h2.} Qf7 35. Qe4 Qd7 36. Qg6 Qg7 37. Rg4 Qxg6 38. Rxg6 {And with the
active rook on g6 and the better king, not to mention his material advantage,
White is winning.} *

