{Here the difference is that Black has a weakness on h6 and the dark-squared
bishops are still on the board.} 14. f4 $1 exf4 {Otherwise f4-f5 is extremely
dangerous.} (14... Bf6 15. f5 $1 Qe7 16. Ne3 Bg5 17. Ng4 Qc5+ 18. Rf2 Nf6 19.
Nxf6+ Bxf6 20. g3 $1 {, and White will start the pawn storm with h4 and g4-g5.}
a5) 15. Bxf4 b5 {only helps White, as Ne3-f5 is on the agenda.} 16. Ne3 Bf6 17.
Rae1 Be5 (17... Bd4 18. Kh1 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 {The exchange of the knight does not
save Black.} Re7 20. Rg3 Kh8 (20... Kh7 21. Bg5 Ree8) 21. Bd2 (21. Bg5 f6)
21... Ne5 22. Bg5 Rd7 23. Bf6 $18) 18. Nf5 Bxf4 19. Rxf4 Ne5 {Black managed to
trade the bishops, transposing to the standard middlegame position we have
already analysed in detail.} 20. Re3 $1 $18 {White has a decisive attack.} Ng6
21. Rg4 Qf6 22. Rf3 (22. d4 $1 $18) 22... Qb2 23. h4 Re6 24. Kh2 Rf8 25. Rgg3
Kh7 26. Qg4 {, and Black resigned.} Rg8 27. d4 Ne7 28. e5 Kh8 29. Nxe7 Rxe7 30.
Rf6 Qc1 31. Rxc6 {would be an easy win.} *

