{In the following two examples we can see how White develops his attack in
case Black's bishop is placed on d6 instead of e7.} 13. f4 $1 exf4 (13... f6 {
is met by} 14. f5 $1 Nc6 15. g4 Nd4 16. Nd5 Bb7 17. c3 {, with a huge
advantage for White.}) 14. Qf3 $1 {Caruana is using all the subtleties of the
position to increase his attacking potential.} Ra7 15. Nxd6 $1 cxd6 16. Bxf4 {
White has a devastating initiative. He has better development and can easily
create threats with the battery Bf4&Qg3, may double his rooks on the semi-open
f-file and use his strong knight on d5.} Be6 17. Qg3 $1 Rd7 18. Nd5 {White is
spoiled for choice.} ({The immediate} 18. e5 $1 {was as good as winning.} dxe5
(18... d5 $2 19. Bg5 Qc7 20. Bf6 g6 21. Qf4) 19. Bxe5 f6 {, and now White is
winning with a simple trick:} 20. Rxf6 Rxf6 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 22. Qxb8+ $18) 18...
Nc6 $4 {Topalov underestimates the danger and makes a fatal blunder. The best
chance was} (18... f6 19. Bd2 Nc6 20. Nf4 Bf7 21. Bc3 b5 22. Qg4 Kh8 23. axb5
axb5 24. Ra6 $40) 19. Bg5 $1 $18 f6 20. Nxf6+ 1-0

