{After I explained the strategical bases of White's plan, I would like to
focus on the different ways of converting the advantages achieved by the
successful execution of the f2-f4 break. In the following example, White wins
after creating a weakness on e5 and then transposing to an endgame.} 15. Nh2 $1
Qh4 16. f4 f6 ({Too bad is} 16... exf4 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Rxf4 Qe7 19. Raf1 f6
20. Ng4 Rf8 21. R4f2 $18) 17. Rf2 $1 h5 18. fxe5 $1 {Ulf Andersson fixes his
advantage by creating a long-term weakness on e5. Then he trades queens and
wins the endgame easily.} (18. Raf1 Bh6) 18... Nxe5 (18... fxe5 19. Nf3 Qg3 20.
Ng5 Bh6 21. Qe1 $3 {is one beautiful idea.} Qxg5 22. Bc1 $18) 19. Nxe5 fxe5 20.
Raf1 Be6 21. Nf3 Qg3 22. Qg5 ({or} 22. Ng5 Bh6 23. Rf6 Bf7 24. Bc1 $18) 22...
Qxg5 23. Nxg5 Bd7 24. Rf7 Rad8 {Black may have hoped to that the first wave of
the attack was over, but there followed} 25. Rxg7+ $3 Kxg7 26. Nf7 $1 Rc8 27.
Nxe5 Be6 28. Ng4+ Kh7 29. Nf6+ {, and White easily won the endgame.} *

