{The weakness on e5 makes Black's position very difficult to defend. Ivanchuk
didn't offer his opponent any chances to survive, creating an endgame
masterpiece.} 26. g4 $1 {With the idea to get more space on the kingside,
planning g5 and Ng4 or Nf5.} Nb5 $5 {Hoping for some counterplay against
White's a5-pawn after Nd4, c6-c5 and Nc6.)} (26... Ref8 27. Rxf7 Rxf7 28. g5
Kf8 29. Ng4 Re7 30. Rf1+ Ke8 31. Kg3) 27. Rxf7 Kxf7 28. Rf1+ Ke6 29. Nf5 Rg8
30. g5 c5 31. c3 (31. h5 $1 Nd4 32. Ne3 Ne2 33. Rf5 Nd4 34. Rf2 $18) 31... Na7
(31... g6 $2 {Ftacnik} 32. Nh6 Rd8 33. Rf6+ Ke7 34. Rf7+ $16) 32. Ne3 Nc8 (
32... Nc6 $1 {was the last chance.} 33. Nd5 ({or} 33. Nc4 Rd8 34. Rf3 $16)
33... Rc8 34. h5 $1 Nxa5 35. h6 Rg8 $1 36. Kh3 c6 37. Ne3 gxh6 38. Rf6+ Kd7 39.
gxh6 $16) 33. h5 $1 (33. Nd5 c6) 33... Ne7 34. Nd5 $1 {Excellent exchange
operation to penetrate on the seventh rank.} Nxd5 (34... c6 35. Nxe7 Kxe7 36.
g6 $1 hxg6 37. hxg6 Rf8 38. Rxf8 Kxf8 39. Kf3 {, and the pawn endgame is
easily winning.}) (34... Rc8 35. Kg3 $1) 35. exd5+ Kxd5 36. Rf7 b6 (36... Kd6
37. Kf3 b6 38. axb6 cxb6 39. Ke4 $18 (39. Ra7 {Ftacnik} a5 40. Ke4 $16)) (36...
Kc6 37. Kf3 $1) 37. Rxc7 bxa5 38. Kf3 Rf8+ 39. Ke3 h6 40. Rxg7 hxg5 41. Rxg5
Rf4 42. c4+ Kc6 43. Rg6+ Kb7 44. b3 Rh4 45. h6 e4 46. dxe4 Rh3+ 47. Kf4 Rxb3
48. Rg3 {A perfect example for the realisation of the better structure in the
endgame.} 1-0

