{The second example of the same topic, converting the space advantage in the
endgame, is played by the same player Osip Bernstein, but 52 years later.
Amazing!} 16. f5 $1 c5 17. b3 $1 Ba5 18. Be3 Bc3 19. Rab1 b6 (19... Bd4 $6 20.
Bd2 $1 {And the only way to save the bishop is to sacrifice a pawn.} c4 21.
bxc4 $18) 20. g4 $1 {Rolling the pawns forward.} Kb7 21. g5 Kc6 22. h4 Rg8 23.
Kf3 Rdf8 24. Ke2 {Moving out of Black's rooks' reach, but stronger was} (24. h5
$1 fxg5 25. Bxg5 g6 26. Bh6 Rf7 27. Rg1 Kd7 28. Ke2 Bd4 29. Rg5 $18) 24... b5
25. h5 b4 ({It is too late for} 25... c4 26. dxc4 bxc4 27. bxc4 Rb8 28. Rxb8
Rxb8 29. Rg1) 26. h6 $1 {A typical tool to break Black's structure on the
kingside.} (26. Rg1 Bd4 $1 {was Black's main idea, but nevertheless White
should be easily winning after} 27. Rg4 Bxe3 28. Kxe3 Kd6 29. Rbg1 Ke7 30. c3
$1 a5 (30... bxc3 31. gxf6+ Kxf6 32. Rc1 Rd8 33. Rxc3) 31. d4 cxd4+ 32. cxd4
exd4+ 33. Kxd4 Rd8+ 34. Ke3 c5 35. h6 $18) 26... gxh6 (26... Bd4 $1 27. hxg7 (
27. Bd2 gxh6 $1) 27... Rxg7 28. Bd2 fxg5 29. Rh1 h5 30. Rxh5 g4 31. Rh6+ Kd7
32. Kf1 g3 33. Kg2) 27. gxf6 Rxf6 (27... Bd4 28. Rg1 $18) 28. Rg1 Rxg1 29. Rxg1
Bd4 30. Rg7 Bxe3 31. Kxe3 a5 32. Rxh7 {Nice and easy.} 1-0

