{Before making his choice, White further improves his position. Gurgenidze is
a great technician, and with his last move he improves the conditions for
f4-f5.} 20. h4 $1 (20. f5 g5 $1 $14) (20. fxe5 fxe5 $14) 20... Kg7 ({In case of
} 20... h6 $2 {White wins a pawn.} 21. fxe5 fxe5 22. Ng4 $18) 21. f5 $1 Nb7 22.
Rf2 Nd6 23. Rdf1 Rd7 24. g4 $1 {Increasing the pressure - the threat is g4-g5
and Ng4.} h6 (24... Rdf7 25. g5 $1 fxg5 (25... gxf5 26. Nxf5+ Nxf5 27. Rxf5 $18
) 26. Ng4 $3 gxf5 27. Nxe5 Re7 28. Nxc6 $18 {is one very nice line.}) 25. g5 $1
fxg5 26. f6+ Kg8 27. hxg5 {Black is lost because of his bad king's position
and the weakness of the e5-pawn.} h5 (27... hxg5 28. Ng4 Nf7 29. Rh1 c5 30. Kf3
b5 31. Rfh2 c4 32. Rh7 $18) 28. Kg3 Nf7 29. Kh4 Rfd8 30. Rg1 Rd4 {And now the
final touch of the Maestro.} 31. Nf5 $3 gxf5 (31... R4d7 32. Ne7+ Kh7 33. Nxc6)
32. Rxf5 Nd6 33. Rxe5 Re8 34. Rxe8+ Nxe8 35. Kxh5 Kf7 36. Rf1 Rd8 37. Kh6 Kf8
38. e5 Rd4 39. g6 Rd7 40. e6 $18 {A memorable achievement of the great Buhuti
Gurgenidze.} 1-0

