{Nowadays Kasimdzhanov is known as one of the best experts of the Exchange
Spanish structure. In this game he beats Krasenkow by early opening the centre
with f2-f4 followed by e4-e5. In the resulting endgame, White got a big
advantage in activity, won a pawn with a small combination, and then easily
converted his material advantage.} 11. f4 $1 exf4 12. Qh5+ $1 (12. Nxd6+ cxd6
13. Rxf4 Bd7 {and 0-0-0, with a defensible position.}) 12... Qf7 (12... g6 13.
Qh6 $1 Rf8 (13... g5 $2 14. Bxf6 gxh4 15. e5 Rf8 16. Rae1 $18) 14. Rae1) 13.
Qxf7+ Kxf7 14. e5 $1 {The black king is in the centre and his pieces are
underdeveloped, so the opening of the centre is quite painful.} fxe5 15. Nxe5+
Ke8 16. Nc4 (16. Rae1 Rg8 17. Nc4) 16... Rg8 17. Rae1 b5 (17... g5 18. Nxd6+
cxd6 19. Bf6) 18. Nxd6+ cxd6 19. Rxf4 Ra7 (19... g5 20. Nf5 gxf4 21. Nxe7 $18)
20. Nf3 h6 21. d4 (21. b4 $5) 21... Rf8 22. Rfe4 Bf5 23. R4e3 Kf7 {It is
impossible to save the game.} (23... Rf7 24. dxc5 dxc5 25. Ne5 Rf6 26. Nd3 $18)
