{I decided to include some of my most recent theoretical investigations, which
may serve you as a base to develop your own complete opening repertoire. You
can also use it as complementary material to further your understanding of the
games from the following chapters. In the centre of my investigation is the
famous Anti-Berlin line with 4.d3 Bc5 5.Bc6 dc6. I covered all white
possibilities on move 6: A) 6.Nc3, which recently became very popular at top
level, B) 6.0-0, which suddenly came back into fashion, just like C) 6 Nbd2.
Furthermore, I analysed the tricky move order 4.d3 Bc5 5.Nc3 and the classical
exchange line 4.Bc6 dxc6 5.0-0, where I have always trusted 5...Bg4 with two
different ideas, A) 6.h3 Bh5 - a pawn sacrifice which leads to an extremely
sharp fight and B) 6.h3 h5 - a more solid line, which involves a temporary
piece sacrifice, which of course can't be accepted. I also cover the delayed
Exchange Spanish 3..a6 4.Ba4 Nf6 5.Bc6 dxc6 6.d3 or 3...Nf6 4.Bxc6 dxc6 5.d3,
a highly underestimated line which may serve you as a surprise weapon. It
often leads to quite specific play in which both sides should postpone
defining their kings' positions.}  *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2019.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "A) Anti-Berlin 6.Nc3!?"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C48"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev"]
[PlyCount "29"]
[EventDate "2019.09.24"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 {A)} 6. Nc3 $5 {This
rather non-typical move (the usual path for the knight is d2-c4) recently came
into fashion after a couple of very nice games (i.e. Caruana-Topalov and
Anand-Topalov from Saint Luis 2016 and Caruana-Anand London 2017, which is
game 6 from Chapter "opposite castling"). It appears that the knight might
have an even better future on c3 than on d2.} O-O {This move can be criticised
as the cause of Black's later troubles. It is safer to postpone the definition
of the king position - therefore the following moves should come into
consideration:} (6... Bg4 {as usual gives White a minimal advantage} 7. h3 $1
Bh5 (7... Be6 $6 8. Nxe5 (8. O-O Nd7 9. Ne2 $14) 8... Qd4 9. Be3 Qxe5 10. d4
Bxd4 11. Bxd4 Qg5 12. Qf3 O-O-O 13. Rd1 $14) 8. g4 Bg6 9. Be3 $1 Qe7 10. Bxc5
Qxc5 11. Qe2 Nd7 (11... O-O-O 12. Qe3 Qa5 13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Nd2 f6 15. a3 Bf7
16. h4 $14) 12. Qe3 $1 f6 13. Nh4 Bf7 14. Nf5 $14 {White keeps the pressure,
as Black's bishop is quite a passive piece and is not really taking part in
the action}) (6... Qe7 7. Be3 $1 {White's priority is to quickly trade one of
Black's bishops.} Bg4 (7... Bb4 8. h3 $14) (7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 Bg4 9. h3 Bxf3
10. Qxf3 Nd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. g4 f6 13. h4 Nf8 14. g5 $36) (7... Nd7 8. Qe2
f6 9. O-O) 8. h3 Bxf3 (8... Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Qe2 O-O-O 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Qe3
Qxe3+ 13. fxe3 Rhe8 {Dzagnidze,N -Olsarova,K Batumi 2018} 14. Nh4 $14) 9. Qxf3
h6 $1 (9... O-O $6 10. Bg5 Bd4 11. Nd1 $1) 10. O-O $14 {You may find similar
positions in the chapter on the f2-f4 break.}) 7. Be3 Qe7 $1 (7... Bd6 {
looks like a more principled way to preserve the bishop pair. Later Black can
play c6-c5 and then look for a way to improve his Nf6.} 8. Bg5 $5 {an
interesting attempt to confuse Black's normal plan - introduced for the first
time in Carlsen,M-Karjakin Riadh 2017} (8. h3 Re8 (8... Nd7 9. O-O Re8 10. Nd2
Nf8 11. Nc4 Ng6 12. Ne2 $1 Be6 13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. f4 $14) 9. Ne2 c5 10. Nd2 $1 {
Fighting for a quick f4.} (10. Ng3 a5 11. a4 Nd7 12. Nf5 Nf8 13. Nd2 Ne6 14.
Nc4 Bf8 {Dominguez Perez,L -So,W Saint Louis 2017} 15. O-O Nd4 16. Ng3 f6 17.
f4 exf4 18. Bxf4 Be6 19. b3 b6 $11) 10... Nh5 (10... Nd7 11. O-O Nf8 12. f4)
11. Nc4 (11. O-O Nf4) 11... b5 12. Nxd6 cxd6 13. O-O Bd7 14. f4 exf4 15. Nxf4
Nxf4 16. Rxf4 $14) 8... Re8 (8... Bg4 $6 9. h3 Bh5 10. g4 Bg6 11. h4 $5 (11.
Ne2 h6 12. Bh4 $36) 11... h6 12. Bxf6 $1 (12. h5 hxg5 13. hxg6 fxg6 14. Nxg5
Qd7 15. Rg1 (15. f3 Be7 16. Qd2 Nxg4) 15... Bc5 16. Rg2 Nh7 $1 17. Nxh7 Kxh7
18. Qd2 Rf4 19. O-O-O Raf8 20. Rh1+ Kg8 21. Nd1 Qe6 22. Kb1 Kf7 23. g5 Ke8 $11)
12... Qxf6 13. h5 (13. Qe2 Qf4 14. h5 Bh7 15. Rg1 f6 16. Nd2 $14) 13... Bh7 14.
g5 hxg5 15. Rg1 Bc5 16. Qe2 Qh6 17. Nxg5 $36) (8... h6 {The combination of 0-0
and h7-h6 looks dangerous.} 9. Bh4 $1 (9. Bd2 $5 {With the idea h3-g4.}) 9...
Qe7 10. O-O Be6 11. Qe2 Rad8 12. Nd1 g5 13. Bg3 Nd7 14. Ne3 $14) (8... Qe7 9.
h3 Re8 10. g4 Qe6 11. Nh4 Nd7 12. Nf5 Nc5 13. h4 Bf8 14. h5 f6 15. Be3 Qf7 16.
f4 exf4 17. Bxf4 b5 18. Qf3 Ne6 19. Be3 Bb7 20. O-O-O $36 {Carlsen,M-Grischuk,
A chess24.com 2020}) 9. h3 c5 10. Nd5 Be7 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. O-O $14 {Carlsen,
M -Karjakin,S Riadh 2017}) 8. Qd2 $1 (8. h3 a5 9. O-O Re8 $11 {Firat,B-Kovalev,
D Lviv UKR 2014}) 8... Rd8 ({is the most precise reply.} 8... Bb4 $5 9. a3 Ba5
10. h3 Rd8 11. b4 Bb6 12. O-O $14 {, with the idea to continue with Nh2 and f4}
) (8... Bg4 9. O-O-O $1 $14) 9. Bxc5 $1 ({The immediate} 9. O-O-O $6 {is
already dubious:} Bb4 $1 10. Qe1 b5 11. Kb1 a5 $36 {, and the pin of the
c3-knight is rather annoying.}) 9... Qxc5 10. Qg5 $1 (10. O-O-O $5 Bg4 (10...
Be6 11. Qg5 Nd7 12. d4 exd4 13. Qxc5 Nxc5 14. Nxd4 $14) 11. h3 Bxf3 12. gxf3
Nh5 13. Qe3 Qa5 14. Kb1 Nf4 15. Ne2 Nxe2 16. Qxe2 Rd6 17. Rdg1 $14) 10... Re8
11. d4 $1 $146 (11. O-O-O Qxf2 $1 (11... Nd7 12. Qg3 $14 {Saric, I-Grischuk,A
Heraklion 2017}) 12. Rhf1 Qc5 13. d4 Qe7 14. Nxe5 Ng4 15. Qxe7 Rxe7 16. Nxg4
Bxg4 17. Rd3 Bh5 $11) 11... Qa5 (11... Qb4 12. O-O-O h6 13. Qh4 exd4 14. Nxd4
$14 {The pawn majority on the kingside offers White a stable positional
advantage.}) 12. O-O-O Bg4 13. Rhg1 $1 (13. dxe5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Qxe5 15. Qe3 Nh5
16. Ne2 $14) 13... h6 14. Qh4 exd4 15. Rxd4 $14 {And Black is under pressure.}
*

