1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 {You can use this idea as well in the
Anti-Berlin move order 3...Nf6 4 Bxc6 dxc6. The only difference is the pawn a7/
a6, as in some lines it is hanging on a7.} 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 Nd7 (6... Bd6 $1
{is clearly stronger than 6...Nd7.}) (6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3 $14 {is
always slightly better for White.}) 7. Be3 $1 {The only sensible continuation
and the best way to fight for an advantage.} (7. Nbd2 $5 {is also playable,
but I have not been able to find a way to an advantage after} g6 $1 {This is
an interesting idea, promoted by Kortchnoi.} (7... Bd6 {is rarely seen and may
transpose to the mainline.}) (7... f6 8. Nc4 Nc5 $6 (8... Bd6 $1 $14) 9. Nfxe5
$1 Be6 $1 (9... fxe5 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Qxe5+ Kf7 12. Qxh8 Nxd3+ 13. Kf1 $1 $18
