1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bg4 6. h3 Bh5 $5 {This is
quite an unclear pawn sacrifice, which in my opinion is highly underestimated.
It might be the ideal weapon to look for winning chances in a sharp position
with opposite castling.} (6... h5 $1) (6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Qd7 $5) 7. g4 Bg6 8.
Nxe5 Qh4 9. Qf3 f6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Kg2 (11. Qg3 $6 {Perhaps surprised by his
opponent's choice of opening, White wants to simplify matters by any means.
But there is also the more ambitious} Qh7 $5 (11... Qxh3 $11 {This way Black
effortlessly gets his draw from a position of strength.} 12. Qxh3 Rxh3 13. Kg2
Rh4 14. f3 O-O-O 15. d3 Bd6 16. Rh1 Rxh1 17. Kxh1 g5 $11 {Stripunsky,
A-Gustafsson,J Philadelphia 2010}) 12. d3 (12. Qxc7 $4 Qxh3 $19) (12. f4 g5 {
[%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ge7g6,Ge8c8]}) 12... g5 13. Be3 Bd6 14. Qg2 Ne7 15. Nd2 Ng6
16. Nf3 O-O-O $15 {[%cal Gh7g8]}) 11... g5 $1 {Black does not show his hand as
far as the position of his king is concerned, and before castling he first
makes the standard moves ...g5, ...Ne7 and ...Qh7.} (11... O-O-O 12. d3 g5 {
is more precise.} (12... Bd6 $6 {This looks premature because White can now
send his knight to c4 to exchange on d6.} 13. Na3 $5 {Nb1-a3 is often a good
reply to an early ...Bd6.} g5 (13... Bxa3 14. bxa3 Ne7 15. Qg3 $14) 14. Nc4 Ne7
(14... Bf4 15. Bxf4 gxf4 16. Rh1 g5 17. e5 $14) 15. Nxd6+ cxd6 16. Qg3 $14 {
[%cal Gf2f4]}) 13. Nd2 Ne7 14. Rh1 Qh7 $1 15. Qe2 (15. Qe3 Kb8 16. Nf3 Ng6 17.
Qe1 $1 Bd6 (17... Qg8 18. b4 Bd6 19. a4) 18. b4 Qg8 19. a4 Qe6 20. b5 $36 {
Solak,D -Anton,T Legnica 2013}) 15... Ng6 16. Nf3 {The knight manoeuvre via d2
to f3 looks better than Nc3-e2. A knight that appears on f4 or h4 can now be
swapped off at any point.} Bd6 17. Be3 (17. a3 Qg8 18. b4 {[%cal Ga1b1,Ga3a4,
Gb4b5]} Rh6 $1 19. Rb1 Bf4 20. Be3 Qh7 (20... Bxe3 $6 21. fxe3) 21. a4 {
[%cal Gb4b5]} Rh8 {[%cal Gh6h3]} 22. Ng1 Bxe3 $1 23. Qxe3 (23. fxe3 $6 Ne5 24.
b5 axb5 25. axb5 cxb5 26. Rxb5 Rh4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gh4g4]}) 23... Nf4+ 24. Kf1
Nxh3 $11) 17... Qg8 $1 {[%csl Gg8][%cal Gg8a2,Gg8h7,Gh8h6]} 18. Qd2 {[%cal
Gb2b4,Gd2a5]} Qe6 $1 19. Qa5 {[%cal Ga5f5]} (19. b4 $5 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gb4b5]} Rh6
{[%cal Gd8h8]} 20. a4 {, and Black reaches an amazing, computer-like draw with}
Rdh8 21. b5 Rxh3 $1 22. Rxh3 Qxg4+ 23. Rg3 Bxg3 24. fxg3 Rh3 25. Qf2 Nf4+ $1
26. Bxf4 gxf4 27. Nh2 Rxg3+ 28. Kh1 Rh3 $1 29. Rg1 Rxh2+ $1 {, with perpetual
check.} 30. Kxh2 Qh5+ 31. Kg2 Qg4+ 32. Kf1 Qd1+ 33. Kg2 Qg4+ $11) 19... c5 20.
Kf1 {This is better.} (20. a3 $6 Kb8 21. b4 $2 Rxh3 $1 22. Rxh3 Qxg4+ 23. Rg3
Bxg3 24. fxg3 Rh8 $40 {[%cal Gh8h3,Gg6f4,Gg6h4]}) (20. Bxc5 $2 {would also
have been too dangerous:} Nf4+) 20... Kb8 21. a3 Rh6 $44 {Maze,S -Naiditsch,A
Montreal 2009}) 12. d4 $1 {This is the model plan against the pawn sacrifice.
White opens the centre (12.d4!), prophylactically secures his king (13.Rh1 and
14.Kg1) and then after appropriate preparation (15.Be3 and 16.Nd2) commences
active operations against the black king (17.b4).} (12. d3 Ne7 13. Rh1 (13. Qg3
{Black should not opt for the exchange of queens.} Qh7 $1 14. Rh1 (14. Qxc7 $4
Qxh3+) 14... O-O-O {, e.g.} 15. f4 $6 Ng6 $1 $17 {[%cal Gf8d6]}) (13. Be3 Qh7
14. Rh1 Ng6 15. Qe2 Qg8 16. Nd2 Bd6 17. Nc4 (17. Nf3 O-O-O {would transpose to
Maze-Naiditsch.}) 17... Bf4 18. a4 Qe6 19. b4 Kf7 $5 {The black king is safer
here than on c8.} (19... O-O-O 20. Rab1 $13 {[%cal Gb4b5]}) 20. Na5 $6 (20. a5
$5 {[%csl Rc4]}) 20... b6 21. Nb3 Be5 22. Rab1 (22. d4 $6 Bd6 {[%csl Rb4,Re4]
[%cal Ge6e4,Gd6b4]}) 22... Bc3 23. Nd2 $6 Nh4+ $1 24. Kg1 Qa2 $15) 13... Qh7
14. Kg1 O-O-O 15. Nc3 $6 {The intended manoeuvre Ne2-g3 is not convincing,
because on g3 the knight has few prospects. It is better going to d2 to later
reach f3 or c4.} Kb8 16. Be3 Ng6 17. Ne2 Bd6 18. Ng3 Nh4 19. Qe2 g6 $15 {
deprives the white knight of squares and prepares ...f5. White is lacking any
active possibilities.}) (12. Nc3 $6 Ne7 13. e5 $2 Ng6 $1 14. d4 (14. exf6 $2
Nf4+) 14... O-O-O {Now White not only has a problem on the queenside but also
in the centre.} 15. Ne2 (15. Qf5+ Kb8 $17 {[%csl Rh3]}) (15. exf6 gxf6 $17 16.
Be3 Qh7 17. Kg1 Nh4 18. Qe2 Re8 {[%cal Gf6f5]}) 15... Qh7 16. Kh2 Nh4 17. Qd3
Qxd3 18. cxd3 fxe5 19. dxe5 Rxd3 $17 {Turner,M -Hammer, J England 2010}) 12...
Ne7 13. Rh1 Qh7 14. Kg1 $1 O-O-O {Black more or less had to castle now. Other
moves would be weaker:} (14... Qg8 $2 15. Qb3 $1) (14... Ng6 $2 15. Qf5) 15.
Be3 $1 (15. c3 $5 Ng6 16. Qf5+ Kb8 17. b4 Qh6 {[%cal Gg6h4] Of course Black,
who is still a pawn behind, wants to attack and thus avoid the exchange of
queens.} 18. Qf3 Re8 {[%csl Re4]} 19. a4 Nh4 20. Qd3 Qh7 {[%csl Re4]} 21. f3 $5
{White has put his development on hold and pushed ahead quite unabashed with
his advance on the queenside. The position is critical for the overall
evaluation of the move 11...0-0-0.} (21. Nd2 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6f4,Gf4d2]} 22. b5
axb5 23. axb5 cxb5 24. Qxb5 $2 Rxe4 $1 $19) 21... f5 $5 {The white pawn chain
will be demolished with a few powerful moves.} 22. e5 (22. gxf5 Nxf5 $1) 22...
c5 $1 23. bxc5 ({Or Oder} 23. b5 $2 cxd4 24. cxd4 fxg4 25. Qxh7 Nxf3+ $17)
23... Bxc5 $1 24. Nd2 $2 {looks reasonable, but now White is punished for his
lack of development.} (24. dxc5 $2 Rd8 25. Qe2 fxg4 26. fxg4 Rd3 $19 {[%cal
Gd3g3]}) (24. Bxg5 $1 $11 fxg4 25. Qxh7 Nxf3+ 26. Kg2 Rxh7 27. Bf4 g5 28. Bg3
Nxd4 29. cxd4 Bxd4 30. Ra3 gxh3+ 31. Rxh3 Rxh3 32. Kxh3 Bxe5) 24... Rxe5 25.
dxc5 Rhe8 26. Rb1 {[%cal Gd3a6]} Qh6 $1 $19 {[%cal Gh6c6]}) 15... Kb8 {Also a
typical move: Black avoids the check on f5.} (15... Ng6 $6 16. Qf5+ Kb8 17. Nd2
$1 {would temporarily disrupt the coordination of his pieces.} Bd6 18. Nf3 Qh6
19. e5) 16. Nd2 Re8 $1 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ge8e4,Ge7g6,Gg6h4] Since White has
played d2-d4, the e4-pawn becomes of interest for Black.} (16... Ng6 17. Qf5 $1
